(204, 1, NULL, 4, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 20, 'Nice try — this one trips up a lot of beginners, especially if you\'ve come from another language!\n\nHere\'s the key idea: Python has many built-in types, but **`array`** is *not* one of them for everyday use. If you want a collection of items, Python gives you a **`list`** instead, written with square brackets:\n\n```python\nnumbers = [1, 2, 3]   # this is a list, not an array\n```\n\nQuick check on the others:\n- **`int`** — whole numbers like `42`\n- **`list`** — ordered collection like `[1, 2, 3]`\n- **`dict`** — key/value pairs like `{\"name\": \"Aaron\"}`\n\nThere *is* an `array` module you can `import`, but it\'s rarely used. When in doubt, reach for a **list**.\n\nTip for next time: if the option isn\'t in the \"four basic types\" (int, float, str, bool) or the common collections (list, dict, tuple, set), it\'s probably the odd one out. You\'ve got this!', '2026-07-04 10:40:04'),
(205, 1, NULL, 2, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>Nice try — this one trips up a lot of beginners! Let\'s untangle it.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <code>1name</code>, but Python has a strict rule:<strong>variable names cannot start with a digit</strong>. The moment Python sees the <code>1</code>, it thinks you\'re writing a number, then gets confused by the letters that follow. So <code>1name</code> raises a <code>SyntaxError</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Quick tour of the others:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><code>name-1</code> — the hyphen is read as the minus operator, so Python thinks you mean <em>name minus 1</em>.</li>\n  <li><code>my name</code> — spaces aren\'t allowed inside a name.</li>\n  <li><code>name_1</code> — starts with a letter, uses only letters, digits, and underscores. Valid!</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Handy rule of thumb: <strong>start with a letter or underscore, then mix in letters, digits, or underscores</strong>. Keep going, you\'ve got this!</p>', '2026-07-04 13:04:01'),
(206, 1, NULL, 3, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nailed it! <strong>3.14</strong> is a <strong>float</strong>, which is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning: in Python, any number with a decimal point is treated as a <strong>float</strong> (short for \"floating-point number\"). Whole numbers like <code>42</code> or <code>-7</code> are <strong>int</strong>, but the moment you add that <code>.</code> and a fractional part, Python switches to float. You can always confirm with<code>type()</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))  # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick pro tip: even <code>3.0</code> is a float, not an int. The decimal point is the giveaway, not whether the number \"looks\" whole. Keep this instinct sharp and you\'ll breeze through type questions.</p>', '2026-07-04 13:15:09'),
(207, 1, NULL, 4, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>A) int</strong>, but<code>int</code> is actually one of Python\'s core built-in types. It\'s the type used for whole numbers like <code>42</code> or <code>-7</code>, and you saw it right in Chapter 1 alongside <code>float</code>, <code>str</code>, and <code>bool</code>. So <code>int</code> definitely belongs in Python\'s toolbox.</p>\n\n<p>The odd one out is <strong>C) array</strong>. Python does not have a built-in <code>array</code> type for everyday use, which the chapter actually flagged in a \"watch out\" note. If you\'re coming from another language like JavaScript or Java, this feels weird because \"array\" is everywhere there. In Python, when you want an ordered collection of values, you reach for a <code>list</code> instead:</p>\n\n<pre><code>numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nnumbers.append(5)</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick recap of what IS built in from the options:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers</li>\n<li><code>list</code> — ordered, changeable collection</li>\n<li><code>dict</code> — key-value pairs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the trick with these questions is to spot the imposter, and <code>array</code> was the sneaky one here.</p>', '2026-07-04 13:42:02'),
