(215, 1, NULL, 2, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> follows every rule Python cares about for variable names.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, and why the others don\'t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B) name_1</strong> — starts with a letter, contains only letters, digits, and an underscore. Perfectly valid.</li>\n<li><strong>A) 1name</strong> — starts with a digit. Python forbids this because it would be ambiguous with number literals. If you tried it, you\'d get a <code>SyntaxError</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>C) name-1</strong> — the hyphen isn\'t allowed in identifiers. Python actually reads this as <code>name - 1</code>, a subtraction, so it thinks you\'re trying to subtract 1 from a variable called <code>name</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>D) my name</strong> — spaces aren\'t allowed. Python treats each word as a separate token, so it can\'t tell this is meant to be one name.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The quick mental checklist for naming: letters, digits, and underscores only; never start with a digit; case matters, so <code>score</code> and <code>Score</code> are two different variables. Underscores are the standard way to separate words in Python, which is why you\'ll see names like <code>user_age</code> or <code>total_score</code> everywhere.</p>', '2026-07-04 15:19:10'),
(216, 1, NULL, 3, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>bool</strong>, which stands for boolean. A bool can only ever be one of two values: <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>. It\'s the type Python uses for yes/no or on/off answers, like <code>is_student = True</code>. Since <code>3.14</code> is clearly a number, not a True/False value, bool doesn\'t fit here.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>float</strong>. Here\'s the reasoning:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>int</strong> is for whole numbers, like <code>42</code> or <code>-7</code>. No decimal point.</li>\n<li><strong>float</strong> is for numbers with a decimal point, like <code>3.14</code>, <code>0.5</code>, or <code>-2.0</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>str</strong> is for text wrapped in quotes, like <code>\"3.14\"</code>. That would be a string, not a number.</li>\n<li><strong>bool</strong> is only <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Because <code>3.14</code> has a decimal point, Python stores it as a float. You can always double-check by asking Python directly:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick rule of thumb: whole number equals int, decimal number equals float.</p>', '2026-07-04 15:19:49'),
(217, 34, NULL, 339, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 16, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your reasoning holds up when you line the numbers by place value:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  15\n+ 27\n----\n</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the <strong>2</strong> and carry the <strong>1</strong> into the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>1 + 2 + 1 (carried)= 4</code>. That gives you <strong>4</strong> tens.</li>\n<li>Put them together: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check with estimation:15 is close to 15, and 27 is close to 30, so the answer should land near 45. Your 42 sits right in that neighborhood, which is a good sign the calculation is reasonable.</p>\n\n<p>The trap options were worth noticing too. <code>40</code> would happen if you forgot to carry the 1. <code>41</code> looks like a small off-by-one slip after carrying. <code>52</code> would come from adding the carry into the wrong column. You avoided all three by handling the carry cleanly, which is the exact habit that keeps multi-digit addition reliable.</p>', '2026-07-04 15:53:22'),
