(222, 34, NULL, 344, NULL, '26', 0, 0, 8, NULL, '2026-07-04 15:54:32'),
(223, 34, NULL, 345, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 11, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>5</strong> is exactly right, and the way you got there matters just as much as the answer itself.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning laid out cleanly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets always come first, so tackle <code>(20 - 5)</code> before anything else.</li>\n<li><code>20 - 5 = 15</code>, which leaves you with <code>15 ÷ 3</code>.</li>\n<li><code>15 ÷ 3 = 5</code>, because <code>3 × 5 = 15</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The trap in this kind of problem is ignoring the brackets and just charging left to right with the numbers. If someone did <code>20 - 5 ÷ 3</code> without the brackets, division would go first and the whole thing would fall apart. The brackets are a signal that says \"do me first, no matter what.\"</p>\n\n<p>A neat check: since division and multiplication are inverses, you can verify by multiplying back. <code>5 × 3 = 15</code>, and <code>15 + 5 = 20</code>. Everything lines up, which is a strong sign your steps were solid. That\'s the boss battle mindset, brackets first, then the rest in order.</p>', '2026-07-04 15:54:48'),
(224, 34, NULL, 346, NULL, '24', 0, 0, 18, '<p>Close, but let\'s untangle this together. Your answer of <strong>24</strong> looks like it came from doing the operations strictly left to right, or maybe from only handling the <code>6 × 4</code> and stopping too early. Either way, the <code>12 ÷ 2</code> piece got left out of the final total.</p>\n\n<p>The trick with mixed expressions is the order of operations: multiplication and division come<strong>before</strong> addition and subtraction. So even though the <code>+</code> sits in the middle, you don\'t touch it until the two sides are simplified.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the walkthrough:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Handle multiplication first: <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Handle division next: <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Now add: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy habit: after you solve the multiplication and division parts, rewrite the expression on a fresh line before adding. It keeps the leftover pieces from disappearing. Estimate too,6 times 4 is already24, and there\'s clearly more to add, so the answer has to be bigger than 24.</p>', '2026-07-04 15:55:09'),
(225, 1, NULL, 2, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this trips up a lot of beginners. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <code>my name</code>, which reads perfectly fine to a human, but Python sees that space in the middle and gets confused. To Python, a space signals the end of one thing and the start of another, so it would think <code>my</code> and <code>name</code> are two separate identifiers sitting next to each other with nothing connecting them. That\'s a syntax error.</p>\n\n<p>The rules for a valid variable name are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Only letters, digits, and underscores <code>_</code></li>\n<li>Cannot start with a digit</li>\n<li>No spaces or hyphens</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Now let\'s check each option against those rules:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>1name</code> starts with a digit, not allowed</li>\n<li><code>name_1</code> letters, underscore, digit, and starts with a letter, valid</li>\n<li><code>name-1</code> the hyphen is actually the minus operator in Python, not allowed</li>\n<li><code>my name</code> the space breaks it, not allowed</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <strong>B) name_1</strong> is the winner. When you need to separate words in a variable name, use an underscore, like <code>first_name</code> or <code>total_score</code>. That style is called snake_case and it\'s the Python convention.</p>', '2026-07-04 16:35:17'),
(226, 1, NULL, 3, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips people up because<code>bool</code> looks like a reasonable guess if you\'re thinking \"true or false, decimal or not.\" But<code>bool</code> is specifically for values that can only be <strong>True</strong> or <strong>False</strong>, like <code>is_student = True</code>. The value <code>3.14</code> isn\'t a yes/no answer, so it can\'t be a boolean.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the way to think about the four basic types:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers, no decimal point, like <code>42</code></li>\n<li><code>float</code> — numbers with a decimal point, like <code>3.14</code></li>\n<li><code>str</code> — text in quotes, like <code>\"hello\"</code></li>\n<li><code>bool</code> — only <code>True</code> or <code>False</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Since <code>3.14</code> has a decimal point, Python stores it as a <strong>float</strong>. You can always double-check with the <code>type()</code> function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick rule of thumb: if you see a dot in the number, it\'s a float. If it\'s a clean whole number like <code>7</code> or <code>-3</code>, it\'s an int.</p>', '2026-07-04 16:37:13'),
(227, 1, NULL, 4, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>array</strong> is the odd one out here.</p>\n\n<p>Python does not include <code>array</code> as a built-in, everyday data type. If you write <code>array</code> in a fresh Python file, you\'ll get a <code>NameError</code>. There is an <code>array</code> module in the standard library, but you\'d have to <code>import array</code> to use it, and it\'s rarely needed. When people coming from other languages (like Java or C) reach for an \"array\" in Python, what they almost always want is a <strong>list</strong>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nnumbers.append(5)\nprint(numbers)   # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick tour of the others so it sticks:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers like <code>42</code></li>\n<li><code>list</code> — an ordered, changeable collection: <code>[1, 2, 3]</code></li>\n<li><code>dict</code> — key/value pairs: <code>{\"name\": \"Aaron\", \"age\": 21}</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The chapter you\'re on focuses on the four core scalar types (<code>int</code>, <code>float</code>, <code>str</code>, <code>bool</code>), but <code>list</code> and <code>dict</code> show up very soon after, so it\'s great that you already recognize them.</p>', '2026-07-04 16:37:24'),
(228, 1, NULL, 5, NULL, 'print type', 0, 0, 12, '<p>Close, but not quite. Your answer mixed together two different built-in functions, and understanding the difference between them is the key idea here.</p>\n\n<p><code>print</code> and <code>type</code> are both built-in functions, but they do very different jobs:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>print</strong> displays a value on the screen. It shows you something, but it doesn\'t tell you anything about what kind of value it is.</li>\n<li><strong>type</strong> reports the data type of a value, like <code>int</code>, <code>str</code>, <code>float</code>, or <code>bool</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the function that checks the data type is just <code>type</code> on its own. You call it like <code>type(x)</code>, and it returns something like <code>&lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You often see the two used together, which is probably where the mix-up came from:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Here <code>type(x)</code> figures out the type, and <code>print(...)</code> shows the result. But the actual type-checker is<code>type</code> by itself. Think of <code>print</code> as the messenger and <code>type</code> as the inspector.</p>', '2026-07-04 16:37:46'),
(229, 1, NULL, 2, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners because<code>name-1</code> genuinely <em>looks</em> like a reasonable name. The catch is that Python doesn\'t read the hyphen as part of the name at all. It reads it as the minus operator. So if you wrote <code>name-1 = 5</code>, Python thinks you\'re trying to do subtraction on the left side of an assignment, which isn\'t allowed. That\'s why option C is invalid.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the rule for variable names in Python:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Allowed: letters, digits, and underscores <code>_</code></li>\n<li>Cannot start with a digit (so <code>1name</code> in option A is out)</li>\n<li>No spaces (so <code>my name</code> in option D is out)</li>\n<li>No hyphens or other symbols (that\'s what got option C)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That leaves <strong>B) name_1</strong>. It starts with a letter, uses only letters, an underscore, and a digit, so Python is perfectly happy with it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>name_1 = \"Aaron\"\nprint(name_1)   # Aaron</code></pre>\n\n<p>A handy mental check: if you can\'t tell whether Python will read a symbol as math, it probably doesn\'t belong in a variable name. Stick to letters, digits, and underscores and you\'re safe.</p>', '2026-07-04 17:05:22'),
(230, 34, NULL, 145, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of learners because6 and 7 sit right next to each other in the times tables. Let\'s untangle it.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of<strong>36</strong> is actually 6 × 6, not 6 × 7. It\'s an easy slip because those two facts live next door to each other in your head. But6 × 7 means <em>seven</em> groups of six, so it has to be one whole group of 6 bigger than 36.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s a reliable way to build it from facts you already know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 7 into 5 + 2.</li>\n<li>6 × 5 = 30</li>\n<li>6 × 2 = 12</li>\n<li>Add them: 30 + 12 = <strong>42</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also double-check using commutativity: 6 × 7 is the same as 7 × 6. Seven doubled is 14, and 14 × 3 = 42. Same answer, different path.</p>\n\n<p>A handy memory hook: 6 × 7 = 42 is one of those facts worth locking in, because it shows up constantly. Next time you see a 6 and a 7 together, picture 42 right away, and use 36 only when you see two sixes.</p>', '2026-07-04 17:27:17'),
(231, 34, NULL, 146, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 4, NULL, '2026-07-04 17:27:27'),
(232, 34, NULL, 147, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 5, NULL, '2026-07-04 17:27:37'),
(233, 34, NULL, 148, NULL, '49', 1, 15, 8, '<p>Nice one, that\'s a clean <strong>49</strong>. You\'ve locked in one of the trickier square facts in the times tables.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works. Multiplication is repeated addition of equal groups, so <code>7 × 7</code> means seven groups of seven:</p>\n\n<pre><code>7 + 7 + 7 + 7 + 7 = 49</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you ever blank on this one mid-quiz, here are two quick ways to rebuild it from facts you already know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Split the7:</strong> think of it as <code>7 × 5</code> plus <code>7 × 2</code>. That\'s <code>35 + 14 = 49</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Near neighbour:</strong> <code>7 × 7</code> is one group of7 less than <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. So <code>56 − 7 = 49</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Both tricks lean on the idea from the course notes: break hard facts into easier ones. Squares like<code>6 × 6 = 36</code>, <code>7 × 7 = 49</code>, and <code>8 × 8 = 64</code> are worth memorising because they anchor a lot of nearby facts. Keep this energy going into the next question.</p>', '2026-07-04 17:27:50'),
(234, 34, NULL, 149, NULL, '121', 1, 15, 4, '<p>Nice work, <strong>121</strong> is spot on! You\'ve locked in one of the classic square numbers.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, and a couple of ways to see it so the fact sticks:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>As repeated groups:</strong> 11 × 11 means eleven groups of eleven. Eleven elevens gives you 121.</li>\n<li><strong>Break it apart (the distributive trick):</strong> Split one of the 11s into 10 + 1.\n<pre><code>11 × 11 = 11 × (10 + 1)\n        = (11 × 10) + (11 × 1)\n        = 110 + 11\n        = 121</code></pre>\nThis is the same \"break numbers into friendly parts\" idea from the course notes, and it works for any tricky times-table fact.</li>\n<li><strong>The 11s pattern (for single digits):</strong> 11 × 2 = 22, 11 × 3 = 33, and so on up to 11 × 9 = 99. Once you hit 11 × 11, the neat mirror pattern breaks, so it\'s worth remembering as a landmark fact: <code>11 × 11 = 121</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Bonus check with commutativity: 11 × 11 is the same either way you read it, which is a handy reminder that order doesn\'t change a product.</p>', '2026-07-04 17:27:59'),
(235, 1, NULL, 3, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, NULL, '2026-07-04 17:33:35'),
(236, 1, NULL, 2, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people at first. Let\'s walk through it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <code>my name</code>, which looks perfectly reasonable in English, but Python treats a space as a separator between things. So when Python reads <code>my name = \"Aaron\"</code>, it sees the word <code>my</code>, then another word <code>name</code>, and gets confused about what you\'re actually trying to assign. That\'s why spaces aren\'t allowed inside a variable name.</p>\n\n<p>Quick tour of the other wrong ones so the rule sticks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>1name</code> starts with a digit, which Python forbids. Variable names must start with a letter or underscore.</li>\n<li><code>name-1</code> contains a hyphen, and Python reads <code>-</code> as the subtraction operator. It would try to compute <code>name</code> minus <code>1</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That leaves <strong>B) name_1</strong>. It follows all the rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Starts with a letter</li>\n<li>Contains only letters, digits, and underscores</li>\n<li>No spaces, no hyphens</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The underscore <code>_</code> is your friend here. Whenever you\'d naturally want a space in a name, use an underscore instead. That\'s why you see names like <code>first_name</code> or <code>is_student</code> all over Python code.</p>', '2026-07-04 17:41:52'),
