(293, 34, NULL, 324, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Close, but not quite. Picking <strong>A) 5</strong> suggests you were one short. That usually happens when we count the starting number itself instead of counting the steps away from it. A classic off-by-one slip.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean way to think about <code>10 - 4</code>. Subtraction measures the distance between two numbers, so start at 10 and take 4 steps down:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>10 → 9 (that\'s 1 step)</li>\n<li>9 → 8 (2 steps)</li>\n<li>8 → 7 (3 steps)</li>\n<li>7 → 6 (4 steps)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Land on <strong>6</strong>. That\'s answer <strong>B</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A great habit from the course material: check subtraction with addition. If <code>10 - 4 = 6</code>, then <code>6 + 4</code> should give us 10 back. And it does. If you had tested5 the same way, <code>5 + 4 = 9</code>, not 10, which would have flagged the mistake before locking it in.</p>\n\n<p>Try that check on your next subtraction question and see how it feels.</p>', '2026-07-04 20:56:33'),
(294, 34, NULL, 325, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>28</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method holds up. When you line up the place values, you get:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  50\n-  22\n----</code></pre>\n\n<p>Look at the ones column first: 0 - 2. Since 0 is smaller than 2, you need to borrow. Take 1 ten from the tens column, which turns the 5 tens into 4 tens and gives the ones column 10.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones: 10 - 2 = <strong>8</strong></li>\n<li>Tens: 4 - 2 = <strong>2</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Put them together and you get 28.</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check with a mental shortcut: 22 is close to 20, and 50 - 20 = 30. Since you actually subtracted 2 more than that, the answer drops by 2, giving 28. Matches perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>And the best way to confirm any subtraction is to flip it into addition: 28 + 22 should equal 50. It does, so your answer is locked in.</p>', '2026-07-04 20:56:49'),
(295, 34, NULL, 326, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one\'s a great chance to sharpen your subtraction instincts. You picked <strong>D) 30</strong>, which is close to the right answer but a bit off. It looks like the numbers got a little mixed up along the way, maybe by thinking of 100 - 70 instead of 100 - 75.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s walk through it properly. The cleanest way is to use a friendly round number, just like the course suggests:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with<code>100 - 75</code>.</li>\n<li>Think of 75 as <strong>25 away from 100</strong>, because 75 + 25 = 100.</li>\n<li>So the difference is <code>25</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it on a number line: from 75, how far do you jump to reach 100? Jump 5 to get to 80, then 20 more to hit 100. That\'s 5 + 20 = <strong>25</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>And here\'s the built-in check the course loves: <code>difference + subtracted = starting number</code>. So <code>25 + 75 = 100</code>. It fits, which confirms <strong>A) 25</strong> is correct. Using addition to verify subtraction is a habit worth keeping.</p>', '2026-07-04 20:57:02'),
(296, 34, NULL, 327, NULL, '18', 1, 15, 9, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>30 - 12 = 18</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s what makes your answer solid. When you subtract, you\'re finding the difference between two numbers, and18 is smaller than 30, which is the quick reasonableness check the course recommends. If you\'d gotten something bigger than 30, that would be a red flag.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s walk through the borrowing logic, since 30 - 12 is a classic borrowing case:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones column: <code>0 - 2</code>. You can\'t take 2 from 0, so you borrow.</li>\n<li>Borrow 1 ten from the 3 tens. Now the tens digit becomes 2, and the ones column becomes 10.</li>\n<li>Ones: <code>10 - 2 = 8</code>.</li>\n<li>Tens: <code>2 - 1 = 1</code>.</li>\n<li>Combine: <strong>18</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And the addition check the course suggests: <code>18 + 12 = 30</code>. Matches the starting number, so the answer is confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>You\'re handling the place-value trade cleanly. Keep that borrowing habit sharp, it\'ll carry you through bigger subtraction problems too.</p>', '2026-07-04 20:57:21'),
(297, 34, NULL, 328, NULL, '111', 0, 0, 4, '<p>Nice try, and good news, you\'re really close. Let\'s untangle where<strong>111</strong> came from.</p>\n\n<p>My guess is you leaned on a mental shortcut like \"200 minus 100 is 100, so 200 minus 99 is around there,\" and something drifted by10. It happens. Let\'s walk it slowly using the friendly-number trick from the lesson.</p>\n\n<p>Round 99 up to 100 first, because 100 is easier to subtract:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>200 - 100 = 100</code></li>\n<li>But you subtracted 1 too many (100 instead of 99), so add that1 back.</li>\n<li><code>100 + 1 = 101</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the difference is <strong>101</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>You can double-check with the inverse operation, addition:</p>\n\n<pre><code>101 + 99 = 200 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you had tried <code>111 + 99</code>, you\'d get 210, which is bigger than 200, a quick signal that 111 was off.</p>\n\n<p>Key takeaway: when subtracting a number that\'s just under a round number, round up, subtract, then add back the small adjustment. And always sanity-check by adding your answer to the number you subtracted.</p>', '2026-07-04 20:57:36'),
(298, 34, NULL, 329, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 10, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean hit. <strong>6 × 7 = 42</strong> is one of those times-table facts worth locking in because it shows up everywhere.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, using the equal-groups idea from the lesson. Multiplication means repeated equal groups, so 6 × 7 is six groups of seven (or seven groups of six, thanks to commutativity). If you ever blank on it, you can rebuild it from friendlier facts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split the6 into 5 + 1: <code>5 × 7 = 35</code> and <code>1 × 7 = 7</code>, then <code>35 + 7 = 42</code>.</li>\n<li>Or double a known fact: <code>3 × 7 = 21</code>, then double it to get <code>42</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>It\'s also worth noticing why the distractors don\'t fit. <strong>36</strong> is 6 × 6, <strong>48</strong> is 6 × 8, and <strong>49</strong> is 7 × 7. They\'re all neighbors of the right answer, which is exactly the trap when you guess instead of calculating. You didn\'t fall for it, you picked the one that actually matches six sevens.</p>\n\n<p>Keep that splitting trick in your pocket for tougher facts like 8 × 7 or 9 × 6.</p>', '2026-07-04 21:07:09'),
(299, 34, NULL, 330, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean hit. <strong>8 × 9 = 72</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth locking in: 8 × 9 is one of the trickier times-table facts, so having a reliable way to reach it matters. A few methods that all land on 72:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Nearby fact:</strong> 8 × 10 = 80, then subtract one group of 8. 80 − 8 = 72.</li>\n<li><strong>Doubling:</strong> 4 × 9 = 36, then double it. 36 + 36 = 72.</li>\n<li><strong>Commutativity:</strong> 8 × 9 is the same as 9 × 8, so use whichever direction feels easier.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>It\'s also worth noticing why the other options are traps. <code>64</code> is 8 × 8, <code>81</code> is 9 × 9, and <code>63</code> is 9 × 7. They all sit next door to 72 in the times tables, which is exactly how tricky questions are built. If you ever feel unsure, estimating first helps: 8 × 9 has to be a bit less than 8 × 10 = 80, so anything far from 80 can be ruled out fast.</p>', '2026-07-04 21:07:23'),
(300, 34, NULL, 331, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean hit. <strong>12 × 5 = 60</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method behind it matters more than the memorized fact. Multiplication is repeated equal groups, so 12 × 5 means twelve groups of five, or equivalently five groups of twelve (thanks to commutativity). Both give the same product.</p>\n\n<p>A reliable way to handle this without leaning on a single memorized fact is to break the bigger number into friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 12 into <strong>10 + 2</strong></li>\n<li>10 × 5 = <strong>50</strong></li>\n<li>2 × 5 = <strong>10</strong></li>\n<li>Add them: 50 + 10 = <strong>60</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also spot a handy pattern here: any number times 5 ends in 0 or 5. Since 12 is even, the product must end in 0, which instantly rules out B (55) and D (65). And12 × 5 has to be bigger than 12 × 4 = 48, so C (50) is too small. That kind of quick sanity check is exactly the estimation habit the course recommends.</p>', '2026-07-04 21:07:37'),
(301, 34, NULL, 332, NULL, '49', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>7 × 7 = 49</strong> is one of those square facts worth locking into memory because it shows up everywhere.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works. Multiplication is repeated addition of equal groups, so 7 × 7 means seven groups of seven:</p>\n\n<pre><code>7 + 7 + 7 + 7 + 7 = 49</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you ever blank on it mid-quiz, you can rebuild it from a nearby known fact:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start from<code>7 × 5 = 35</code> (an easy one from the fives table).</li>\n<li>Add two more sevens: <code>35 + 7 = 42</code>, then <code>42 + 7 = 49</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Or split it using the tens-and-ones trick from the course:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>7 × 7 = 7 × (5 + 2)</code></li>\n<li><code>= (7 × 5) + (7 × 2)</code></li>\n<li><code>= 35 + 14 = 49</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And remember commutativity: 7 × 7 is a square, so both factors are the same, but for other facts like 8 × 6 and 6 × 8, you only need to learn it once. Keep that momentum going.</p>', '2026-07-04 21:07:50'),
(302, 34, NULL, 333, NULL, '121', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>11 × 11 = 121</strong> is one of those facts worth locking in because the 11s table has such a satisfying pattern.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up, using the break-apart strategy from the material:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 11 into <code>10 + 1</code>.</li>\n<li>Then <code>11 × 11</code> becomes <code>11 × (10 + 1)</code>.</li>\n<li>That\'s <code>11 × 10 = 110</code> and <code>11 × 1 = 11</code>.</li>\n<li>Add them: <code>110 + 11 = 121</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also check it by thinking of multiplication as equal groups: eleven groups of eleven. Estimate first, eleven is close to ten, and <code>10 × 10 = 100</code>, so the real answer should be a bit more than 100. 121 sits right in that reasonable zone, which is a good sanity check.</p>\n\n<p>One handy pattern for the 11s up to <code>11 × 9</code>: the digit just doubles, like <code>11 × 4 = 44</code>. Past that, the pattern shifts, which is why <code>11 × 11</code> is worth remembering directly. You\'re building real fluency here.</p>', '2026-07-04 21:08:05'),
(303, 25, NULL, 237, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 9, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of learners because6 × 7 sits in a tricky corner of the times tables. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You chose <strong>48</strong>, which is actually 6 × 8 or 8 × 6. So your thinking was close, but one of the factors got bumped up by one group. That\'s a super common slip.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning for<strong>6 × 7</strong>, which means six groups of seven (or seven groups of six, since multiplication is commutative):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split it into friendly parts: <code>6 × 7 = 5 × 7 + 1 × 7</code></li>\n<li><code>5 × 7 = 35</code></li>\n<li><code>35 + 7 = 42</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Or use doubles if that feels easier: <code>3 × 7 = 21</code>, then double it: <code>21 + 21 = 42</code>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy way to lock this one in: remember the little sequence <strong>5, 6, 7, 8</strong> — because <code>56 = 7 × 8</code> and <code>42 = 6 × 7</code>. Whenever you see 6 and 7 together, picture 42. Try building the answer from a known fact next time instead of estimating, and these tricky middle-table facts get much steadier.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:01:43'),
(304, 25, NULL, 238, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 8, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>81</strong>, which is actually <code>9 × 9</code>. That\'s a super common mix-up because8 and 9 sit right next to each other in the times tables, and81 is a familiar-looking square number. So your brain was in the right neighborhood, just one house off.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>72</strong>. Here\'s a reliable way to get there:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Think of <code>8 × 9</code> as eight groups of nine.</li>\n  <li>Split it into easier facts: <code>8 × 10= 80</code>, then subtract one group of 8 → <code>80 − 8 = 72</code>.</li>\n  <li>Or use doubles: <code>4 × 9 = 36</code>, then double it → <code>36 + 36 = 72</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check: multiplication is commutative, so <code>8 × 9 = 9 × 8</code>. If you know <code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, you know both. And to catch the 81 trap next time, ask yourself: am I multiplying by 8 or by 9? That tiny pause makes a big difference.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:02:27'),
(305, 25, NULL, 239, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>Close, but not quite. Picking <strong>55</strong> suggests you were thinking of 11 × 5 = 55, which is one group of 5 short. With 12 × 5, we need <em>twelve</em> groups of five, not eleven.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s a clean way to see it using the \"break numbers into friendly parts\" strategy from the course:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 12 into <strong>10 + 2</strong>.</li>\n<li>10 × 5 = <strong>50</strong></li>\n<li>2 × 5 = <strong>10</strong></li>\n<li>Add them: 50 + 10 = <strong>60</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the correct answer is <strong>A) 60</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Another quick check uses commutativity:12 × 5 is the same as 5 × 12. Counting by fives twelve times gives 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55, <strong>60</strong>. Notice 55 is only the eleventh step, one short of the answer.</p>\n\n<p>A handy pattern for the×5 table: any even number times 5 ends in 0, and any odd number times 5 ends in 5. Since 12 is even, the answer must end in 0, which rules out 55 and 65 straight away.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:02:49');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(306, 25, NULL, 240, NULL, '45', 0, 0, 13, '<p>No worries, 45 is really close, and I can see what likely happened. You may have slipped into the 5 times table for a moment (since 9 × 5 = 45), or you were thinking of 7 × 6 = 42 and added one7 but only counted up by3. Either way, the reasoning tripped, not you.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s rebuild <code>7 × 7</code> using the method from the lesson, breaking a tricky fact into friendlier ones:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Think of 7 × 7 as <strong>7 groups of 7</strong>.</li>\n<li>Split it:5 × 7 + 2 × 7.</li>\n<li>5 × 7 = 35.</li>\n<li>2 × 7 = 14.</li>\n<li>Add them: 35 + 14 = <strong>49</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way to lock it in: doubles. 7 × 7 is a \"square\" fact, so imagine a 7 by 7 grid. Two rows of 7 make 14, four rows make 28, six rows make 42, and one more row of 7 gets you to 49.</p>\n\n<p>Quick check with estimation: 7 is close to 10, and 7 × 10 = 70, so 7 × 7 should be a bit less than 70. That makes 49 feel just right, while 45 would mean 7 groups averaging under6.5 each. Squares like this one (49) are worth memorizing since they show up everywhere.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:03:17'),
(307, 25, NULL, 241, NULL, '101', 0, 0, 14, '<p>Close, but not quite. Your answer of <strong>101</strong> looks like it came from adding rather than multiplying. If you did11 + 11, you would get 22, so101 suggests the digits got mixed up somewhere along the way. Multiplication grows much faster than addition, so 11 × 11 has to be significantly bigger than 22.</p>\n\n<p>Here is a clean way to think about <code>11 × 11</code> using the break-apart strategy from the course materials:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split the second 11 into <strong>10 + 1</strong>.</li>\n<li>Multiply each part: <code>11 × 10 = 110</code> and <code>11 × 1 = 11</code>.</li>\n<li>Add the two results: <code>110 + 11 = 121</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the product is <strong>121</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy pattern for the 11 times table up to 11 × 9: just write the digit twice. 11 × 3 = 33, 11 × 7 = 77, and so on. Once you hit 11 × 10, it becomes 110, and 11 × 11 is just one more group of 11 on top of that. Estimating first (11 is close to 10, and 10 × 10 = 100) also tells you the answer must be a bit above 100, which rules out something like 22.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:03:44'),
(308, 25, NULL, 375, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> is a perfectly valid Python variable name.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works and the others don\'t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B) <code>name_1</code></strong> — starts with a letter, contains only letters, digits, and an underscore. All good.</li>\n<li><strong>A) <code>1name</code></strong> — starts with a digit, which Python doesn\'t allow. Variable names must begin with a letter or underscore.</li>\n<li><strong>C) <code>name-1</code></strong> — the hyphen isn\'t a valid character in an identifier. Python actually reads this as <code>name - 1</code>, a subtraction.</li>\n<li><strong>D) <code>my name</code></strong> — spaces aren\'t allowed. Python would see two separate tokens and throw a syntax error.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The rule of thumb: a variable name can only contain letters, digits, and underscores, and it can\'t start with a digit. Underscores are your friend when you want a name made of multiple words, like <code>user_age</code> or <code>total_score</code>. This style is called snake_case and it\'s the Python convention.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check, which of these do you think is valid: <code>_score</code>, <code>2players</code>, or <code>player.name</code>?</p>', '2026-07-04 23:27:25'),
(309, 25, NULL, 376, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice one, spot on.<strong>3.14</strong> is a <code>float</code>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the why: Python looks at the literal you type and picks a type automatically. The moment it sees a decimal point, it treats the number as a floating-point value, meaning a number that can have a fractional part.</p>\n\n<p>Quick comparison so the distinction sticks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>3</code> is an <code>int</code> — a whole number, no decimal point.</li>\n<li><code>3.14</code> is a <code>float</code> — has a decimal point, even<code>3.0</code> counts.</li>\n<li><code>\"3.14\"</code> is a <code>str</code> — the quotes turn it into text, not a number.</li>\n<li><code>True</code> / <code>False</code> are <code>bool</code> — yes/no values.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always double-check with the built-in <code>type()</code> function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>One tiny thing worth remembering: even <code>1.0</code> is a float, not an int. The decimal point is what flips the type, not whether there\'s anything meaningful after it.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:27:41'),
(310, 25, NULL, 377, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right! <strong>array</strong> is the odd one out.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning: Python does have a module called <code>array</code>, but it\'s not a built-in everyday data type you can just use out of the box. You\'d have to import it explicitly with <code>from array import array</code>, and even then it\'s rarely used in beginner code. As the course notes point out, when people coming from other languages reach for an \"array\" in Python, what they almost always want is a <strong>list</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The other three are all core, always-available types:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers like <code>42</code></li>\n<li><code>list</code> — an ordered, changeable collection like <code>[1, 2, 3]</code></li>\n<li><code>dict</code> — key-value pairs like <code>{\"name\": \"Aaron\"}</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick way to check whether something is truly built-in: try using it without any import. If Python knows what it is immediately, it\'s built-in.</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = [1, 2, 3]\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'list\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>You\'ve got the instinct to spot the \"outsider\" in a list — that pattern-matching will help you a lot as concepts stack up.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:27:54'),
(311, 25, NULL, 378, NULL, 'type', 1, 15, 9, '<p>Nice one, you nailed it. <code>type()</code> is exactly the built-in you reach for when you want Python to tell you what kind of value a variable holds.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works the way it does. Python is dynamically typed, meaning you don\'t declare a type when you create a variable, Python figures it out from the value you assign. That\'s convenient, but it also means sometimes you need to ask, \"wait, what type is this actually?\" That\'s where <code>type()</code> comes in.</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\n\nname = \"Aaron\"\nprint(type(name))     # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\n\nis_ready = True\nprint(type(is_ready)) # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Notice the output is <code>&lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code>, not just <code>float</code>. That\'s because in Python every type is actually a class under the hood, even the basic ones like <code>int</code> and <code>str</code>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy debugging habit: when a program misbehaves and you suspect a value isn\'t what you think it is (a common one is a number arriving as a string like <code>\"5\"</code> instead of <code>5</code>), drop in a quick <code>print(type(x))</code> to check.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:28:14'),
(312, 25, NULL, 379, NULL, 'none', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, you\'ve got the concept down. <strong>None</strong> is exactly how Python represents \"no value\" or \"nothing at all.\"</p>\n\n<p>Quick heads-up though: the platform accepted <code>none</code>, but in real Python code that would actually be a bug. Python is case-sensitive, and the built-in keyword is capitalized: <code>None</code> (with a big N). If you type <code>none</code> in an editor, Python will treat it as a variable name it\'s never heard of and throw a <code>NameError</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the difference in action:</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None      # works — no value assigned yet\nprint(winner)      # None\n\nloser = none       # NameError: name \'none\' is not defined\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Two other capitalized values worth remembering for the same reason:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>True</code> — not <code>true</code></li>\n<li><code>False</code> — not <code>false</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You\'ll usually see <code>None</code> used as a placeholder when a value hasn\'t been decided yet, or as the default return value of a function that doesn\'t explicitly return anything. Keep an eye on that capital N and you\'re golden.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:28:29'),
(313, 25, NULL, 375, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> follows every rule Python has for naming variables, so the interpreter is perfectly happy with it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works and why the others don\'t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A) <code>1name</code></strong> starts with a digit. Python variable names have to begin with a letter or an underscore, so this one gets rejected before it even gets read as a name.</li>\n<li><strong>C) <code>name-1</code></strong> contains a hyphen. Python reads the<code>-</code> as the subtraction operator, so it thinks you\'re trying to do <code>name minus 1</code>, not naming a variable.</li>\n<li><strong>D) <code>my name</code></strong> has a space in it. Spaces separate tokens in Python, so it looks like two things instead of one identifier.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The quick rule to remember: variable names can only contain <strong>letters, digits, and underscores</strong>, and they <strong>can\'t start with a digit</strong>. That\'s why underscores are so common in Python, they let you glue words together like <code>user_age</code> or <code>total_score</code> where other languages might use spaces or dashes. Also worth remembering, names are case-sensitive, so <code>name_1</code> and <code>Name_1</code> would be two different variables.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:32:04'),
(314, 25, NULL, 376, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>3.14</code> is a <strong>float</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning behind it. In Python, any number written with a decimal point is treated as a floating-point number, which is just a fancy name for a number that can have a fractional part. The moment you write that dot, Python decides \"this isn\'t a whole number, so it can\'t be an <code>int</code>\" and stores it as a <code>float</code> instead.</p>\n\n<p>Quick way to see it for yourself:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Compare that with the other options:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> is for whole numbers only, like <code>3</code> or <code>-42</code>. No decimal point.</li>\n<li><code>str</code> is for text, and would need quotes: <code>\"3.14\"</code> is a string, not a number.</li>\n<li><code>bool</code> only has two possible values, <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A small gotcha to file away: even <code>3.0</code> is a float, not an int. It\'s the decimal point that decides the type, not whether the fractional part happens to be zero.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:32:19'),
(315, 25, NULL, 377, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work spotting that one. <strong>array</strong> is the odd one out, and you nailed why it\'s a trap answer.</p>\n\n<p>Python does have a module called <code>array</code> in its standard library, but you have to import it explicitly with <code>import array</code>, and it\'s rarely used in everyday code. It\'s not a built-in type sitting thereready to go like <code>int</code> or <code>str</code>. Coming from languages like Java or C, people often expect <code>array</code> to be a core type in Python, but it just isn\'t.</p>\n\n<p>The three real built-ins in your options are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers like <code>42</code></li>\n<li><code>list</code> — ordered collections like <code>[1, 2, 3]</code></li>\n<li><code>dict</code> — key-value pairs like <code>{\"name\": \"Aaron\"}</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>When Python beginners want an \"array,\" what they almost always want is a <code>list</code>. Lists are flexible, can hold mixed types, and grow or shrink as needed:</p>\n\n<pre><code>scores = [90, 85, 72]\nscores.append(100)\nprint(scores)  # [90, 85, 72, 100]</code></pre>\n\n<p>Remembering that distinction will save you from a lot of confused Google searches later.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:32:31'),
(316, 25, NULL, 378, NULL, 'type', 1, 15, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>type</code> is the built-in you reach for whenever you want Python to tell you what kind of value something is.</p>\n\n<p>The way it works: you pass any value or variable into it, and it hands back the class the value belongs to. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\nprint(type(\"hello\"))  # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\nprint(type(42))       # &lt;class \'int\'&gt;\nprint(type(True))     # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth locking in while this is fresh:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>type()</code> is a function, so it always needs parentheses around the thing you\'re checking. Writing <code>type x</code> would be a syntax error.</li>\n<li>The output looks like <code>&lt;class \'int\'&gt;</code> rather than just <code>int</code>. That\'s because in Python, every type is itself a class.</li>\n<li>It\'s a handy debugging tool. If your code is misbehaving, printing <code>type(some_var)</code> often reveals that a value you thought was an <code>int</code> is actually a <code>str</code>, especially when reading input from a user.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You\'ve got the foundation for spotting type-related bugs before they bite you.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:32:50'),
(317, 25, NULL, 379, NULL, 'none', 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, you clearly know the concept. Python\'s placeholder for \"no value\" is indeed <code>None</code>, and the quiz accepted your answer. One small thing worth flagging though: in real Python code, capitalization matters. <code>None</code> with a capital N is the correct spelling, and <code>none</code> in lowercase would give you a <strong>NameError</strong> because Python would try to look it up as a variable that doesn\'t exist.</p>\n\n<p>So while your answer got credit here, keep this in mind when you\'re typing actual code:</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None      # works, this is the special value\nloser = none       # NameError: name \'none\' is not defined</code></pre>\n\n<p>Why does <code>None</code> exist at all? It\'s a way to say \"this variable exists, but there\'s nothing meaningful in it yet.\" You\'ll see it used a lot as a starting placeholder:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>A function that doesn\'t explicitly <code>return</code> anything gives back <code>None</code></li>\n<li>Optional function parameters often default to <code>None</code></li>\n<li>You can check for it with <code>if x is None:</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>It\'s different from <code>0</code>, <code>False</code>, or an empty string, those are actual values. <code>None</code> means the absence of a value entirely.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:33:02'),
(318, 25, NULL, 375, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> follows every Python naming rule.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works and the others don\'t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A) <code>1name</code></strong> starts with a digit. Python forbids this because it needs to tell variable names apart from numbers at a glance. <code>1name</code> looks too much like the number<code>1</code> followed by something.</li>\n<li><strong>B) <code>name_1</code></strong> is valid. It starts with a letter, and the rest is just letters, digits, and an underscore, which are the only characters allowed.</li>\n<li><strong>C) <code>name-1</code></strong> contains a hyphen. Python reads the hyphen as the minus operator, so it would try to compute <code>name - 1</code> instead of treating it as one name.</li>\n<li><strong>D) <code>my name</code></strong> has a space. Python uses spaces to separate tokens, so it would see two things (<code>my</code> and <code>name</code>) rather than one variable.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy rule of thumb: a variable name must start with a letter or underscore, then contain only letters, digits, or underscores. That\'s why <code>snake_case</code> is the go-to style in Python. Try declaring one yourself:</p>\n\n<pre><code>user_age = 21\nprint(user_age)</code></pre>', '2026-07-04 23:44:56'),
(319, 25, NULL, 376, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice one, you nailed it.<strong>3.14</strong> is a <code>float</code>, and spotting that instantly is exactly the instinct you want.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning underneath your answer. Python looks at the literal you wrote and picks a type automatically. The dot in<code>3.14</code> is the giveaway — the presence of a decimal point tells Python \"this is a floating-point number,\" so it stores it as a <code>float</code>. If you had written <code>3</code> with no dot, it would have been an <code>int</code> instead.</p>\n\n<p>Quick side-by-side so the distinction sticks:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers like <code>42</code>, <code>0</code>, <code>-7</code></li>\n<li><code>float</code> — numbers with a decimal point like <code>3.14</code>, <code>0.5</code>, even <code>2.0</code></li>\n<li><code>str</code> — text in quotes like <code>\"3.14\"</code> (that one is a string, not a number)</li>\n<li><code>bool</code> — only <code>True</code> or <code>False</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always double-check in code:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Notice that even <code>2.0</code> is a <code>float</code>, not an <code>int</code> — the decimal point is what matters, not the value.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:45:12'),
(320, 25, NULL, 377, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>array</strong> is the odd one out here.</p>\n\n<p>Python doesn\'t have a built-in <code>array</code> type for everyday use. If you want to store a collection of values, the go-to option is a <strong>list</strong>, which is built right into the language, no imports needed:</p>\n\n<pre><code>numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nprint(numbers[0])   # 1</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick note on the others so you know why they\'re valid:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> is a built-in numeric type for whole numbers like <code>42</code>.</li>\n<li><code>list</code> is a built-in ordered, changeable collection like <code>[1, 2, 3]</code>.</li>\n<li><code>dict</code> is a built-in key-value store like <code>{\"name\": \"Aaron\", \"age\": 21}</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>There is technically an <code>array</code> module in Python\'s standard library, and NumPy has its own array type, but you have to <code>import</code> those. They\'re not built-in like <code>list</code> is. For a beginner, the rule of thumb is simple: when you\'d reach for an \"array\" in another language, reach for a <strong>list</strong> in Python.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:45:40'),
(321, 25, NULL, 378, NULL, 'type', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice one, that\'s exactly right. <code>type()</code> is the built-in you reach for whenever you want Python to tell you what kind of value a variable is holding.</p>\n\n<p>The neat thing about Python is that you never declare types up front, the interpreter figures them out from the value you assign. So <code>type()</code> is your window into what Python decided:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\n\nname = \"Aaron\"\nprint(type(name))     # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\n\nis_ready = True\nprint(type(is_ready)) # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth locking in while this is fresh:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>type()</code> is a function, so it needs the parentheses when you call it, like <code>type(x)</code>.</li>\n<li>The four basic types you\'ll see over and over are <strong>int</strong>, <strong>float</strong>, <strong>str</strong>, and <strong>bool</strong>.</li>\n<li>Watch out for surprises,<code>type(3)</code> gives <code>int</code> but <code>type(3.0)</code> gives <code>float</code>, even though the values look almost the same.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This little function becomes really handy later when a bug turns out to be \"oh, that was a string, not a number.\"</p>', '2026-07-04 23:45:59'),
(322, 25, NULL, 379, NULL, 'none', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, you clearly know the concept. <strong>None</strong> is exactly Python\'s way of saying \"no value here yet.\" The quiz accepted your answer, but there\'s one small detail worth locking in now so it doesn\'t trip you up later.</p>\n\n<p>In real Python code, capitalization matters. The keyword is <code>None</code> with a capital N. Lowercase <code>none</code> will actually raise a <code>NameError</code> because Python thinks you\'re referring to a variable called <code>none</code> that was never defined.</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None      # works, winner now holds \"nothing\"\nloser = none       # NameError: name \'none\' is not defined</code></pre>\n\n<p>The same rule applies to Python\'s two boolean values, <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>. All three of these built-in constants start with a capital letter. That\'s different from some other languages (like JavaScript\'s <code>null</code> or <code>true</code>), so it\'s a common early stumble.</p>\n\n<p>You\'ll typically see <code>None</code> used as a placeholder before a real value is known, or as the default return from a function that doesn\'t explicitly <code>return</code> anything. Great instinct on the concept, just remember the capital N when you type it into an editor.</p>', '2026-07-04 23:46:15'),
(357, 34, NULL, 155, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 7, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method holds up so well on a problem like this. When you add two-digit numbers, you\'re really adding by place value, one column at a time:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones column:</strong> <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. That\'s more than 9, so you write down the <code>2</code> and carry <code>1</code> into the tens column.</li>\n<li><strong>Tens column:</strong> <code>1 + 2 = 3</code>, plus the carried <code>1</code> makes <code>4</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Result:</strong> 4 tens and 2 ones, which is <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also works nicely here. Round to friendly numbers: <code>15</code> is close to <code>15</code>, and <code>27</code> is close to <code>30</code>. So <code>15 + 30= 45</code>, then subtract the <code>3</code> you added, and you land on <code>42</code>. That matches, so the answer is reasonable.</p>\n\n<p>The trap options were interesting. <code>40</code> and <code>41</code> would happen if someone forgot the carried<code>1</code>, and <code>52</code> would come from carrying twice by mistake. You handled the carry correctly, which is the key skill for the whole addition level.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:28:48'),
(358, 34, NULL, 156, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve. 🎉 You picked <strong>45</strong>, which is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method holds up. When you subtract <code>84 - 39</code>, the ones column trips people up because <code>4 - 9</code> can\'t be done directly, so you borrow.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones column: <code>4 - 9</code> needs borrowing. Take1 ten from the 8, so 84 becomes 7 tens and 14 ones.</li>\n<li>Now <code>14 - 9 = 5</code>.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>7 - 3 = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Answer: <strong>45</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also check it with the shortcut from the course: 39 is close to 40, so think<code>84 - 40 = 44</code>, then add back 1 (because you subtracted one too many) to get <strong>45</strong>. Both roads lead to the same place.</p>\n\n<p>And the quickest sanity check is addition, since subtraction and addition are inverses: <code>45 + 39 = 84</code>. ✅ That confirms the difference is correct. Keep that borrowing habit sharp, it\'ll carry you straight into the boss battle mix.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:29:01'),
(359, 34, NULL, 157, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, 78 is spot on.<strong>13 × 6 = 78</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is by breaking the harder number into friendly parts, just like the Level 3 examples.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the split-and-multiply approach:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Break 13 into <strong>10 + 3</strong></li>\n<li>Multiply each part by 6: <code>10 × 6 = 60</code> and <code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Add the pieces back together: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check with a quick estimate. 13 is a little more than 10, and 10 × 6 = 60, so the answer should be somewhat above 60 but well below 100. That instantly rules out anything wildly off.</p>\n\n<p>Why the other options were tempting traps:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>76</strong> and <strong>72</strong> are close neighbours, the kind of near-miss you get from a shaky times-table recall.</li>\n<li><strong>84</strong> is 14 × 6, one group of6 too many.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Carry this splitting trick into the Boss Battle. It works beautifully when a multiplication step sneaks into a mixed expression.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:29:12'),
(360, 34, NULL, 158, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one\'s a great chance to lock in a division trick. You picked <strong>D) 14</strong>, which would mean 8 × 14 groups of 8 make 96. Let\'s test that: 8 × 14 = 8 × 10 + 8 × 4 = 80 + 32 =<strong>112</strong>. That\'s already past 96, so 14 is too many groups.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reliable way to handle <code>96 ÷ 8</code>: turn it into a multiplication question. Ask yourself, \"8 times what gives me 96?\"</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with a friendly fact: 8 × 10 = 80.</li>\n<li>You still need to reach 96, so how much more? 96 − 80 = 16.</li>\n<li>How many 8s fit in 16? 8 × 2 = 16.</li>\n<li>Add the groups: 10 + 2 = <strong>12</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So 96 ÷ 8 = <strong>12</strong>, which matches option A. Quick check using the inverse operation: 8 × 12 = 96. ✅</p>\n\n<p>The big idea: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Whenever a division fact feels tricky, break the total into a round chunk you know (like 8 × 10) and handle the leftover separately.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:29:37'),
(361, 34, NULL, 159, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 25, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of learners, and looking at your blank answer, it seems like you might have hesitated on where to start. That\'s actually the most important clue in this whole problem, so let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>The expression is <code>7 × 8 - 6</code>. When you see multiplication and subtraction in the same line, order of operations tells you to handle multiplication <strong>before</strong> subtraction, even though subtraction appears further right.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>First, multiply: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>56 - 6</code></li>\n<li>Then subtract: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the answer is <strong>A) 50</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Notice why the other options are tempting traps:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>56</strong> is what you get if you stop after multiplying and forget the subtraction.</li>\n<li><strong>48</strong> comes from doing <code>8 - 6 = 2</code> first, then <code>7 × 2</code>, which reverses the correct order.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The habit to build: underline the multiplication sign first, solve that chunk, then rewrite the shorter expression before finishing. Rewriting keeps you from losing your place.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:30:14'),
(362, 34, NULL, 160, NULL, '36', 0, 0, 14, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, and your answer actually tells me exactly what happened. You got <strong>36</strong>, which is what you get if you work strictly left to right: 9 + 9 = 18, then 18 × 2 = 36. That feels natural, but order of operations has other plans.</p>\n\n<p>The rule is that <strong>multiplication happens before addition</strong>, even when the addition appears first in the expression. So you have to hunt down the × symbol and deal with it before touching the +.</p>\n\n<p>Here is the correct path:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Spot the multiplication: <code>9 × 2= 18</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what is left: <code>9 + 18</code></li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy trick from the course: before you calculate anything, underline the operation symbols and circle any multiplication or division. That visual cue reminds you to jump to those first, no matter where they sit in the line. Left-to-right only applies <em>within</em> the same priority level, like when you have two multiplications back to back.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:30:45'),
(363, 34, NULL, 161, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 15, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>5</strong> is the answer, and the way you handled the brackets shows you\'re following the order of operations properly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your reasoning fits the method perfectly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets always come first. So <code>(20 - 5)</code> gets solved before anything else: <code>20 - 5 = 15</code>.</li>\n<li>The expression then becomes <code>15 ÷ 3</code>.</li>\n<li>Division gives you <code>15 ÷ 3 = 5</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick check using the inverse operation confirms it: <code>5 × 3 = 15</code>, which matches what was inside the brackets. That\'s the multiplication-division link from Level 4 in action.</p>\n\n<p>One thing worth noticing: if you had ignored the brackets and just worked left to right, you\'d have done <code>20 - 5 ÷ 3</code>, which would mean dividing <code>5 ÷ 3</code> first, and the whole thing would fall apart. The brackets are what forced the subtraction to happen first, and you caught that. That\'s the exact skill the Boss Battle is testing.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:31:10'),
(364, 34, NULL, 162, NULL, '30', 1, 20, 9, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. 30 is exactly right, and the fact that you landed on it means you handled the order of operations correctly rather than just charging through left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. The expression has two operations that outrank addition: multiplication and division. Both need to happen before the plus sign gets its turn.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Multiplication first: <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Division next: <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Now the expression is<code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Add last: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick trap to notice, if someone worked strictly left to right, they\'d get <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, then <code>24 + 12 = 36</code>, then <code>36 ÷ 2 = 18</code>. Totally wrong answer, and it\'s a super common slip. You avoided it.</p>\n\n<p>The habit that keeps paying off here is scanning the whole expression before touching anything. Spot the <strong>×</strong> and <strong>÷</strong> first, resolve those, then bring the<strong>+</strong> and <strong>−</strong> in at the end. You\'ve got the routine down.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:31:34'),
(365, 34, NULL, 312, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on! <strong>True</strong> is a <code>bool</code>, short for boolean, which is Python\'s type for yes/no or on/off values. There are only two possible booleans: <code>True</code> and <code>False</code> (note the capital letters, Python is picky about that).</p>\n\n<p>Booleans show up all over the place, especially in control flow. Every time you write an <code>if</code> statement, Python is evaluating a condition down to either <code>True</code> or <code>False</code> to decide whether to run the block:</p>\n\n<pre><code>is_student = True\nif is_student:\n    print(\"Welcome!\")</code></pre>\n\n<p>One fun quirk worth knowing: under the hood, <code>bool</code> is actually a subclass of <code>int</code> in Python. That means <code>True</code> behaves like <code>1</code> and <code>False</code> like <code>0</code> in arithmetic:</p>\n\n<pre><code>print(True + True)   # 2\nprint(False * 10)    # 0</code></pre>\n\n<p>You won\'t need that trick often, but it can be handy for counting how many conditions are true in a list. For the quiz though, the clean answer is exactly what you picked: <code>bool</code>.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:40:30'),
(366, 34, NULL, 313, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nailed it! <strong>elif</strong> is exactly right, and this one trips up a lot of people coming from other languages, so give yourself credit.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the other options are wrong in Python specifically:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>elseif</code> is what PHP uses</li>\n<li><code>else if</code> (two words) is what JavaScript, C, and Java use</li>\n<li><code>elsif</code> is what Ruby and Perl use</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Python\'s designers went with <code>elif</code> to keep things short and to make the indentation line up cleanly. Since Python uses whitespace to define blocks, a single keyword avoids the awkwardness of nesting a fresh <code>if</code> inside every <code>else</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the shape you\'ll use constantly:</p>\n\n<pre><code>score = 75\nif score >= 90:\n    grade = \"A\"\nelif score >= 75:\n    grade = \"B\"\nelif score >= 60:\n    grade = \"C\"\nelse:\n    grade = \"F\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>Python checks each condition top to bottom and runs the first block whose condition is <code>True</code>, then skips the rest. So order matters. If you flipped <code>&gt;= 60</code> above <code>&gt;= 90</code>, everyone would get a C. Nice work spotting the Python-flavored answer.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:40:42'),
(367, 34, NULL, 314, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice one, that\'s exactly right. <strong>while</strong> is Python\'s condition-controlled loop, it keeps running as long as the condition evaluates to true and stops the moment it becomes false.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the mental model: a <code>while</code> loop checks its condition <em>before</em> each iteration. If it\'s true, run the body. Then check again. Repeat until it\'s false.</p>\n\n<pre><code>count = 0\nwhile count &lt; 3:\n    print(\"hello\")\n    count += 1</code></pre>\n\n<p>That prints \"hello\" three times, then stops because <code>count</code> becomes 3 and <code>count &lt; 3</code> is no longer true.</p>\n\n<p>Quick notes on the other options:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>for</strong> exists in Python, but it iterates over a sequence (a list, a range, a string), it doesn\'t watch a condition.</li>\n<li><strong>repeat</strong> and <strong>foreach</strong> aren\'t Python keywords at all. You may have seen them in other languages.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>One thing to keep in your back pocket: if the variable in a <code>while</code> condition never changes inside the loop, you get an infinite loop. Always make sure something in the body moves the condition toward false.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:40:55'),
(368, 34, NULL, 315, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>def</strong> is the keyword Python uses to define a function.</p>\n\n<p>The name is short for \"define,\" which is probably why <code>define</code> feels tempting as an answer, but Python\'s designers went with the shorter version. The other options are traps from other languages or just plausible-sounding words: some languages use <code>function</code> (like JavaScript) or <code>func</code> (like Go and Swift), but Python is not one of them.</p>\n\n<p>The full pattern looks like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def greet(name):\n    return f\"Hello, {name}!\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>A few things worth noticing in that one line:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>def</code> starts the definition</li>\n<li><code>greet</code> is the function\'s name, following the same rules as variable names</li>\n<li><code>(name)</code> lists the parameters the function accepts</li>\n<li>The colon <code>:</code> at the end is required, and the body must be indented (4 spaces is standard)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Once defined, you call it with <code>greet(\"Aaron\")</code>. That separation between defining and calling is what makes functions reusable, you write the logic once and run it as many times as you want.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:41:13'),
(369, 34, NULL, 316, NULL, 'stop', 0, 0, 13, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners because <code>stop</code> feels like the most natural English word for the job. But Python actually reserves a specific keyword for it: <strong>break</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why <code>stop</code> doesn\'t work: Python only recognizes a fixed set of built-in keywords, and <code>stop</code> isn\'t one of them. If you tried to run it, Python would just treat <code>stop</code> as an undefined variable name and raise a <code>NameError</code>, not exit the loop.</p>\n\n<p>The keyword you want is <code>break</code>. It immediately exits the nearest enclosing loop, skipping any remaining iterations. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>for i in range(10):\n    if i == 5:\n        break\n    print(i)\n# prints 0 1 2 3 4, then stops</code></pre>\n\n<p>The moment <code>i</code> hits 5, <code>break</code> fires and the loop is done, even though<code>range(10)</code> had more numbers to go.</p>\n\n<p>Its cousin is <code>continue</code>, which doesn\'t stop the loop but skips to the next iteration. Handy to keep them paired in your head: <strong>break</strong> exits, <strong>continue</strong> skips.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:41:36'),
(370, 34, NULL, 317, NULL, 'f', 1, 20, 4, '<p>Nice one, you nailed it. The lowercase <code>f</code> is exactly what goes right before the opening quote to turn a normal string into an f-string.</p>\n\n<p>The magic is that once you prefix a string with <code>f</code>, Python looks inside the quotes for anything wrapped in curly braces <code>{ }</code> and replaces it with the actual value of that variable or expression. Without the <code>f</code>, the braces are just literal characters.</p>\n\n<pre><code>name = \"Aaron\"\nage = 21\nprint(f\"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.\")\n# My name is Aaron and I am 21 years old.</code></pre>\n\n<p>A few things worth tucking away:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <code>f</code> is case-insensitive — <code>F\"...\"</code> works too, but lowercase is the convention.</li>\n<li>You can put expressions inside the braces, not just variables: <code>f\"Next year I\'ll be {age + 1}\"</code>.</li>\n<li>Forgetting the <code>f</code> is a super common bug. <code>\"Hello, {name}\"</code> will literally print the braces instead of the value.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You\'re through the boss battle content on this one, well done.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:41:51'),
(371, 34, NULL, 318, NULL, 'mi', 0, 0, 7, '<p>No worries, this one is quick to nail down. Your answer <code>mi</code> doesn\'t match any Python keyword, so it looks like the response may have been cut off before you finished typing. The keyword you were reaching for is <strong>return</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the idea: when a function does some work, it often needs to hand the result back to whoever called it. That handoff happens with <code>return</code>. Without it, the function still runs, but it silently gives back <code>None</code>.</p>\n\n<pre><code>def square(n):\n    return n * n\n\nanswer = square(4)\nprint(answer)   # 16\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Notice how <code>square(4)</code> becomes the value <code>16</code> because of that<code>return</code> line. If you swap <code>return n * n</code> for <code>print(n * n)</code>, the number shows on screen but <code>answer</code>ends up as <code>None</code>, which is a super common beginner bug.</p>\n\n<p>Rule of thumb: if you want to use a function\'s result later in your code, the function must<code>return</code> it. Printing is for humans, returning is for the rest of your program.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:42:09'),
(372, 34, NULL, 287, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners. You picked <code>1name</code>, but Python has a strict rule here: <strong>a variable name cannot start with a digit</strong>. If you tried to run <code>1name = \"Aaron\"</code>, Python would immediately throw a <code>SyntaxError</code> because when it sees a <code>1</code> at the start, it expects a number, not a name.</p>\n\n<p>The reason the correct answer is <code>name_1</code> is that it follows all three of Python\'s naming rules:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>It only contains letters, digits, and underscores</li>\n<li>It starts with a letter (not a digit)</li>\n<li>It has no spaces or hyphens</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick look at why the others fail:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>name-1</code> — the hyphen is actually the minus operator, so Python reads this as <code>name minus 1</code></li>\n<li><code>my name</code> — spaces aren\'t allowed; Python sees two separate tokens</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy way to remember it: a variable name must start with a <strong>letter or underscore</strong>, and after that you can mix in digits freely. So <code>_name1</code>, <code>user2</code>, and <code>score_final</code> are all fair game.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:43:33'),
(373, 34, NULL, 288, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>3.14</strong> is a <code>float</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning: in Python, any number written with a decimal point is treated as a floating-point number, which is the type used to represent decimal (non-whole) values. So the moment you write <code>3.14</code>, Python looks at that dot and decides \"this is a float.\"</p>\n\n<p>Quick comparison so the distinction sticks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>3</code> would be an <code>int</code> (whole number, no decimal point)</li>\n<li><code>3.14</code> is a <code>float</code> (has a decimal point)</li>\n<li><code>\"3.14\"</code> would be a <code>str</code> (wrapped in quotes, so it\'s just text)</li>\n<li><code>True</code> or <code>False</code> would be a <code>bool</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always confirm a value\'s type with the built-in <code>type()</code> function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>One neat thing to remember: even <code>3.0</code> is a float, not an int, because that decimal point changes everything. Python decides the type based on how you write the literal.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:43:44'),
(374, 34, NULL, 289, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners because <code>list</code> feels like it could go either way. Let\'s untangle it.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>B) list</strong>. A <code>list</code> is actually one of Python\'s most-used built-in types. You can create one anytime, no imports needed:</p>\n\n<pre><code>fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"]\nprint(type(fruits))   # &lt;class \'list\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>So<code>list</code> is very much built in. The odd one out is <strong>C) array</strong>. As the chapter mentioned in a \"watch out\" note, Python doesn\'t have an everyday built-in <code>array</code> type the way some other languages do. There is an <code>array</code> module in the standard library, but you have to <code>import array</code> to use it, and even then it\'s rarely used. When beginners reach for an \"array\" in Python, what they actually want is a <code>list</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Quick recap of what is built in andready to use:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code>, <code>float</code>, <code>str</code>, <code>bool</code> — the four basics from this chapter</li>\n<li><code>list</code>, <code>dict</code>, <code>tuple</code>, <code>set</code> — built-in collections you\'ll meet soon</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the trick was spotting the type that sounds familiar from other languages but isn\'t a first-class citizen in Python.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:43:57'),
(375, 34, NULL, 290, NULL, 'break', 0, 0, 10, '<p>No worries, this one\'s a mix-up worth clearing up because<code>type</code> and <code>break</code> live in totally different corners of Python.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer, <code>break</code>, is actually a loop keyword. It\'s used inside a <code>for</code> or <code>while</code> loop to exit the loop early. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>for i in range(10):\n    if i == 5:\n        break\n    print(i)</code></pre>\n\n<p>That stops the loop as soon as <code>i</code> hits 5. Useful, but it has nothing to do with inspecting variables.</p>\n\n<p>The function you were after is <code>type()</code>. You pass any value or variable into it and it tells you what kind of data Python thinks it is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\nprint(type(\"hello\"))  # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\nprint(type(42))       # &lt;class \'int\'&gt;\nprint(type(True))     # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>The mental split to remember:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Keywords</strong> like <code>break</code>, <code>if</code>, <code>for</code> control the flow of your program.</li>\n<li><strong>Built-in functions</strong> like <code>type()</code>, <code>len()</code>, <code>print()</code> do something with a value, and you always call them with parentheses.</li>\n</ul>', '2026-07-05 05:44:39'),
(376, 34, NULL, 291, NULL, 'no', 0, 0, 9, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners because the concept sounds so simple. Your answer <code>no</code> is a very natural guess in English, but Python doesn\'t recognize <code>no</code> as anything special. If you typed it into the shell, Python would just complain that <code>no</code> is an undefined variable.</p>\n\n<p>The value you\'re after is <strong>None</strong>. It\'s Python\'s built-in way of saying \"there\'s nothing here yet.\" A few things worth knowing about it:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>It must be capitalized, exactly like <code>None</code>. Lowercase <code>none</code> won\'t work.</li>\n<li>It\'s not the same as <code>0</code>, an empty string <code>\"\"</code>, or <code>False</code>. Those are real values. <code>None</code> means no value at all.</li>\n<li>It\'s often used as a placeholder before a real value is known.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None\nprint(winner)   # None</code></pre>\n\n<p>Later in the program, you might assign <code>winner = \"Aaron\"</code> once the result is decided. Think of <code>None</code> as an empty slot waiting to be filled.</p>', '2026-07-05 05:46:05'),
(377, 34, NULL, 287, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, NULL, '2026-07-05 06:06:10'),
(384, 34, NULL, 339, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up when you check it with place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the ones and tens columns: <code>15 + 27</code></li>\n<li>Ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the <strong>2</strong>, carry the <strong>1</strong> over to the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>1 + 2 + 1 (carried) = 4</code>. That gives you <strong>4</strong> tens.</li>\n<li>Put them together: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check using estimation also confirms it. <code>15</code> is close to <code>15</code>, and <code>27</code> is close to <code>30</code>, so you\'d expect something near <code>45</code>. Getting <code>42</code> lands right in that neighborhood, which tells you the answer is reasonable.</p>\n\n<p>The other options were traps that skip a step. <code>40</code> and <code>41</code> would happen if you forgot to carry the <code>1</code>, and <code>52</code> would come from carrying the wrong digit. You handled the carry cleanly, which is the whole trick with two-digit addition.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:16:50'),
(385, 34, NULL, 340, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up because of the borrowing step. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>35</strong>, which usually happens when the ones column gets subtracted the wrong way around. In <code>84 - 39</code>, the ones are <code>4 - 9</code>. Since 4 is smaller than 9, it\'s tempting to flip it and do <code>9 - 4 = 5</code>, which lands you at 35. But subtraction isn\'t reversible like that. You can\'t swap the digits inside a column, you have to borrow instead.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean walkthrough:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  8 4\n- 3 9</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones: 4 minus 9 doesn\'t work, so borrow 1 ten from the 8. Now the 8 becomes 7, and the 4 becomes 14.</li>\n<li>Ones: <code>14 - 9 = 5</code>.</li>\n<li>Tens: <code>7 - 3 = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Answer: <strong>45</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick check with the opposite operation: <code>45 + 39 = 84</code>. It matches, so we know 45 is solid. Whenever the top digit is smaller, reach for borrowing rather than flipping the column.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:17:03'),
(386, 34, NULL, 341, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>13 × 6= 78</strong>, and picking A shows you\'ve got a real handle on breaking numbers apart.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean way to see why it works, straight from the Level 3 strategy of splitting numbers into friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 13 into <strong>10 + 3</strong>.</li>\n<li>Multiply each piece by 6: <code>10 × 6 = 60</code> and <code>3 × 6 = 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Add them back together: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check helps too. You know<code>13 × 5 = 65</code> (half of 130), and one more group of 13 gives <code>65 + 13 = 78</code>. Two different paths, same answer, which is a good sign your method is solid.</p>\n\n<p>The trap answers were built to catch common slips: <strong>76</strong> is what you get if you miscount the ones (say, 3 × 6 = 16),<strong>72</strong> is 12 × 6, and <strong>84</strong> is 14 × 6. Estimating first (13 is a bit over 12, so the product should be a bit over 72) rules those out fast. Keep leaning on that split-and-add trick, it scales up beautifully once numbers get bigger.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:17:15');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(387, 34, NULL, 342, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>96 ÷ 8 = 12</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"8 times what equals 96?\" So instead of trying to split 96 into piles one by one, you can hunt for the missing factor.</p>\n\n<p>One clean way to get there is to break 96 into friendlier parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>8 × 10 = 80</li>\n<li>96 − 80 = 16, and 16 ÷ 8 = 2</li>\n<li>So 10 + 2 =<strong>12</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And the check works beautifully: <code>12 × 8 = 96</code>. That\'s the inverse-operation trick from Level 4, and it\'s the fastest way to be sure a division answer is right.</p>\n\n<p>A quick estimation sanity check also would have ruled out the other options. 8 × 11 = 88(too small), 8 × 13 = 104 (too big), 8 × 14 = 112 (way too big). Only 12 lands exactly on 96. Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit, it\'ll carry you straight through the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:17:29'),
(388, 34, NULL, 343, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve! You spotted the order of operations trap and handled it perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why<strong>50</strong> is right. The expression mixes multiplication and subtraction, so multiplication comes first:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>Step 2: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The tempting wrong turn here is doing it strictly left to right, but that only works when operations are the same priority. Since multiplication outranks subtraction, it always goes first unless brackets say otherwise.</p>\n\n<p>Notice how option B (56) is exactly what you\'d get if you stopped after the multiplication step and forgot to subtract. Option C (48) is the trap for anyone who does <code>8 - 6 = 2</code> first and then <code>7 × 2</code>, treating the expression like it had hidden brackets. Both are common boss-battle slip-ups, and you avoided them.</p>\n\n<p>A good habit to keep: after each step, rewrite what\'s left. So <code>7 × 8 - 6</code> becomes <code>56 - 6</code>, then <code>50</code>. One clean line per step keeps your brain from losing the thread on longer expressions.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:17:44'),
(389, 34, NULL, 344, NULL, '27', 1, 20, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>27</strong> shows you trusted the order of operations instead of just reading left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your reasoning holds up. In any mixed expression, multiplication and division come before addition and subtraction. So even though the<code>+</code> shows up first when you read the expression, the <code>×</code> gets priority.</p>\n\n<p>Walking through it one step at a time:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with <code>9 + 9 × 2</code></li>\n<li>Handle multiplication first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>9 + 18</code></li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick trap to watch for on the boss battle: if you had gone strictly left to right, you\'d get <code>9 + 9 = 18</code>, then <code>18 × 2 = 36</code>. That\'s the classic mistake, and you avoided it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Estimation check works too. <code>9 × 2</code> is close to <code>20</code>, plus <code>9</code> lands near <code>29</code>, so <code>27</code> feels right in the neighborhood. Solid instincts here.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:18:01'),
(390, 34, NULL, 345, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>5</strong> is the answer, and more importantly, you handled the order of operations cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your reasoning holds up:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets always come first, so <code>(20 - 5)</code> gets solved before anything else: <code>20 - 5 = 15</code>.</li>\n<li>That leaves <code>15 ÷ 3</code>, which is a straight division question: how many groups of3 fit into 15? Five groups, because <code>3 × 5 = 15</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The trap on a question like this is skipping the brackets and going left to right, which would give you <code>20 - (5 ÷ 3)</code>. That\'s a completely different expression and would not land on a clean whole number. You avoided that, which tells me the bracket rule is clicking.</p>\n\n<p>A quick habit to keep sharp: after you solve the brackets, rewrite the expression on a fresh line as <code>15 ÷ 3</code> before dividing. It keeps longer boss-battle problems from getting tangled once more operations get thrown in.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:18:14'),
(391, 34, NULL, 346, NULL, '109', 0, 0, 6, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>109</strong> suggests you worked strictly left to right and treated everything as it came:6 × 4 = 24, then 24 + 12 = 36, then maybe something went sideways with the ÷ 2 step. The main issue is that arithmetic has a required order, and left-to-right isn\'t always the right path when multiple operations are mixed.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the rule: <strong>multiplication and division happen before addition and subtraction</strong>. So we handle the × and ÷ parts first, then combine with the +.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Multiplication: <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Division: <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Now rewrite what\'s left: <code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Addition last: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy trick for the Boss Battle: before you calculate anything, scan the expression and underline every × and ÷. Solve those first, rewrite the shorter expression, then finish with + and −. Rewriting after each step keeps you from losing your place, which is where big jumps like 109 usually sneak in.</p>', '2026-07-05 08:18:30'),
(395, 34, NULL, 433, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up when you check it with place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the2, carry the 1 into the tens column.</li>\n<li>Now the tens column: <code>1 + 2 = 3</code>, plus the carried 1 makes <strong>4</strong>.</li>\n<li>Put it together: <code>42</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The tricky part of this one is that carried 1. If you forget it, you\'d land on32, which is way too small. If you added the ones without carrying and just glued digits together, you\'d get something like 312, which is way too big. A quick estimate confirms your answer sits in the right zone: 15 is close to 15, 27 is close to 25, so the total should be near40. Your 42 fits that estimate perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>That habit of estimating first is going to save you in the Boss Battle when expressions get longer. Keep it up.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:10:18'),
(396, 34, NULL, 434, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>84- 39 = 45</strong>, and the way you handled the borrowing is the whole game here.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning laid out cleanly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the place values: 84 on top, 39 underneath.</li>\n<li>Ones column: 4 - 9 won\'t work directly, so borrow 1 ten from the 8. Now the tens digit becomes 7, and the ones become 14.</li>\n<li>Ones: 14 - 9 = 5.</li>\n<li>Tens: 7 - 3 = 4.</li>\n<li>Answer: <code>45</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>There\'s also a quick mental-math shortcut worth knowing. 39 is close to 40, so:</p>\n\n<pre><code>84 - 40 = 44\n44 + 1 = 45 (add1 back because you subtracted 1 too many)</code></pre>\n\n<p>Both methods land in the same place, which is a great way to double-check yourself. And you can verify with the inverse: 45 + 39 should equal 84.45 + 39 = 84. Locked in.</p>\n\n<p>The trap answers were tempting too.55 is what you\'d get if you skipped the borrow, and 35 is what happens if you borrow but forget to reduce the tens column. You avoided both.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:10:32'),
(397, 34, NULL, 435, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean <strong>78</strong>. You nailed a multiplication fact that trips up a lot of people because13 isn\'t in the standard times tables.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, using the \"break it apart\" trick from Level 3. Splitting 13 into friendlier parts makes the mental math much easier:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 13 into <strong>10 + 3</strong></li>\n<li>Multiply each part by 6: <code>10 × 6 = 60</code> and <code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Add the pieces back together: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check by estimating. 13 is close to 12, and <code>12 × 6 = 72</code>. Since 13 is one more group of 6, add 6 to get 78. That estimation habit is exactly what saves you from tempting wrong answers like 76 or 72, which sit suspiciously close to the real result.</p>\n\n<p>Remember for the boss battle: if this shows up inside a bigger expression like <code>13 × 6 + 4</code>, multiplication happens before addition. Keep breaking numbers into tens and ones, and larger products stop feeling scary.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:10:50'),
(398, 34, NULL, 436, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nicely done! <strong>12</strong> is spot on.🎯</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer works so well. Division asks the question: how many groups of 8 fit into 96? The fastest way to check is to flip it into multiplication and ask, <strong>8 times what equals 96?</strong></p>\n\n<p>One clean way to get there is to break 96 into friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 10 = 80</code></li>\n<li><code>96 − 80 = 16</code>, and <code>16÷ 8 = 2</code></li>\n<li>So <code>10 + 2 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And the multiplication check confirms it: <code>8 × 12 = 96</code>. ✅</p>\n\n<p>Quick look at why the others don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 11 would give <code>8 × 11 = 88</code>, too small.</li>\n<li>C) 13 would give <code>8 × 13 = 104</code>, too big.</li>\n<li>D) 14 would give <code>8 × 14 = 112</code>, way over.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The big idea to carry forward: whenever a division answer is offered as a choice, multiply it by the divisor. If it lands back on the original number, you\'ve got it. That inverse-operation habit will keep you fast and accurate in the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:11:02'),
(399, 34, NULL, 437, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 15, '<p>Nice attempt, and I can see exactly what happened. You picked <strong>56</strong>, which is the result of <code>7 × 8</code>. That tells me you nailed the multiplication part, you just stopped one step too early and forgot to subtract the 6 at the end.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the full journey through this expression:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Order of operations says multiplication happens before subtraction.</li>\n<li>Step 1, multiply: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>.</li>\n<li>Step 2, rewrite what\'s left: <code>56 - 6</code>.</li>\n<li>Step 3, subtract: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the answer is <strong>A) 50</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy Boss Battle habit: after you finish the multiplication or division step, rewrite the expression on a new line with the remaining numbers. That way, the leftover <code>- 6</code> can\'t sneak away from you. Option B is a classic trap the quiz sets for anyone who stops at the first calculation, so spotting it means you\'re already thinking about the pattern.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:11:28'),
(400, 34, NULL, 438, NULL, '26', 0, 0, 13, '<p>Close, but not quite. Your answer of 26 looks like it came from adding 9 + 9 first to get 18, then adding 2× somewhere, or maybe 9 + 9 = 18, then 18 + something. Either way, it points to the classic trap: solving strictly left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the fix. Order of operations says<strong>multiplication comes before addition</strong>, even when the addition is written first. So we handle 9 × 2 before touching the 9 +.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Spot the operations: one addition, one multiplication.</li>\n<li>Do multiplication first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>9 + 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A helpful habit from the course: after you resolve the multiplication, rewrite the expression on a new line so you don\'t accidentally reuse the old numbers. That single rewrite step prevents most mixed-operation slips.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check with estimation: 9 × 2 is around 20, plus another 9 lands near 30. So 27 feels right, and 26 would only work if the expression were <code>(9 + 9) + something small</code>, which it isn\'t.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:11:51'),
(401, 34, NULL, 439, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. You nailed a classic order-of-operations trap.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. The expression has brackets, so those come first, no matter what:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets first: <code>20 - 5 = 15</code></li>\n<li>Then divide: <code>15 ÷ 3 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The reason this problem catches people is that if you ignore the brackets and go left to right with the numbers, you might be tempted to do <code>5 ÷ 3</code> first, which gives a messy decimal and throws the whole thing off. The brackets are basically a signal that says \"treat what\'s inside me as one single number before you do anything else.\" So <code>(20 - 5)</code> becomes 15, and only then does the division come into play.</p>\n\n<p>A good habit for the boss battle: whenever you see brackets, circle them first so your eyes know exactly where to start. Then it\'s just multiplication and division, then addition and subtraction. You\'re clearly getting the hang of the sequence, keep that method going.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:12:10'),
(402, 34, NULL, 440, NULL, '30', 1, 20, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>30</strong> is the answer, and the way you got there shows you\'re handling order of operations like a pro.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works. The expression has multiplication, division, and addition all mixed together, so the order matters a lot. The rule is: multiplication and division come before addition, and you work them left to right.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Then <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Now the expression becomes <code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Finally, <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A common trap here is solving strictly left to right, which would give you <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, then <code>24 + 12 = 36</code>, then <code>36 ÷ 2 = 18</code>. Totally wrong answer, and it comes from ignoring that multiplication and division outrank addition.</p>\n\n<p>Quick estimation check too: 6 × 4 is around 25, and 12 ÷ 2 is small, so an answer near 30 feels right. That kind of gut-check is a great habit for the boss battle. Keep it up.</p>', '2026-07-05 11:12:28'),
(404, 34, NULL, 433, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve. <strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method holds up, using the place-value routine from Level 1:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the 2, carry the 1 into the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>1 + 2 + 1 (carried) = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Put them together: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also confirms it. Round<code>15</code> up to <code>15</code> and <code>27</code> to about <code>30</code>, and you\'d expect something close to <code>45</code>. Landing on <code>42</code> is right in that neighborhood, so the answer passes the estimation test too.</p>\n\n<p>The trap options were designed around common slips. <code>40</code> would come from forgetting the carried 1. <code>41</code> looks like an off-by-one from miscounting the ones. <code>52</code> is what happens when the carry gets added twice. You avoided all three by handling the carry cleanly, which is the whole skill in two-digit addition.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:21:08'),
(405, 34, NULL, 434, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people. Your answer of <strong>55</strong> would happen if the borrowing step got skipped and the ones column was flipped, doing <code>9 - 4= 5</code> instead of <code>4 - 9</code>. That gives 55, but subtraction doesn\'t let us swap digits inside a column just because the top one is smaller. We have to borrow instead.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean walk-through for <code>84 - 39</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones column:</strong> 4 - 9 won\'t work, so borrow 1 ten from the 8. Now the tens digit becomes 7, and the ones become 14.</li>\n<li><strong>Ones:</strong> 14 - 9 = 5</li>\n<li><strong>Tens:</strong> 7 - 3 = 4</li>\n<li><strong>Answer:</strong> 45</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick check using the inverse: <code>45 + 39</code> should get us back to 84. Ones: 5 + 9 = 14, carry 1. Tens: 4 + 3 + 1 = 8. That\'s 84. Perfect match.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea: whenever the top digit is smaller, borrowing is a place-value trade, not a shortcut you can skip. Try that rhythm on<code>72 - 38</code> next and see how it feels.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:21:31'),
(406, 34, NULL, 435, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>13 × 6 = 78</strong>, and you locked in the right option.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method behind it matters more than the answer itself. When a times-table fact isn\'t one you have instantly memorized, break the bigger number into friendly parts using place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 13 into <code>10 + 3</code></li>\n<li>Multiply each part by 6: <code>10 × 6 = 60</code> and <code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Add them back together: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This \"split and combine\" trick works for any two-digit times one-digit problem, and it\'s much safer than guessing.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also helps rule out the distractors. Option B (76) and C (72) are both even numbers close to the real answer, which is exactly how tricky options are designed. But if you estimate first, <code>13 × 6</code> is a bit more than <code>12 × 6 = 72</code>, so72 is too low and 76 isn\'t a multiple of 6 at all. That kind of estimation habit will serve you well in the Boss Battle when mixed operations start stacking up.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:21:42'),
(407, 34, NULL, 436, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. 96 ÷ 8 =<strong>12</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your thinking pays off. Division asks: how many groups of 8 fit into 96? The quickest route is to lean on the multiplication table you already know.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You know 8 × 10 = 80.</li>\n<li>96 − 80 = 16, which is 8 × 2.</li>\n<li>So 8 × (10 + 2) = 8 × 12 = 96.</li>\n<li>That means 96 ÷ 8 = 12.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick from Level 4: whenever you see a division, flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of \"96 shared into 8 groups,\" ask \"8 times what gives 96?\" It\'s usually faster and lets you double-check instantly.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check with estimation also confirms your choice. 8 × 11 = 88 (too small), 8 × 13 = 104 (too big), so 12 sits right in the sweet spot. That\'s exactly the kind of reasonableness check that keeps you from falling for close-but-wrong distractors in the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:21:57'),
(408, 34, NULL, 437, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 11, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. 🎉 You handled the order of operations perfectly on this one.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why <strong>50</strong> is the correct answer. When an expression mixes multiplication and subtraction, multiplication always goes first, no matter which symbol appears earlier when reading left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Multiply first: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>56 - 6</code></li>\n<li>Subtract: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Notice how the trap answer <strong>62</strong> would happen if someone worked strictly left to right: <code>7 × 8 - 6</code> misread as <code>7 × (8 - 6) = 7 × 2 = 14</code>… actually that gives 14, but <strong>56</strong> is the classic trap. It\'s the value right after the multiplication step, tempting if you forget to finish the subtraction.</p>\n\n<p>Your solving habit here is exactly what the Boss Battle rewards: spot the operations, do multiplication and division before addition and subtraction, then rewrite the expression after each step so nothing gets lost.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:22:27'),
(409, 34, NULL, 438, NULL, '10', 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this is one of the classic order-of-operations traps, and spotting it now is exactly how you beat it.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>10</strong> tells me you likely went left to right and also treated the numbers a bit differently than the expression says. If you added <code>9 + 9</code> first you get <code>18</code>, then times <code>2</code> gives <code>36</code>, not<code>10</code>. So it looks like something got mixed up in the middle, maybe reading <code>9 × 2</code> as just <code>2</code> or subtracting somewhere. Either way, the real issue is which operation to do first.</p>\n\n<p>The rule: multiplication happens before addition, no matter which one appears first when reading left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Spot the operations: one addition, one multiplication.</li>\n<li>Multiplication first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>9 + 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy trick is to underline the <code>×</code> before you start, so your eye jumps to it first. Estimate too: <code>9 × 2</code> alone is already <code>18</code>, so the final answer has to be bigger than that.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:22:48'),
(410, 34, NULL, 439, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 15, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>5</strong> is the answer, and you clearly followed the order of operations to get there.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your reasoning holds up:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets come first, so <code>(20 - 5)</code> gets solved before anything else. That gives you <code>15</code>.</li>\n<li>Now the expression is <code>15 ÷ 3</code>, a clean division.</li>\n<li>Ask yourself: what number times 3 equals 15? Since <code>3 × 5 = 15</code>, the quotient is <code>5</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The trap in a problem like this is skipping the brackets and going left to right, which would give you <code>20 - 5 ÷ 3</code>, a very different expression. You avoided that, which is the whole point of the Boss Battle level. Brackets always jump the line, then multiplication and division, then addition and subtraction last.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also works here: <code>5 × 3 = 15</code>, and <code>15 + 5= 20</code>. Everything ties back to the original numbers, so the answer is confirmed.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:23:18'),
(411, 34, NULL, 440, NULL, '30', 1, 20, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. You handled the order of operations like a pro.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why<code>30</code> is the winning answer. When an expression mixes multiplication, division, and addition, you don\'t just read it left to right. You take care of multiplication and division first, then come back for addition and subtraction.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Multiplication first: <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Division next: <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Now the expression is <code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Add last: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The key idea here is that multiplication and division sit on the same tier, and they both outrank addition. So even though the<code>+</code> shows up in the middle of the expression, it has to wait its turn. A common trap is to compute <code>6 × 4 + 12</code> first and get <code>36 ÷ 2 = 18</code>, but thatignores the rule. You avoided it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Estimation check: <code>24</code> plus something small, so an answer near <code>30</code> feels right. Solid instincts.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:23:30'),
(412, 19, NULL, 255, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, NULL, '2026-07-05 12:33:45'),
(413, 19, NULL, 255, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <code>my name</code>, which looks perfectly readable to us as humans, but Python sees that space in the middle and gets confused. To Python, <code>my</code> and <code>name</code> would look like two separate things sitting next to each other with no operator between them, so it raises a syntax error. Variable names have to be a single unbroken token, no spaces allowed.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the quick rule set for naming variables in Python:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Allowed characters: letters, digits, and underscores <code>_</code></li>\n<li>Cannot start with a digit (so <code>1name</code> is out)</li>\n<li>No spaces (rules out <code>my name</code>)</li>\n<li>No hyphens either, because Python reads <code>-</code> as the minus operator (rules out <code>name-1</code>)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That leaves <strong>B) <code>name_1</code></strong> as the winner. It starts with a letter, uses only letters, digits, and an underscore, and has no spaces. A common convention you\'ll see is <code>snake_case</code>, where words are joined by underscores, like <code>first_name</code> or <code>total_score</code>. Very Pythonic.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:35:00'),
(415, 19, NULL, 256, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners. It looks like you didn\'t select an answer, so let\'s walk through it together so it sticks.</p>\n\n<p>The value <code>3.14</code> has a decimal point, and in Python any number with a decimal point is a <strong>float</strong> (short for \"floating-point number\"). That makes <strong>B</strong> the correct choice.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the others don\'t fit:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>int</strong> is for whole numbers only, like <code>42</code> or <code>-7</code>. As soon as you add a <code>.</code>, it stops being an int.</li>\n<li><strong>str</strong> is for text wrapped in quotes, like <code>\"3.14\"</code>. Notice the quotes — that would be a string containing those characters, not the number itself.</li>\n<li><strong>bool</strong> only has two possible values: <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always confirm a type in Python with the built-in <code>type()</code> function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick rule of thumb: whole number means int, decimal means float, quoted means str, True/False means bool.</p>', '2026-07-05 12:35:28'),
(420, 19, NULL, 260, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people coming from other languages. You picked <code>s{0}</code>, but curly braces <code>{ }</code> in Python are used for something completely different: they build sets and dictionaries. So <code>s{0}</code> isn\'t valid syntax for grabbing a character from a string, and Python would just raise an error.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) s[0]</strong>. Here\'s the idea: strings in Python are sequences of characters, and you access individual characters using square brackets <code>[ ]</code> with an index inside. Indexing is <strong>zero-based</strong>, meaning the first character sits at position <code>0</code>, not <code>1</code>.</p>\n\n<p>So for <code>s = \"hello\"</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>s[0]  # \'h\'  ← first character\ns[1]  # \'e\'\ns[2]  # \'l\'\ns[-1] # \'o\'  ← last character</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick tour of the other options so they stick:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>s(0)</code> — parentheses mean \"call this like a function,\" but strings aren\'t callable.</li>\n<li><code>s.first()</code> — looks reasonable, but Python strings just don\'t have a <code>.first()</code> method.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Whenever you want a single character or a slice out of a string, reach for square brackets.</p>', '2026-07-05 13:18:24'),
(421, 19, NULL, 261, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, especially if you\'ve seen other languages before. Your pick, <code>.uppercase()</code>, sounds like it should work because \"uppercase\" is exactly what we want to do. But Python doesn\'t have a method by that name. If you tried running <code>\"hello\".uppercase()</code>, you\'d get an <strong>AttributeError</strong> telling you that string objects have no such method.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) .upper()</strong>. Python\'s string methods tend to favor short, punchy names:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>.upper()</code> makes everything uppercase</li>\n<li><code>.lower()</code> makes everything lowercase</li>\n<li><code>.strip()</code> trims whitespace</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Here it is in action:</p>\n\n<pre><code>greeting = \"hello\"\nprint(greeting.upper())   # HELLO</code></pre>\n\n<p>One thing worth remembering: strings in Python are <strong>immutable</strong>, so <code>.upper()</code> doesn\'t change the original string. It returns a new one. If you want to keep the uppercase version, you have to assign it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>greeting = greeting.upper()</code></pre>\n\n<p>The other two options, <code>.capital()</code> and <code>.toUpper()</code>, don\'t exist either. The real cousin of <code>.upper()</code> is <code>.capitalize()</code>, which only uppercases the first letter.</p>', '2026-07-05 13:18:34'),
(422, 19, NULL, 262, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people. Your answer, <code>\"abc 123\"</code>, assumed that the <code>+</code> operator would politely insert a space between the two strings. That\'s a reasonable guess since we humans naturally add spaces between words, but Python is more literal than that.</p>\n\n<p>When you use<code>+</code> with strings, Python does something called <strong>concatenation</strong>, which just means gluing the two sequences of characters together <em>exactly as they are</em>, with nothing added in between. So:</p>\n\n<pre><code>\"abc\" + \"123\"   # \'abc123\'</code></pre>\n\n<p>The characters <code>a</code>, <code>b</code>, <code>c</code> are followed immediately by <code>1</code>, <code>2</code>, <code>3</code>. No space, because neither string contained one.</p>\n\n<p>If you actually wanted a space, you\'d have to include it yourself, like one of these:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>\"abc\" + \" \" + \"123\"</code></li>\n<li><code>\"abc \" + \"123\"</code></li>\n<li><code>f\"{\'abc\'} {\'123\'}\"</code> using an f-string</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The key idea: Python only gives you what you literally write. Strings don\'t get \"helpful\" spaces added, whitespace is always something you put there on purpose.</p>', '2026-07-05 13:18:44'),
(423, 19, NULL, 263, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips people up because<code>s.last(3)</code> <em>sounds</em> like it should exist. It reads so naturally in English. But Python strings don\'t actually have a <code>.last()</code> method, so calling it would give you an <strong>AttributeError</strong>. That\'s the key thing to lock in: string methods you\'ll actually use are things like <code>.upper()</code>, <code>.lower()</code>, <code>.strip()</code>, <code>.replace()</code>, and <code>.split()</code>.</p>\n\n<p>To grab characters by position, Python uses <strong>slicing</strong> with square brackets, not a method. The pattern is <code>s[start:end]</code>, and the neat trick is that negative numbers count from the end of the string. So:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>s[-1]</code> is the last character, <code>\'g\'</code></li>\n<li><code>s[-3:]</code> means \"start3 from the end, go all the way to the end\"</li>\n</ul>\n\n<pre><code>s = \"programming\"\nprint(s[-3:])   # \'ing\'</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick tour of the other options so nothing feels mysterious: <code>s[3:]</code> gives <code>\'gramming\'</code> (everything from index 3 onward), and <code>s[3:-1]</code> gives <code>\'grammin\'</code> because the end index is exclusive, so the final character gets chopped off. Whenever you want \"the last N characters,\" reach for <code>s[-N:]</code>.</p>', '2026-07-05 13:18:53'),
(424, 36, 42, 260, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 2, NULL, '2026-07-05 13:25:53'),
(425, 36, 42, 261, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, NULL, '2026-07-05 13:25:56'),
(426, 36, 42, 262, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 0, NULL, '2026-07-05 13:26:03'),
(427, 36, 42, 263, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '2026-07-05 13:26:05'),
(428, 36, 42, 264, NULL, 'fewfew', 0, 0, 1, NULL, '2026-07-05 13:26:08'),
(429, 24, NULL, 95, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, especially if you\'ve seen JavaScript before, where <code>function</code> really is the keyword. In Python though, it\'s actually <code>def</code> (short for \"define\"). So option A looked reasonable, but Python borrowed a shorter, snappier keyword instead.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the shape of every Python function you\'ll ever write:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def greet(name):\n    print(f\"Hello, {name}!\")\n\ngreet(\"Aaron\")   # Hello, Aaron!</code></pre>\n\n<p>Breaking that down:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>def</strong> tells Python \"a function is about to be defined\"</li>\n<li><strong>greet</strong> is the function\'s name, which you\'ll use to call it later</li>\n<li><strong>(name)</strong> lists the parameters the function accepts</li>\n<li>The indented block below is the body, which runs each time the function is called</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick memory trick: <code>def</code> = <strong>def</strong>ine. The other options are close cousins from other languages: <code>function</code> is JavaScript, <code>func</code> is Go and Swift, and <code>define</code> isn\'t a keyword anywhere mainstream. Now that you\'ve seen it once, <code>def</code> will stick.</p>', '2026-07-05 14:25:11'),
(430, 24, NULL, 96, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this is one of those Python quirks that trips almost everyone up at first. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>A) 0</strong>. That\'s a reasonable guess if you\'re coming from a math mindset, where \"nothing\" often means zero. But in Python, <code>0</code> is a real, meaningful integer value. If a function returned <code>0</code> by default, you couldn\'t tell the difference between a function that genuinely calculated zero and one that just forgot to return anything. Python needs those two situations to look different.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) None</strong>. <code>None</code> is Python\'s special \"no value\" placeholder, and every function that doesn\'t explicitly return something hands back <code>None</code> automatically. Watch:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def shout(msg):\n    print(msg)\n\nresult = shout(\"hi\")\nprint(result)   # None\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><code>shout</code> printed something, but it never said <code>return</code>, so <code>result</code> is <code>None</code>.</p>\n\n<p>This is exactly the \"watch out\" from the Functions chapter: printing a value is not the same as returning it. If your function seems broken because the caller gets <code>None</code>, the fix is usually adding a <code>return</code>.</p>', '2026-07-05 14:25:25'),
(431, 24, NULL, 97, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>greet(\"Alice\")</code> is how you call the function.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the underlying idea. When you write <code>def greet(name):</code>, you\'re defining the function, meaning you\'re teaching Python what <code>greet</code> should do. But defining it doesn\'t run it. To actually execute the code inside, you need to call it, and the way you call any function in Python is by writing its name followed by parentheses containing the arguments:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def greet(name):\n    print(f\"Hello, {name}!\")\n\ngreet(\"Alice\")   # Hello, Alice!</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick look at why the others don\'t work:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A</strong> — Python has no <code>call</code> keyword. The parentheses alone do the calling.</li>\n<li><strong>C</strong> — <code>-&gt;</code> is used in type hints for return values, not for calling.</li>\n<li><strong>D</strong> — the dot is for accessing attributes or methods on an object, like <code>\"hi\".upper()</code>, not for passing arguments.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the pattern to remember is simple: <code>function_name(arguments)</code>. That\'s it, every time.</p>', '2026-07-05 14:25:40'),
(432, 24, NULL, 98, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people because the vocabulary all sounds similar. Let\'s untangle it.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>operator</strong>. An operator is actually a symbol that performs an action on values, like <code>+</code> for addition, <code>==</code> for comparison, or <code>%</code> for remainder. So operators live<em>inside</em> expressions, they aren\'t things you pass into a function.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>argument</strong>. Here\'s the mental model:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Parameter</strong> = the name listed in the function definition (the placeholder)</li>\n<li><strong>Argument</strong> = the actual value you hand over when you call the function</li>\n</ul>\n\n<pre><code>def add(a, b):        # a and b are parameters\n    return a + b\n\nadd(3, 5)             # 3 and 5 are arguments</code></pre>\n\n<p>So when you <em>define</em> the function, you list parameters. When you <em>call</em> it, you supply arguments that get plugged into those parameters.</p>\n\n<p>Quick note on the other options: a <strong>variable</strong> is a named container for a value in general, and an <strong>iterator</strong> is something you loop over. Close cousins, but not the word for what you pass in.</p>', '2026-07-05 14:25:52'),
(433, 24, NULL, 99, NULL, 'idk', 0, 0, 5, '<p>No worries, \"idk\" is a totally fair place to start. Let\'s lock this one in so it sticks.</p>\n\n<p>The keyword you\'re after is <code>return</code>. It\'s the line inside a function that hands a value back to whoever called it. Without it, the function still runs, but it silently gives back <code>None</code>, which is Python\'s way of saying \"nothing here.\"</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the shape of it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def square(n):\n    return n * n\n\nresult = square(4)\nprint(result)   # 16</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth burning into memory:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>return</strong> sends a value out. <strong>print</strong> just displays it on the screen. They look similar in simple examples, but only<code>return</code> lets you store the result in a variable or use it in more code.</li>\n<li>Once <code>return</code> runs, the function is done. Any lines after it are skipped.</li>\n<li>If you forget <code>return</code>, your function will seem \"broken\" because it hands back <code>None</code>. That\'s one of the most common beginner bugs, so you\'re not alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Try rewriting <code>is_even(n)</code> from the chapter using <code>return</code>. It\'ll click fast.</p>', '2026-07-05 14:26:06'),
(434, 34, NULL, 433, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method holds up, using place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the ones and tens: <code>15</code> over <code>27</code>.</li>\n<li>Ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down <strong>2</strong>, carry <strong>1</strong> into the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>1 + 2 + 1 (carried) = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Result: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check with estimation: <code>15</code> is close to <code>15</code>, and <code>27</code> is close to <code>30</code>, so the answer should land near <code>45</code>. That instantly rules out option B (<code>40</code>, too small) and C (<code>52</code>, too large). Option D (<code>41</code>) is the classic trap when someone forgets the carried <strong>1</strong> from the ones column, a mistake worth watching for on the boss battle.</p>\n\n<p>Remembering to carry whenever a column hits <code>10</code> or more is the whole game with two-digit addition. You handled it cleanly here.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:58:02'),
(435, 34, NULL, 434, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>84 - 39 = 45</strong>, and the way you can prove it to yourself is what matters here.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s walk the borrowing method, since39 has a bigger ones digit than 84 does:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up place values: 84 on top, 39 underneath.</li>\n<li>Ones column: 4 - 9 won\'t work, so borrow 1 ten from the 8. Now the tens digit becomes 7, and the ones become 14.</li>\n<li>Ones: <code>14 - 9 = 5</code>.</li>\n<li>Tens: <code>7 - 3 = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Answer: <strong>45</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>There\'s also a quicker mental trick you can lean on next time: 39 is close to 40. So do <code>84 - 40 = 44</code>, then add 1 back (because you subtracted one too many) to get <strong>45</strong>. Same answer, less writing.</p>\n\n<p>And you can always check with addition: <code>45 + 39</code> should give back 84. <code>45 + 39 = 84</code>. Confirmed. That inverse check is your best friend on subtraction questions.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:58:13'),
(436, 34, NULL, 435, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>13 × 6 = 78</strong> ✨</p>\n\n<p>What makes this one worth pausing on is the strategy.13 isn\'t a standard times-table fact, so the smart move is to break it apart using place value, just like the course suggests:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 13 into <code>10 + 3</code></li>\n<li>Multiply each part by 6: <code>10 × 6 = 60</code> and <code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Add the pieces back: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check with estimation. 13 is a little more than 12, and <code>12 × 6 = 72</code>, so the answer should be a bit above 72. That instantly rules out 72 and makes 76 look suspicious too (only4 more than 72, not enough for a whole extra group of 6).</p>\n\n<p>The trap answers here play on small slips: 76 is what you\'d get if you added 6 once too few, and 84 is <code>14 × 6</code>. Recognizing those patterns is exactly the kind of thinking that\'ll help you power through the mixed-operation problems coming up.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:58:24'),
(437, 34, NULL, 436, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>96 ÷ 8 = 12</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"8 times what number gives 96?\" If you know your 8 times table, <code>8 × 12 = 96</code> lands you straight on the answer.</p>\n\n<p>If the times table for 12 feels shaky, you can also break 96 into friendlier parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><code>80 ÷ 8 = 10</code></li>\n  <li><code>16 ÷ 8 = 2</code></li>\n  <li>Add them: <code>10 + 2 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Same answer, different route. That splitting trick is really useful when a number feels too big to divide in one go.</p>\n\n<p>And the quick sanity check the course recommends works beautifully here: multiply your answer by the divisor. <code>12 × 8 = 96</code>, which matches the original total, so the division is exact with no remainder. Since this is the Boss Battle, keep that habit going, one clean step at a time, and mixed-operation problems will feel much less intimidating.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:58:36'),
(438, 34, NULL, 437, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>62</strong> looks like it came from doing <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>, then adding 6 instead of subtracting it. That gives 62, but the expression uses a minus sign, so we need to take6 away, not add it on.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean walkthrough using order of operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>No brackets, so scan for multiplication or division first.</li>\n  <li><code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Rewrite the expression: <code>56 - 6</code>.</li>\n  <li>Now handle the subtraction: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the answer is <strong>A) 50</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A quick tip that saves marks on the boss battle: before you calculate, glance at every operation symbol in the expression. It\'s easy for your brain to see a number pair like56 and 6 and default to adding, especially under time pressure. Underlining the <code>−</code> sign first locks in the correct move. Also notice option B (56) is the multiplication result on its own, and D (62) is what you get if you add. The trap options are designed around common slips, so estimating first (56 minus a small number should land near 50) helps you spot the right one.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:58:48'),
(439, 34, NULL, 438, NULL, '8', 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, and your answer of<strong>8</strong> actually tells me something interesting about what happened. To get 8, you likely did <code>9 + 9 = 18</code>, then somehow landed on 8, or maybe <code>9 - 9 × ...</code> slipped in. Either way, the sign got lost, because9 + 9 × 2 can never be smaller than 9. That\'s a great estimation check to lean on next time: a sum with positive numbers should grow, not shrink.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the proper walkthrough using order of operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Scan the expression first. You see a <code>+</code> and a <code>×</code>.</li>\n<li>Multiplication comes before addition, so handle <code>9 × 2</code> first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left so you don\'t lose your place: <code>9 + 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The key idea: even though addition sits on the left, that doesn\'t mean it goes first. Multiplication and division always jump the queue ahead of addition and subtraction. A quick trick is to underline the <code>×</code> and <code>÷</code> symbols before you start, so your eyes know where to begin.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:59:05'),
(440, 34, NULL, 439, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>5</strong> is the answer, and the way you got there matters just as much as the number itself.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning, step by step, following order of operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets come first, always. So <code>(20 - 5)</code> gets handled before anything else: <code>20 - 5 = 15</code>.</li>\n<li>Now the expression becomes <code>15 ÷ 3</code>.</li>\n<li>Divide: <code>15 ÷ 3 = 5</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The trap in a problem like this is doing the division first, left to right, which would give you <code>20 - (5 ÷ 3)</code>, a totally different (and messy) answer. The brackets are the signal that says \"do me first, no matter what.\"</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check with the inverse: <code>5 × 3 = 15</code>, and<code>15 + 5 = 20</code>. Everything lines up, which means your answer is solid.</p>\n\n<p>Keep circling those brackets when you see them, it\'s the habit that keeps mixed expressions from tripping you up.</p>', '2026-07-05 18:59:18'),
(441, 34, NULL, 440, NULL, '45', 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of learners because it looks like a simple left-to-right calculation. Let\'s see what happened with your <strong>45</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>It looks like you worked strictly left to right: 6 × 4 = 24, then 24 + 12 = 36, then 36 ÷ 2 = 18... or maybe 6 × 4 = 24, then 24 + 12 ÷ 2 read as (24+12)÷2 doesn\'t give 45 either. Most likely you did 6 × 4 = 24, then added 12 to get 36, then something like 36 + (12÷2 reused)... either way, the mix-up is about<strong>order of operations</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the rule: multiplication and division come before addition and subtraction. So you handle both sides of the plus sign first:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Then add: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy trick: underline the × and ÷ parts before you start. Solve those little pieces first, then bring them together with the + at the end. Rewriting after each step keeps you from losing track:</p>\n\n<pre><code>6 × 4 + 12 ÷ 2\n= 24 + 6\n= 30</code></pre>', '2026-07-05 18:59:32'),
(442, 34, NULL, 312, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice one, that\'s spot on. <code>True</code> is a <strong>bool</strong>, short for boolean, and its only two possible values are <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>. Booleans are how Python represents yes/no or on/off states, which makes them the backbone of every<code>if</code> statement and <code>while</code> loop you\'ll write.</p>\n\n<p>You can always double-check a type using <code>type()</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>print(type(True))   # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;\nprint(type(False))  # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>One fun quirk worth knowing: under the hood, <code>bool</code> is actually a subclass of <code>int</code> in Python. That means <code>True</code> behaves like <code>1</code> and <code>False</code> like <code>0</code> in arithmetic:</p>\n\n<pre><code>print(True + True)    # 2\nprint(False * 10)     # 0</code></pre>\n\n<p>But even so, the <em>type</em> of <code>True</code> is still <code>bool</code>, not <code>int</code>, which is why B is the right pick. You\'ll see booleans pop up constantly when you compare things, like <code>age &gt;= 18</code> or <code>name == \"Aaron\"</code>. Every one of those comparisons evaluates to a <code>bool</code>.</p>', '2026-07-05 19:59:24');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(443, 34, NULL, 313, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice one, that\'s exactly right. <strong>elif</strong> is Python\'s keyword for chaining another condition after an <code>if</code>.</p>\n\n<p>The reason this trips people up is that almost every other language spells it differently. JavaScript and C use <code>else if</code> (two words), Ruby uses <code>elsif</code>, and some older languages use <code>elseif</code>. Python picked <code>elif</code> to keep things short and to avoid the awkward nested feel of writing <code>else: if ...:</code> over and over.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the shape you\'ll see everywhere:</p>\n\n<pre><code>score = 75\nif score &gt;= 90:\n    grade = \"A\"\nelif score &gt;= 75:\n    grade = \"B\"\nelif score &gt;= 60:\n    grade = \"C\"\nelse:\n    grade = \"F\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth locking in:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You can have as many <code>elif</code> branches as you want between the <code>if</code> and the <code>else</code>.</li>\n<li>Python checks them top to bottom and stops at the first one that\'s true, so order matters.</li>\n<li>The <code>else</code> at the end is optional. It only runs if none of the earlier conditions matched.</li>\n</ul>', '2026-07-05 19:59:35'),
(444, 34, NULL, 314, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice one! <strong>while</strong> is exactly right, and you clearly grasped the key distinction between Python\'s two main loop types.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the mental model worth locking in: a <code>while</code> loop keeps checking its condition before each iteration. As long as that condition evaluates to <code>True</code>, the loop body runs again. The moment it becomes <code>False</code>, the loop exits.</p>\n\n<pre><code>count = 0\nwhile count &lt; 3:\n    print(\"hello\")\n    count += 1</code></pre>\n\n<p>Notice how <code>count += 1</code> is doing the important work here. It updates the variable in the condition, so eventually<code>count &lt; 3</code> becomes false and the loop stops.</p>\n\n<p>Quick rundown of the other options:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>for</strong> iterates over a known sequence (a list, a<code>range()</code>, characters in a string). You use it when you know what you\'re looping through.</li>\n<li><strong>repeat</strong> and <strong>foreach</strong> exist in other languages (like Lua or C#), but they\'re not Python keywords.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Rule of thumb: use <code>for</code> when you know how many times to loop, and <code>while</code> when you\'re waiting for some condition to change, like user input or a gameending.</p>', '2026-07-05 19:59:46'),
(445, 34, NULL, 315, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>def</strong> is the keyword Python uses to define a function, and the name is short for \"define.\"</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the anatomy of what you just picked:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def greet(name):\n    return f\"Hello, {name}!\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>Reading it left to right:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>def</code> tells Python \"a function is coming\"</li>\n<li><code>greet</code> is the name you\'ll use to call it later</li>\n<li><code>(name)</code> lists the parameters the function accepts</li>\n<li>The colon and the indented block underneath are the function\'s body</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The other options are worth knowing so you can rule them out on sight. <code>function</code> and <code>define</code> feel like they should work because they read naturally, but Python\'s designers picked the shorter <code>def</code> to keep code compact. <code>func</code> isn\'t a Python keyword at all, though you\'ll sometimes see it used as a variable name for a function that\'s being passed around.</p>\n\n<p>One small thing that trips people up next: defining a function doesn\'t run it. You still need to call it with <code>greet(\"Aaron\")</code> for anything to happen.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:00:03'),
(446, 34, NULL, 316, NULL, 'break', 1, 20, 4, '<p>Nice one, that\'s exactly right. <code>break</code> is the keyword that stops a loop dead in its tracks, no matter how many iterations were left to go.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the mental model: when Python hits a <code>break</code> inside a loop, it immediately exits the loop and jumps to whatever code comes after it. Everything remaining in the current iteration and all future iterations are skipped.</p>\n\n<pre><code>for i in range(10):\n    if i == 3:\n        break\n    print(i)\nprint(\"done\")\n# 0\n# 1\n# 2\n# done</code></pre>\n\n<p>Notice the loop was set up to go from 0 to 9, but as soon as <code>i</code> became 3, <code>break</code> stopped it cold.</p>\n\n<p>It\'s worth keeping <code>break</code> in the same mental drawer as its cousin <code>continue</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>break</strong> exits the loop entirely</li>\n<li><strong>continue</strong> skips just the current iteration and moves to the next one</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A classic use case for <code>break</code> is searching, once you\'ve found what you\'re looking for, there\'s no reason to keep looping.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:00:20'),
(447, 34, NULL, 317, NULL, 'f', 1, 20, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. The letter <code>f</code> right before the opening quote is what turns an ordinary string into an f-string, which is short for \"formatted string literal.\"</p>\n\n<p>Once you add that prefix, Python starts scanning the string for curly braces <code>{ }</code> and evaluates whatever expression is inside them, dropping the result into the text. So this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>name = \"Aaron\"\nage = 21\nprint(f\"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.\")</code></pre>\n\n<p>prints <code>My name is Aaron and I am 21 years old.</code></p>\n\n<p>A few things worth remembering:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <code>f</code> goes outside the quotes, not inside: <code>f\"hello\"</code>, not <code>\"f hello\"</code>.</li>\n<li>Case matters a little less here, <code>F\"...\"</code> also works, but lowercase <code>f</code> is the convention.</li>\n<li>You can put real expressions inside the braces, not just variable names: <code>f\"{2 + 2}\"</code> gives <code>\"4\"</code>.</li>\n<li>Without the <code>f</code>, the braces are treated as literal characters, so <code>\"{name}\"</code> just prints the word <code>{name}</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You\'ve got the muscle memory for one of the most-used string tricks in Python.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:00:34'),
(448, 34, NULL, 433, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up under the place-value method:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the ones and tens: <code>15</code> above <code>27</code>.</li>\n<li>Ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the <strong>2</strong>, carry the <strong>1</strong> into the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>1 + 2 + 1 (carried) = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Put them together: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check with estimation: <code>15</code> is close to <code>15</code>, and <code>27</code> is close to <code>30</code>, so the answer should land near <code>45</code>. Your answer of <code>42</code> sits right in that neighborhood, which is a good sign you didn\'t miss a carry.</p>\n\n<p>Notice how option D (<code>41</code>) is what you\'d get if you forgot to carry the 1, and option C (<code>52</code>) is what happens if you carry a 2 instead of a 1. Getting the carry right is the whole game in two-digit addition, and you nailed it.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:04:35'),
(449, 34, NULL, 434, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 12, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve.<strong>45</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method holds up. When you line up 84 and 39 by place value, the ones column asks for 4 − 9, which doesn\'t work as-is, so you borrow. Take 1 ten from the 8 tens, leaving 7 tens, and turn the 4 ones into 14 ones.</p>\n\n<pre><code>  8 4       7 14\n-  3 9  →  -39\n             45</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones: 14 − 9 = <strong>5</strong></li>\n<li>Tens: 7 − 3 = <strong>4</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the difference is 45. You can double-check with the inverse operation: 45 + 39 should return you to 84.Ones: 5 + 9 = 14, write 4 carry 1. Tens: 4 + 3 + 1 = 8. That gives 84, confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>A quick estimation trick also would\'ve backed this up: 84 − 39 is close to 84 − 40 = 44, then add back 1 to get 45. That mental shortcut is handy when the number you\'re subtracting is near a roundten.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:04:57'),
(450, 34, NULL, 435, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, you were super close on this one. Picking <strong>76</strong> tells me your instinct on the size of the answer was solid, it just slipped by2. That usually means a small slip in one of the partial products, not a misunderstanding of multiplication itself.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s use the break-apart method from Level 3. Split 13 into friendly pieces: <code>13 = 10 + 3</code>.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>10 × 6 = 60</code></li>\n<li><code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Add them: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the correct answer is <strong>78</strong>. Here\'s a quick way to see where 76 goes wrong: if the answer were 76, then dividing back would give <code>76 ÷ 6</code>, which is not a whole number. Since 13 × 6 must split evenly by 6, the answer has to be a multiple of 6, and 78 fits (<code>6 × 13 = 78</code>).</p>\n\n<p>Little tip for next time: after multiplying, do a fast check with the inverse operation. It catches those off-by-two slips before they cost you a point.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:05:11'),
(451, 34, NULL, 436, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>96 ÷ 8 = 12</strong>, and you picked A.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method matters more than the answer. Division asks: \"8 times what equals 96?\" So instead of hunting blindly, you lean on your multiplication facts.</p>\n\n<p>One clean way to get there is to break 96 into friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>8 × 10 = 80</li>\n<li>96 − 80 = 16left over</li>\n<li>8 × 2 = 16</li>\n<li>So 8 × (10 + 2) = 8 × 12 = 96</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That gives you <code>96 ÷ 8 = 12</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also check by reversing the operation, since multiplication and division are inverses: <code>12 × 8 = 96</code>. It matches, so the answer holds up.</p>\n\n<p>A quick glance at the other options shows why they don\'t fit:<code>11 × 8 = 88</code> (too small) and <code>13 × 8 = 104</code> (too big). Estimating like that is a great habit for the boss battle, where mixed operations can trip you up if you skip the sanity check.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:05:22'),
(452, 34, NULL, 437, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>50</strong> is exactly right, and the reason you landed there matters just as much as the answer itself.</p>\n\n<p>This problem is a classic order-of-operations trap. When you see<code>7 × 8 - 6</code>, multiplication has to happen before subtraction, even though the subtraction sits on the right. Here\'s the clean walk-through:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Multiply first: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>Then subtract: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Notice how option B (56) is the number you\'d get if you stopped after the multiplication step, and option D (62) is what you\'d get if you accidentally added instead of subtracted. The trap answer here is really C (48), which is what happens if someone reads left to right and does <code>7 × 8 - 6</code> as <code>7 × (8 - 6) = 7 × 2 = 14</code>... wait, that gives 14, not 48. The 48 trap is actually <code>7 × (8 - 6)</code> misread another way. Either way, you avoided all of them.</p>\n\n<p>The rule to lock in: <strong>multiplication and division come before addition and subtraction</strong>, unless brackets say otherwise. You applied it cleanly.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:05:33'),
(453, 34, NULL, 438, NULL, '0', 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, and it\'s actually a perfect chance to lock in a key rule. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>0</strong> suggests you might have subtracted somewhere, maybe reading the expression as <code>9 + 9 - 9 × 2</code> or treating it like <code>(9 + 9) - (9 × 2)</code>, which would give <code>18 - 18 = 0</code>. That\'s a clever pattern, but the original expression only has a plus and a times, so subtraction never enters the picture.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the rule for mixed expressions: <strong>multiplication happens before addition</strong>, even when addition appears first when reading left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Step by step:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Spot the operations: <code>+</code> and <code>×</code>.</li>\n<li>Do the multiplication first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>9 + 18</code>.</li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick way to remember it: think of <code>9 × 2</code> as one bundled chunk worth 18. The plus sign is just waiting to combine 9 with that chunk. Left-to-right only applies when the operations are the same priority.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:05:46'),
(454, 34, NULL, 439, NULL, '5', 1, 20, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>5</strong> is exactly right, and the fact that you handled the brackets first tells me you\'re thinking about order of operations the correct way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning laid out cleanly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets come first, so tackle <code>(20 - 5)</code> before anything else.</li>\n<li><code>20 - 5 = 15</code>, which leaves you with <code>15 ÷ 3</code>.</li>\n<li><code>15 ÷ 3 = 5</code>, because <code>3 × 5 = 15</code>. That multiplication check is a great habit for division.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The trap on a problem like this is rushing left to right and doing <code>20 - 5 ÷ 3</code> without the brackets. If someone ignored them, they\'d divide <code>5 ÷ 3</code> first and get a messy, wrong answer. The brackets change the whole shape of the calculation, so circling them before you start (like the boss-battle strategy suggests) really pays off.</p>\n\n<p>Quick estimation check too: 15 split into 3 equal groups should feel like about 5 per group, and it does. Your answer is reasonable and correct.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:06:00'),
(455, 34, NULL, 440, NULL, '67', 0, 0, 5, '<p>No worries, this one trips up loads of people because it looks like a straight left-to-right calculation. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>67</strong> looks like you worked through it in reading order: 6 × 4 = 24, then 24 + 12 = 36, then 36 ÷ 2 would give18... so you may have done6 × 4 = 24, then added 12 to get 36, then somewhere doubled instead of halved, landing near 67. Either way, the real issue is the order, not your arithmetic.</p>\n\n<p>In mixed expressions, multiplication and division come before addition and subtraction. So treat <code>6 × 4</code> and <code>12 ÷ 2</code> as their own little packages first:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Now the expression becomes <code>24 + 6</code>, which gives <strong>30</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy trick: before you calculate, underline the × and ÷ parts. Solve those first, rewrite the line, then finish with + and −. That rewrite step keeps you from losing track mid-problem.</p>', '2026-07-05 20:06:19'),
(733, 24, NULL, 449, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>Close one. Picking <strong>A) 11</strong> usually means you counted on from7 but stopped one number short. If you start at 7 and count five more, it\'s easy to accidentally say \"8, 9, 10, 11\" — that\'s only four jumps, not five.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s slow it down using the counting-on method:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start at <strong>7</strong>.</li>\n<li>Count five more: 8 (1), 9 (2), 10 (3), 11 (4), <strong>12</strong> (5).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way is to break 5 into friendly parts. Add 3 first to reach the nextten:</p>\n\n<pre><code>7 + 3 = 10\n10 + 2 = 12</code></pre>\n\n<p>So the correct answer is <strong>B) 12</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A quick reasonableness check: the sum of two positive numbers has to be larger than either one on its own. 11 is only4 more than 7, but you were adding 5, so 11 couldn\'t be right. Try counting on your fingers or jumping to the nearest ten next time. That trick keeps small addition rock solid.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:29:31'),
(736, 24, NULL, 450, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 5, '<p>No worries, this one is a small slip and easy to fix. Let\'s look at what happened.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>D) 35</strong>. That answer is what you\'d get if you added the tens correctly (2 + 1 = 3) but only counted the 5 from the ones place and forgot to include the 3 from 13. So the ones column got shortchanged.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean way to work it out using place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the digits so ones sit underones and tens sit under tens.</li>\n<li>Add the ones column: <code>5 + 3 = 8</code>.</li>\n<li>Add the tens column: <code>2 + 1 = 3</code>, which means3 tens, or 30.</li>\n<li>Combine: <code>30 + 8 = 38</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the correct answer is <strong>A) 38</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check you can use: the sum has to be bigger than both numbers you started with. Since 35 is only10 more than 25, it couldn\'t possibly include all of 13. Estimating like that catches this kind of mistake before you commit to an answer.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:29:55'),
(738, 24, NULL, 451, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 10, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>350</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your thinking holds up. When you add <code>100 + 250</code>, lining up the place values makes it clean:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  100\n+ 250\n-----\n  350\n</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones:</strong> 0 + 0 = 0</li>\n<li><strong>Tens:</strong> 0 + 5 = 5</li>\n<li><strong>Hundreds:</strong> 1 + 2 = 3</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>No carrying needed here since no column reaches 10. That\'s theideal case for column addition.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also confirms it: 250 is already bigger than 100, so the sum has to be larger than 250. Answer B (305) would mean you only added 55, and C (250) would mean you added nothing at all, so both fail that reasonableness test. D (450) overshoots by a full hundred.</p>\n\n<p>The habit worth locking in: <strong>estimate before you commit</strong>. \"100 plus something in the 200s lands in the 300s\" gets you to the right ballpark before you even calculate. That instinct will save you on trickier problems later.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:30:14'),
(740, 24, NULL, 452, NULL, '15', 1, 15, 7, '<p>Nice work —<strong>15</strong> is spot on!</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one matters even though it looks small: <code>9 + 6</code> is one of those single-digit sums that crosses the ten mark, and it\'s the exact pattern you\'ll rely on later when carrying in bigger addition problems.</p>\n\n<p>A couple of ways to see it clearly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Counting on:</strong> start at 9, then count up 6 more — 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15.</li>\n<li><strong>Make ten:</strong> borrow 1 from the 6 to turn the 9 into 10. That leaves 5. Then <code>10 + 5 = 15</code>. This trick is fast and it\'s the same idea behind carrying.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick reasonableness check: the sum should be bigger than both9 and 6, and 15 comfortably is. Good instinct to trust.</p>\n\n<p>When you meet something like <code>29 + 6</code> later, theones column does exactly this: <code>9 + 6 = 15</code>, write the 5, carry the 1. You\'ve already got the engine running.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:30:32'),
(741, 24, NULL, 453, NULL, '162', 0, 0, 9, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>162</strong> suggests the digits got added across columns without keeping place values lined up. If you add every digit as if it were loose (4 + 8 + 5 + 2 = 19) and then shuffle things around, you can drift into the 160s. But addition only works whenones sit under ones and tens sit under tens.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean walkthrough for <code>48 + 52</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones column:</strong> 8 + 2 = 10. Write down 0, carry the 1.</li>\n<li><strong>Tens column:</strong> 4 + 5 = 9, plus the carried 1 = 10. Write down 10.</li>\n<li><strong>Total:</strong> 100.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check helps too. Both numbers are under 100, so their sum has to be under 200. And 48 is just2 away from 50, while 52 is 2 past50, so they snap together neatly:<code>50 + 50 = 100</code>. That estimation trick is gold for catching answers that drift too high.</p>\n\n<p>Give the carrying step extra attention next time and you\'ve got this.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:30:54'),
(748, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and the way to lock this in is to connect division back to multiplication, which is exactly the method from Level 4.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning laid out:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Division asks: how many equal groups of 4 fit into 20?</li>\n<li>Flip it into a multiplication question: <code>4 ×? = 20</code></li>\n<li>From your times tables, <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so the missing number is 5.</li>\n<li>Check it:5 groups of 4 gives <code>4 + 4 + 4 = 20</code>. Perfect fit, no remainder.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 20 items into 4 equal piles. Each pile ends up with 5 items. Same answer, just a different way of reading the expression.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options:4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, too small. 6 would mean <code>4 × 6 = 24</code>, too big. 10 would mean <code>4 × 10 = 40</code>, way over. Only 5 lands exactly on 20, which is what \"exact division\" looks like in this course.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:33:25'),
(749, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks a question you can flip into multiplication: \"9 times what equals 81?\" Since <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, the quotient has to be 9. That inverse relationship is the fastest way to lock in division facts without guessing.</p>\n\n<p>A quick check using the method from the course:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Rewrite as a multiplication question: <code>9 × ? = 81</code></li>\n<li>Recall your 9 times table: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So<code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check by estimating. 81 is close to 80, and 80 ÷ 10 is 8, so the answer should be near 8 or 9. That rules out the smaller options like 6 or 7 almost immediately.</p>\n\n<p>One thing worth noticing: 81 is a perfect square (<code>9 × 9</code>), which is why dividing it by 9 gives 9 back. Spotting square numbers like 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, and 100 will speed up a lot of division problems for you.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:33:44'),
(750, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve. <strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong> is spot on.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up, using the inverse-operation trick from the course. Division asks: what number times the divisor gives the total? So for<code>144 ÷ 12</code>, ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>12 times what equals 144?</strong></li>\n<li>You might already know <code>12 × 12 = 144</code> from the times tables.</li>\n<li>If not, break it up: <code>12 × 10 = 120</code>, and <code>12 × 2 = 24</code>. Then <code>120 + 24 = 144</code>. That confirms 12 groups of 12 fit into 144 exactly.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick check on why the other options don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>11</strong> would mean <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, short by 12.</li>\n<li><strong>13</strong> would mean <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, over by 12.</li>\n<li><strong>14</strong> would mean <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>, way over.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The takeaway: whenever you divide, lean on multiplication to verify. It turns a division question into a familiar times-table question, which is exactly what you did here.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:33:57'),
(751, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So <code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" Flip it into a multiplication question and your times tables do the heavy lifting:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code> (too small)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> (that\'s the one)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 8 = 64</code> (too big)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So 56 splits evenly into 8 groups of 7, or 7 groups of 8. Both readings land at the same place, which is why division and multiplication are called inverse operations.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check any division answer: multiply it back. <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>, matches the original total, so you know it\'s exact with no remainder. That habit will save you on trickier problems like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>, where checking with <code>11 × 12 = 132</code> confirms the answer without second-guessing.</p>\n\n<p>Ready to try a tougher one, or want to jump into the Boss Battle?</p>', '2026-07-06 01:34:14'),
(752, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>, and the fact that you locked it in shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So for <code>100 ÷ 25</code>, you\'re really asking, \"How many 25s fit inside 100?\" You can picture it as counting up in 25s:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25</li>\n<li>50</li>\n<li>75</li>\n<li>100</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four jumps to reach 100, so the quotient is 4.</p>\n\n<p>The other reliable trick, straight from the course, is to flip it into a multiplication check: <strong>what times 25 equals 100?</strong> Since <code>25 × 4 = 100</code>, you know <code>100 ÷ 25 = 4</code> must be correct. That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is your best friend, especially when the numbers get bigger or trickier.</p>\n\n<p>Quick tip for later levels: whenever a division problem feels heavy, ask yourself the multiplication question instead. It often turns a scary divide into a familiar times-table fact.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:34:28'),
(753, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks how many equal groups fit into a total. So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking: how many groups of 4 fit into 20? Or flip it around: 4 times what equals 20?</p>\n\n<p>Since division and multiplication are inverse operations, you can always check a division answer by multiplying:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That confirms 5 is correct. If you had picked 4, that would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, too small. Picking 6 would mean <code>4 × 6 = 24</code>, too big. Picking 10 would mean <code>4 × 10 = 40</code>, way over. The multiplication check quickly rules those out.</p>\n\n<p>A handy habit for division problems: when you see something like <code>a ÷ b</code>, ask yourself \"b times what equals a?\" Then verify by multiplying your answer back. That single trick will carry you through the whole level cleanly.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:37:25'),
(754, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a question: \"how many groups of9 fit into 81?\" The fastest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations. So you ask yourself:</p>\n\n<p><strong>9 times what equals 81?</strong></p>\n\n<p>From the times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. That confirms the quotient is 9.</p>\n\n<p>You can double-check any division answer the same way:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer: 9</li>\n<li>Multiply it by the divisor: <code>9 × 9</code></li>\n<li>If you get the original total (81), you\'re correct</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This is a handy trick when you\'re staring at multiple choice options. If you weren\'t sure, you could test each one: <code>9 × 8 = 72</code> (too small), <code>9 × 7 = 63</code> (smaller still), <code>9 × 6 = 54</code>. Only 9 × 9 lands on 81.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that multiplication-division connection. It\'ll make Level 5\'s mixed problems much smoother.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:37:39'),
(755, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks \"what number, multiplied by the divisor, gives the total?\" So instead of trying to split144 into piles, you can flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<p><code>12 × ? = 144</code></p>\n\n<p>From the times tables, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, so the quotient must be 12. That inverse-operation trick is the fastest way to handle clean division problems.</p>\n\n<p>If you ever forget the fact, you can rebuild it by breaking 12 into friendlier parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options: <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>. None of them land on 144, which confirms A is the only fit. Multiplying the choices back by the divisor is a great habit for locking in division answers.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:37:56'),
(756, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks: how many equal groups of 8 fit into 56? The fastest way to find out is to flip the question into multiplication, since division and multiplication are inverse operations. So instead of \"56 ÷ 8 = ?\", you can ask \"8 × ? = 56\".</p>\n\n<p>Running through the 8 times table:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code> (too small)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> (perfect match)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 8 = 64</code> (too big)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That confirms 7 groups of 8 make exactly 56, with nothing left over. This is what the course calls exact division, the total splits evenly into equal groups.</p>\n\n<p>A quick habit to keep using: after any division, multiply your answer by the divisor to check. <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>, so you can be confident. That same trick will save you on trickier problems like 132 ÷ 11 or anything that shows up in the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:38:14'),
(757, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this one is to flip it into a multiplication question: what number times 25 gives 100? Since 25 is a quarter of 100, four of them fit perfectly, so<code>25 × 4 = 100</code>, which confirms <code>100 ÷25 = 4</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Another way to picture it: division splits a total into equal groups. Here you\'re taking 100 and splitting it into groups of 25. You can count them out:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25</li>\n<li>25 + 25 = 50</li>\n<li>50 + 25 = 75</li>\n<li>75 + 25 = 100</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 fit into 100, matching your answer.</p>\n\n<p>A handy pattern to remember: 25 goes into 100 exactly 4 times, so anytime you see a multiple of 100 being divided by 25, you can shortcut it. For example, <code>200 ÷ 25 = 8</code> and <code>300 ÷ 25 = 12</code>. That inverse link between multiplication and division is the key idea from this level, and you used it well.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:38:31'),
(758, 30, NULL, 492, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, NULL, '2026-07-06 01:39:07'),
(759, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning behind it. Division asks one of two questions: \"How many equal groups fit?\" or \"If I split evenly, how big is each group?\" For 20 ÷ 4, you can read it as: split 20 into 4 equal groups. Each group gets 5. Or flip it: how many 4s fit inside 20? Four fits five times.</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to lock this in is to connect division to multiplication, since they\'re inverse operations. Ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>4 times what equals 20?</strong></li>\n<li>4 × 5 = 20, so 20 ÷ 4 must be 5.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s also a great way to double-check the other options. If you\'d picked B (4), then 4 × 4 = 16, not 20. If C (6), then 4 × 6 = 24, too big. If D (10), then 4 × 10 = 40, way over. Only 5 lands exactly on 20.</p>\n\n<p>Keep using that \"multiply to check\" trick and division problems get a lot friendlier.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:40:42'),
(760, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the key idea working underneath your answer: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what equals 81?\" Since <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, the answer has to be 9.</p>\n\n<p>That multiplication check is the secret weapon for every division problem. Whenever you\'re unsure, flip it around:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>81 ÷ 9 = ?</code> becomes <code>9 × ? = 81</code></li>\n<li>Run through your9 times table until you land on 81</li>\n<li><code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so the quotient is 9</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can even sanity-check by estimating. 9 tens would be 90, which is a bit more than 81, so the answer should be just under 10. Nine fits perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>This one is also a nice square-number moment: <code>9 × 9</code> is one of those facts worth locking in, because it shows up constantly in both multiplication and division questions. You\'re building the right instinct here, keep leaning on that inverse-operation trick as the numbers get bigger.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:40:56'),
(761, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Instead of trying to \"split 144 into 12 groups\" from scratch, you can flip the question around and ask:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>12 times what number equals 144?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>From your times tables, <code>12 x 12 = 144</code>, so the answer has to be 12. That\'s the inverse-operation trick from the Level 4 material, and it\'s the fastest way to handle exact division.</p>\n\n<p>If you ever forget the fact, you can build it up in friendly parts:</p>\n\n<pre><code>12 x 10 = 120\n12 x 2  = 24\n120 + 24 = 144</code></pre>\n\n<p>So 12 groups of 12 fit perfectly into 144, no remainder. A quick sanity check also helps: the other options would give you <code>12 x 14 = 168</code>, <code>12 x 11 = 132</code>, or <code>12 x 13 = 156</code>. None land on 144, so A is the only one that fits. Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit, it\'ll carry you straight through the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:41:14'),
(762, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 7, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this one is to flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of asking \"how do I split 56 into 8 equal groups,\" ask yourself:</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"8 times what equals 56?\"</strong></p>\n\n<p>From your 8 times table:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 5 = 40</code></li>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code></li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So7 is the number that fits, which means 56 splits evenly into 8 groups of 7 (or 7 groups of 8, since multiplication works both ways).</p>\n\n<p>You can always double-check a division answer by multiplying it back: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. If it matches the original number, you know you\'re safe. That inverse-check trick is one of the most reliable habits you can build for division, especially once the numbers get bigger.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:41:32'),
(763, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 7, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this one is to flip it into a multiplication question: <em>what times 25 gives me 100?</em> Since 25 is a quarter of 100, four of them fit perfectly. So the equal-groups picture is: split 100 into groups of 25, and you get4 groups.</p>\n\n<p>A couple of handy ways to see it:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Money trick: four quarters make a dollar, and each quarter is 25 cents. So <code>25 + 25 + 25 + 25 = 100</code>.</li>\n<li>Multiplication check: <code>25 × 4 = 100</code>. That confirms the quotient is correct, which is exactly the checking method from the Level 4 notes.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Remember the key idea for division: it\'s the inverse of multiplication. Whenever you\'re unsure, ask yourself <em>\"what number times the divisor gives me the total?\"</em> That question turns every division problem into a multiplication one you might already know. Keep that habit going and the boss battle will feel much friendlier.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:41:49'),
(764, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up. Division asks one of two questions:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>How many groups of 4 fit inside 20?</li>\n<li>If I split 20 into 4 equal parts, how big is each part?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Both questions give the same answer here. The fastest way to solve division is to flip it into a multiplication question: <strong>what times 4 equals 20?</strong> Since<code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the quotient must be 5.</p>\n\n<p>You can always sanity-check a division answer by multiplying it back:</p>\n\n<pre><code>5 × 4 = 20 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>If it matches the original number, you know the answer is solid.</p>\n\n<p>A quick look at why the other choices fail:4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, too small. 6 would mean <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, too big. 10 would mean <code>10 × 4 = 40</code>, way too big. Only 5 lands on 20 exactly, which is what \"exact division\" means in this level, no leftover.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:42:14'),
(765, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 8, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean hit.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks the question: how many equal groups fit into the total? So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what equals 81?\" Since<code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, the answer must be 9.</p>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick, and it\'s the fastest way to lock in division facts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Turn the division into a multiplication question.</li>\n<li>Find the missing factor using your times tables.</li>\n<li>Check by multiplying back: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 81 items into 9 equal piles, each pile ends up with 9 items. Same idea, different lens.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options: if the answer were 8, then<code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, too small. If it were 7, <code>9 × 7 = 63</code>, even smaller. That \"multiply back to verify\" habit will save you all the way through the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:42:47'),
(766, 30, NULL, 494, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 17, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up because11 and 12 are neighbors in the times tables. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>11</strong> would mean that <code>11 × 12 = 144</code>. But if we check that: <code>11 × 12 = 11 × 10 + 11 × 2 = 110 + 22 = 132</code>. That\'s 12 short of 144, so 11 isn\'t quite enough groups.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reliable way to handle division: turn it into a multiplication question. Ask yourself, \"12 times what equals 144?\"</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Try breaking 144 into friendly parts: <code>120 + 24</code>.</li>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Add the groups: <code>10 + 2 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, which means <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>. That\'s option A.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea from Level 4: division and multiplication are inverses. Whenever a division answer feels uncertain, multiply your guess by the divisor and see if it lands on the total. That check would have shown 132, not 144, and pointed you one step higher.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:43:14'),
(767, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 9, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So <code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking: how many 8s fit into 56? The fastest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question: <strong>8 times what equals 56?</strong> Since<code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7.</p>\n\n<p>That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is the whole trick for this level. Whenever you see a division problem, you can hunt for the matching times-table fact:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>56 ÷ 8 = 7</code> because <code>8 × 7 = 56</code></li>\n<li><code>56 ÷ 7 = 8</code> because <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And a quick check confirms it: multiply your answer by the divisor. <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches the total, so the split is exact with no remainder, which is what this level is all about.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on those times tables and division will keep feeling this smooth.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:44:31'),
(768, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking that makes this one click. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"How many 25s fit inside 100?\"</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to see it is through multiplication, since division and multiplication are inverse operations. Ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>25 × 1 = 25</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 2 = 50</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 3 = 75</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 make exactly 100, so the quotient is 4. You can also feel it intuitively because 25 is a quarter of 100, like four quarters in a dollar.</p>\n\n<p>A good habit to carry forward: whenever you finish a division, mentally multiply your answer by the divisor and confirm it lands back on the original total. If <code>4 × 25 = 100</code>, you know you\'re safe. That check is your best defense against slip-ups on trickier problems later.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:44:49'),
(769, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. 20 ÷ 4 = <strong>5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks one of two questions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>How many equal groups can I make?</li>\n<li>How big is each group when I split evenly?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For<code>20 ÷ 4</code>, you can read it as \"split 20 into 4 equal groups, how many go in each?\" Each group gets 5. Or flip it: \"how many 4s fit into 20?\" Also5.</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to lock this in is to lean on multiplication, since division is just its mirror image.Ask yourself: <strong>4 times what equals 20?</strong> You know <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4</code> has to be 5. That\'s also your built-in check, multiply your answer by the divisor and you should land back on the original number.</p>\n\n<p>Quick glance at the wrong options so you can spot the traps later. B (4) just echoes the divisor. C (6) would need <code>4 × 6 = 24</code>, too big. D (10) is <code>20 ÷ 2</code>, right idea, wrong divisor. You avoided all of them cleanly.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:45:08'),
(770, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks a grouping question: how many 9s fit inside 81? The cleanest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ask yourself: <code>9 ×? = 81</code></li>\n<li>From the 9 times table: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always double-check a division answer by multiplying it back with the divisor. In this case, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code> matches the original total, so the split is exact with no remainder. That\'s the hallmark of clean division at this level.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check with estimation also helps. If 9 fits into 81 roughly nine times, then answers like 6, 7, or 8 would leave leftovers (<code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, short by 9). That kind of reasoning is exactly what will carry you into the Boss Battle later.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:45:30'),
(771, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks: how many equal groups fit into the total? So<code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really asking, \"12 times what equals 144?\" The fastest route is to lean on multiplication facts you already know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So 12 groups of 12 make 144, which means<code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>. This is one worth locking in, since 12 × 12 shows up a lot.</p>\n\n<p>You can always check a division answer by flipping it back into multiplication: <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>. If the product matches the original total, the quotient is correct. That habit will save you on trickier problems where the options look close together, like the 11, 13, and 14 traps in this question. Onward to the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:45:40'),
(772, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>, and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a question that multiplication can answer: \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7. That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is the fastest, most reliable way to solve these.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it two ways, and both lead to 7:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Equal groups:</strong> Split 56 into 8 equal groups. Each group holds 7.</li>\n  <li><strong>How many fit:</strong> How many 8s fit inside 56? Seven of them, exactly.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And a quick reasonableness check: 8 × 5 = 40 (too small), 8 × 10 = 80 (too big), so the answer sits between 5 and 10. Landing on 7 fits perfectly, with no remainder, which is what \"exact division\" means at this level.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on your times tables like this. Every division fact you meet is really a multiplication fact wearing a different hat.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:45:55'),
(773, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up. Division asks the question: how many groups of the divisor fit into the total? So for <code>100 ÷ 25</code>, you\'re really asking, \"How many 25s fit into 100?\" Since division is the inverse of multiplication, you can flip it around and ask, \"25 times what equals 100?\"</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 × 1 = 25</li>\n<li>25 × 2 = 50</li>\n<li>25 × 3 = 75</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100 ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That confirms the answer is 4. A handy shortcut for dividing by 25: since four 25s make 100, dividing any multiple of 100 by 25 just means multiplying the hundreds digit by 4. For example, <code>300 ÷ 25 = 12</code>, and <code>500 ÷ 25 = 20</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Always remember the check step from the course: multiply your quotient by the divisor and see if you get the original total. <code>4 × 25 = 100</code>, so this one\'s locked in.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:46:10'),
(774, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks so cleanly. Division asks: how many equal groups fit? So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really the question, \"4 times what equals 20?\" Since you know <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the quotient has to be 5.</p>\n\n<p>You can picture it two ways, and both land in the same place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Splitting into4 equal groups:</strong> share 20 items across 4 groups, and each group gets 5.</li>\n<li><strong>Fitting groups of 4:</strong> how many 4s fit inside 20? Five of them.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check is the multiplication trick from the material: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you get back the total. <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>, so the answer holds up.</p>\n\n<p>Also worth noticing why the other options don\'t fit. If it were 4, then <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, too small. If 6, then <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, too big. If 10, then <code>10 × 4 = 40</code>, way over. That inverse check is your best friend on every division question in this level.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:46:28');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(775, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on! You picked <strong>A) 9</strong>, and it\'s exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up so well: division asks how many equal groups fit into a total. So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"How many 9s make 81?\" The cleanest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 ×? = 81</code></li>\n<li>From your times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s the big idea from this level: division and multiplication are inverse operations. Every division fact has a matching multiplication fact hiding right behind it, and you can always check your answer by multiplying back. Here, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code> confirms the split is exact, no remainder.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also works: if you split 81 into 9 equal groups, each group holds 9. Both readings of division (splitting into groups vs. counting how many fit) land on the same answer. You\'re clearly connecting the two operations, which is exactly the skill this level is training.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:46:46'),
(776, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth celebrating: you used the connection between division and multiplication, which is the heart of Level 4. Division asks \"what number times the divisor gives me the total?\" So for 144 ÷ 12, the question becomes:</p>\n\n<p><code>12 × ? = 144</code></p>\n\n<p>If you know your12 times table, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code> jumps out. If you don\'t have that fact memorized, you can build it from friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s the same \"break into tens and ones\" trick from Level 3, used in reverse to check a division.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options: 11 would give <code>11 × 12 = 132</code>, 13 would give <code>13 × 12 = 156</code>, and 14 would overshoot even further. Only 12 lands exactly on 144, which is why exact division works here with no remainder.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:47:03'),
(777, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is exactly how the course frames division: ask yourself \"what number times 8 gives me 56?\"</p>\n\n<p>Since<code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7. That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is the whole trick to Level 4. Whenever you see a division problem, flip it into a multiplication question and lean on the times table you already know.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer: 7</li>\n<li>Multiply it by the divisor: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>Matches the original total, so the split is exact.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as equal groups: 56 items shared into 8 equal piles gives 7 per pile, or 56 items grouped in bundles of 8 gives you 7 bundles. Both readings land on the same number, which is a nice sign you\'ve got the concept, not just the fact.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:47:21'),
(778, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"How many 25s fit into 100?\" Since multiplication is the inverse of division, the fastest way to check is to flip it around:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>25 × 1 = 25</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 2 = 50</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 3 = 75</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 land exactly on 100, so the quotient is 4 with no remainder. That\'s what the course means by <strong>exact division</strong>: the total splits evenly into equal groups.</p>\n\n<p>A handy mental shortcut for 25s: think of quarters. Four quarters make a whole dollar (100 cents), so 100 ÷ 25 naturally lands on 4. Same idea works for 200 ÷ 25 = 8, or 75 ÷ 25 = 3. Keep leaning on that link between multiplication and division, it\'ll make Level 5 much smoother.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:47:41'),
(779, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the concept locked in: division asks either \"how many equal groups fit?\" or \"what size is each group?\" So20 ÷ 4 is really asking, \"if I split 20 into 4 equal groups, how many are in each?\" Or flip it: \"how many 4s fit inside 20?\" Either way, the answer is 5.</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to check yourself is to use the multiplication link, since division and multiplication are inverse operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ask: <code>4 × ? = 20</code></li>\n<li>From your times tables: <code>4 × 5 = 20</code> ✓</li>\n<li>So <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options:4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code> (too small), 6 would mean <code>4 × 6 = 24</code> (too big), and 10 would mean <code>4 × 10 = 40</code> (way too big). Rejecting wrong answers by multiplying back is a solid habit for the boss battle later.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:48:04'),
(780, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a question: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what number gives me 81?\" The fastest way to find that is to lean on the multiplication fact you already know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick from Level 4. Every division problem has a matching multiplication problem hiding inside it, and finding that partner fact is usually faster than trying to split 81 into piles one at a time.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check yourself in the future: take your answer and multiply it back by the divisor. If<code>9 × 9</code> lands you at 81, you know the quotient is correct. That habit will save you on trickier ones like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>, where the multiplication check confirms 12 is right because <code>11 × 12 = 132</code>.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:48:22'),
(781, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>The best way to think about a division problem like this is to flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of asking \"how do I split 144 into 12 equal groups,\" ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>12 times what equals 144?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you know your12 times table, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code> jumps right out. That\'s a classic square number worth memorizing because it shows up often.</p>\n\n<p>If the fact didn\'t come to mind instantly, you could break it down using the method from the course:</p>\n\n<pre><code>12 × 10 = 120\n12 × 2= 24\n120 + 24 = 144</code></pre>\n\n<p>So 12 tens plus 2 more twelves gives 144, which means the answer is <code>10 + 2 = 12</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also quickly rule out the other options by checking: <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>. None land on 144, which confirms A is the only fit. Great use of the inverse-operation trick.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:48:39'),
(782, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks a simple question: how many groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" The fastest way to land on that is to lean on your times tables, which is the trick the course material highlights: division and multiplication are inverse operations.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s check it the way the course suggests:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ask the multiplication question: <code>8 ×? = 56</code></li>\n<li>Recall the fact: <code>8 × 7 = 56</code></li>\n<li>So the quotient must be <strong>7</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting: if you take 56 items and share them into 8 equal groups, each group holds 7. Same answer, different lens.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches the original total, so the division is exact with no remainder, which is exactly what this level expects. Keep using that \"multiply to check\" habit and Level 5will feel much smoother.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:48:59'),
(783, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is to flip the problem into a multiplication question: what number times 25 gives 100?</p>\n\n<p>Since<code>25 × 4 = 100</code>, the quotient has to be 4. That inverse-operation trick is the heart of Level 4, division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin.</p>\n\n<p>A couple of ways your brain might have gotten there:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Quarters of100:</strong> 25 is one quarter of 100, so100 splits into 4 equal groups of 25.</li>\n<li><strong>Count up in 25s:</strong> 25, 50, 75, 100. That\'s four jumps.</li>\n<li><strong>Check with multiplication:</strong> <code>25 × 4 = 100</code> confirms it.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The equal-groups idea is what makes division click: you\'re asking how many groups of 25 fit inside 100, and the answer is 4. Keep leaning on the multiplication facts you already know, they\'ll carry you through almost every division question at this level.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:49:19'),
(784, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks one of two questions:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>How many equal groups of 4 fit into 20?</li>\n<li>If I split 20 into 4 equal parts, how big is each part?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Both roads lead to the same place. The fastest way to get there is to flip it into a multiplication question: <code>4 × ? = 20</code>. Since <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the answer has to be 5.</p>\n\n<p>That inverse trick is your best friend for the rest of this level. Every division fact has a matching multiplication fact hiding behind it, so if your times tables are solid, division comes almost for free.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options:4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code> (too small), 6 would mean <code>4 × 6 = 24</code> (too big), and 10 would mean <code>4 × 10 = 40</code> (way over). Only 5 lands exactly on 20, which is what \"exact division\" means, no remainder left over.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:49:40'),
(785, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. When you see <code>81 ÷ 9</code>, the smartest move is to flip it into a multiplication question and ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>\"What number times 9 gives me 81?\"</li>\n<li>From your times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>.</li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9</code> must be <strong>9</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That check-by-multiplying trick is your best friend in Level 4. Any time you pick a division answer, you can multiply it back by the divisor to confirm. For example, if you had been tempted by B) 8, you could test it: <code>8 × 9 = 72</code>, not 81, so it wouldn\'t fit.</p>\n\n<p>Think of it as splitting 81 items into 9 equal groups, and each group ends up with 9 items. Clean, exact division with no remainder, which is exactly what this level is training you to spot. Keep leaning on your times tables and you\'ll fly through the rest.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:49:58'),
(786, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks: \"how many equal groups fit into the total?\" So<code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really asking, \"12 times what equals 144?\" The fastest way to confirm is to flip it into multiplication:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, which means <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>. That inverse-operation check is your best friend for division, especially when the answer choices are close together like 11, 12, 13, 14.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options: <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>. None of them land on 144, so A is the only one that fits. Keep leaning on multiplication to verify division, it\'ll make the Boss Battle much smoother.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:50:15'),
(787, 24, NULL, 449, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips people up because 10 feels like such a natural landing spot when you\'re adding. Your answer of <strong>10</strong> would mean 7 + 3, so you\'re just2 short of the real total.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s a clean way to think about 7 + 5. A really handy trick is the <strong>make-ten strategy</strong>: break the smaller number into whatever gets you to 10 first, then add what\'s left.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start at 7. How many more to reach 10? That\'s <code>3</code>.</li>\n<li>Split the 5 into <code>3 + 2</code>.</li>\n<li>7 + 3 = 10, then 10 + 2 = <strong>12</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also just count on from the bigger number: start at 7, then count up five... 8, 9, 10, 11, 12.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check: since both numbers are positive, the sum has to be bigger than either one. 10 is only 3 more than 7, which feels a little light for adding a whole 5. Estimation like that will catch these slips before you lock in an answer.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:50:30'),
(788, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work! <strong>7</strong> is exactly right, and I can tell you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. When you see <code>56 ÷ 8</code>, the fastest move is to flip it into a multiplication question: \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since<code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7.</p>\n\n<p>You can double-check any division answer this way:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer:7</li>\n<li>Multiply by the divisor:<code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>Matches the original total, so it\'s correct.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way to picture it: imagine splitting 56 cookies evenly onto 8 plates. Each plate gets 7 cookies. Or flip the meaning: how many groups of 8 fit inside 56? Seven groups. Both readings give the same answer, which is a good sign you understand the concept, not just the fact.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on your times tables like this when you hit the Boss Battle. Division problems dissolve quickly when you already know the matching multiplication fact.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:50:35'),
(789, 24, NULL, 450, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Close one. Your answer of <strong>37</strong> is just one short of the correct total, which tells me the tens lined up fine but something slipped in the ones column.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s walk through <code>25 + 13</code> using place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones column:</strong> 5 + 3 = 8</li>\n<li><strong>Tens column:</strong> 2 + 1 = 3</li>\n<li><strong>Combine:</strong> 3 tens and 8 ones = <strong>38</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the correct answer is <strong>A) 38</strong>. My guess is you may have done 5 + 2 = 7 for the ones by accident, which would land you on 37. That\'s a super common slip when your eyes jump between columns.</p>\n\n<p>A quick trick to lock this in: stack the numbers vertically in your head so ones sit under ones and tens under tens:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  2 5\n+ 1 3\n-----\n  3 8</code></pre>\n\n<p>And a sanity check: 25 + 13 should be a bit more than 25, and 38 fits that nicely. Estimation catches these small slips before they cost you a point.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:50:43'),
(790, 24, NULL, 451, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Close, but not quite. Let\'s untangle what happened. You picked <strong>305</strong>, which looks like the digits of the correct sum got shuffled a little. That\'s a really common slip when the tens column has a zero, so don\'t sweat it. Let\'s line the numbers up properly and it\'ll click.</p>\n\n<p>Stack them by place value:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  100\n+ 250\n-----\n</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones:</strong> 0 + 0 = 0</li>\n<li><strong>Tens:</strong> 0 + 5 = 5</li>\n<li><strong>Hundreds:</strong> 1 + 2 = 3</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Reading the columns from hundreds down to ones gives <strong>350</strong>, which is option A.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check: your answer 305 is actually smaller than 250, one of the numbers you were adding. When you add two positive numbers, the sum has to be bigger than both of them. That\'s a great gut-check trick, if the total looks smaller than either number you started with, something went sideways. Estimation helps too: 100 + 250 is clearly in the 300s, and specifically 50 above300.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:50:53'),
(791, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up. Division asks how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total. So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking: how many 25s fit inside 100?</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to check this is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What times 25 equals 100?</li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code></li>\n<li>So<code>100 ÷ 25 = 4</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it with money, which makes 25s feel natural. Four quarters make a dollar, and a dollar is 100 cents. Four groups of 25 cents = 100 cents. Same idea, just wearing a different outfit.</p>\n\n<p>A quick estimation trick for problems like this:25 is one-quarter of 100, and \"one-quarter\" literally means \"one of four equal parts.\" So dividing by 25 is the same as asking how many quarters are in the whole, which is 4.</p>\n\n<p>Keep that inverse-operation check in your back pocket. It\'s your best defense against division slip-ups on the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:50:55'),
(792, 24, NULL, 452, NULL, '56', 0, 0, 9, '<p>No worries, this one\'s a classic slip and easy to fix. Your answer of <strong>56</strong> looks like the two digits got stuck side by side rather than actually added. You wrote the5 and the 6 next to each other, but56 is really \"5 tens and 6 ones,\" which is way bigger than what 9 + 6 couldever be.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking that gets you to the right sum:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start at 9 and count on6 more: 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, <strong>15</strong>.</li>\n<li>Or use a friendly ten. Take 1 from the 6 and give it to the 9: <code>9 + 1 = 10</code>, and you have <code>5</code> left over. So <code>10 + 5 = 15</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check: when you add two single digits, the biggest possible answer is 9 + 9 = 18. So any sum here has to land between the larger addend (9) and 18. That estimate alone tells you 56 can\'t be right.</p>\n\n<p>The real answer is <strong>15</strong>. Keep that \"make a ten\" trick in your pocket, it makes single-digit addition much smoother.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:51:13'),
(793, 24, NULL, 453, NULL, '67', 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one\'s a classic place-value trip-up, and it\'s totally fixable. Your answer of<strong>67</strong> is quite a bit smaller than it should be, which is a clue on its own: since both48 and 52 are close to 50, the sum has to land near100. A quick estimate like that can save you every time.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s walk through it properly using place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ones column:</strong> 8 + 2 = 10. Write down 0 and carry the 1 to the tens column.</li>\n<li><strong>Tens column:</strong> 4 + 5 = 9, plus the carried 1 makes 10.</li>\n<li><strong>Result:</strong> <code>100</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Here\'s the stacked version so you can see it clearly:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  ¹48\n+5 2\n-------\n  1 0 0</code></pre>\n\n<p>My guess is you may have forgotten to carry the 1 when the ones column hit 10, which is one of the most common addition slips. Whenever a column reaches 10 or more, that extra ten always moves up to the next column. Try the estimate-first trick on the next one: \"48 is near 50, 52 is near 50, so the answer should be around 100.\" That instinct will guide you.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:51:28'),
(794, 24, NULL, 449, 'a', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, and you were super close. You picked <strong>11</strong>, which would be the answer if the problem were <code>7 + 4</code>. It looks like the 5 got counted as a 4 somewhere along the way, maybe by counting on from7 but starting at7 itself instead of the next number up.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean way to think about <code>7 + 5</code> using the counting-on strategy from the lesson:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start at<strong>7</strong> (the bigger number).</li>\n<li>Count on <strong>5</strong> more, one step at a time: 8, 9, 10, 11, <strong>12</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Notice the trick: the first number you say is <strong>8</strong>, not 7. That\'s because 7 is where you\'re starting from, not one of the steps you\'re adding.</p>\n\n<p>Another handy way is the \"make ten\" method: borrow 3 from the 5 to turn 7 into 10, then add the leftover 2. So <code>7 + 5 = 10 + 2 = 12</code>. That one gets faster with practice and works great for bigger sums too.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:51:46'),
(795, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks the question: how many equal groups fit into the total? So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"4 times what equals 20?\" Since <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the answer has to be 5.</p>\n\n<p>You can double-check by using the inverse relationship between multiplication and division:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If<code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code>, then <code>5 × 4</code> must give back 20. It does.</li>\n<li>If you had picked 4, that would mean <code>4 × 4 = 20</code>, but that\'s 16.</li>\n<li>If you had picked 10, that would mean <code>10 × 4 = 20</code>, but that\'s 40.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That \"multiply to check\" habit is your best friend in division problems, especially when the numbers get larger. Anytime you\'re unsure, just multiply your answer by the divisor and see if it matches the total.Ready for a trickier one?</p>', '2026-07-06 01:52:13'),
(796, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. 81 ÷ 9 = 9, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth celebrating: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. When you see<code>81 ÷ 9</code>, the smart move is to flip it into a multiplication question in your head:</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"9 times what equals 81?\"</strong></p>\n\n<p>From the times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so the answer has to be 9. That\'s exactly the check the course recommends, if the quotient times the divisor gives you back the original number, you know you\'re right.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to spot-check the other options:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, not 81</li>\n  <li><code>9 × 7 = 63</code>, not 81</li>\n  <li><code>9 × 6 = 54</code>, not 81</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Only 9 lands on the target. This habit of turning division into \"what fits into the multiplication?\" will carry you through much bigger problems later, like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>, where you ask \"11 times what equals 132?\" and build it from friendly facts.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:52:32'),
(797, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin, so instead of trying to \"split\" 144 into 12 groups from scratch, you can flip the question:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ask: <code>12 ×? = 144</code></li>\n<li>From your times tables, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code></li>\n<li>So <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the12 times table felt shaky, you could also break it apart like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>12 × 10 = 120\n144 − 120 = 24\n24 ÷ 12 = 2\n10 + 2 = 12</code></pre>\n\n<p>Same answer, just built from friendlier pieces.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options:11would give <code>11 × 12 = 132</code>, 13 would give <code>13 × 12 = 156</code>, and 14 would overshoot even more. That \"multiply back to check\" habit is going to save you on the Boss Battle, where mixing operations makes it easy to slip.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:52:49'),
(798, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks a grouping question: how many 8s fit into 56? The fastest way to answer that is to lean on the multiplication table you already know, since division and multiplication are inverse operations.</p>\n\n<p>Ask yourself: <code>8 × ? = 56</code>. Running through the 8 times table:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 5 = 40</code> (too small)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code> (still short)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> (perfect match)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So 56 splits cleanly into 7 groups of 8, with no remainder. That \"no remainder\" part matters at this level, exact division means the total divides evenly.</p>\n\n<p>And you can always sanity-check by reversing the operation: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. It checks out, which is the golden rule for division. Every time you solve one, multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back at the original number. Keep that habit going into the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:53:08'),
(799, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total. So 100 ÷ 25 is really asking: how many 25s fit into 100? Since multiplication is the inverse of division, you can flip the question around and ask what number times 25 gives 100.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 × 1 = 25</li>\n<li>25 × 2 = 50</li>\n<li>25 × 3 = 75</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 land exactly on 100, which confirms the quotient is 4. You can also picture it with money: four quarters make one dollar, and a dollar is 100 cents. Same idea.</p>\n\n<p>The habit worth locking in here is the check-with-multiplication move. Whenever you land on a division answer, multiply it back by the divisor. If you get the original number, you know you\'re safe. That one trick will keep you accurate all the way into the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:53:28'),
(800, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one clicks so cleanly. Division asks: how many equal groups fit into the total? So 20 ÷ 4 is really asking, \"4 times what equals 20?\" Flip it into a multiplication question and it almost answers itself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 20 items into 4 equal piles, each pile ends up with 5. Same idea, different angle.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to sanity-check any division answer is to multiply it back by the divisor. If you land on the original total, you\'re good:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Answer × Divisor = Total5   ×    4    =  20  ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>That inverse-check trick is your best friend for the rest of this level. If a division problem ever feels shaky, ask yourself the multiplication version instead and use your times tables to guide you. Ready for a trickier one when you are.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:53:49'),
(801, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this a solid answer, not just a lucky pick. Division asks the question: \"what number, multiplied by the divisor, gives the total?\" So instead of thinking about splitting 81 into piles, you can flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<p><code>9 × ? = 81</code></p>\n\n<p>From your times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so the missing number must be 9. That\'s the inverse-operation trick, and it\'s the fastest way to handle exact division.</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check with the other two wrong options to see why they don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>8</strong> would mean <code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, too small.</li>\n<li><strong>7</strong> would mean <code>9 × 7 = 63</code>, way off.</li>\n<li><strong>6</strong> would mean <code>9 × 6 = 54</code>, even further off.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Only 9 lands exactly on 81, which confirms the answer. Keep using that \"multiply back to check\" habit. It will save you on trickier divisions like <code>132 ÷ 11</code> later.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:54:08'),
(802, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up so well. Division asks the question: how many groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really asking, \"12 times what equals 144?\" The fastest way to check is with the inverse operation, multiplication.</p>\n\n<p>You can verify it two ways:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Direct fact: <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, a classic square from the times tables.</li>\n<li>Break it apart if the fact feels shaky: <code>12 × 10 = 120</code>, then <code>12 × 2 = 24</code>. Add them: <code>120 + 24 = 144</code>. Confirmed.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The other options fall apart quickly with that same check:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, not 144.</li>\n<li><code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, too big.</li>\n<li><code>12 × 14 = 168</code>, way past.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The big idea to carry forward: whenever a division answer is offered as a choice, multiply it by the divisor. If you land back on the original number, you\'ve got it. That inverse-operation trick makes division feel a lot less mysterious.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:54:25'),
(803, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks the question: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the answer must be 7.</p>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick from the lesson, and it\'s the fastest way to lock in division facts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Turn the division into a multiplication question.</li>\n<li>Pull the matching times-table fact from memory.</li>\n<li>Check by multiplying back: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>.✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also helps. Estimate first: 8 × 10 would be 80, which is too big, and 8 × 5 is only 40, too small. So the answer has to sit between 5 and 10, and 7 lands right in that window. That kind of estimation will save you on trickier problems later, especially when the numbers get bigger or a boss-battle expression mixes operations together.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:54:44'),
(804, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks: how many groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"How many 25s fit inside 100?\"</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to check is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What times 25 equals 100?</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy mental trick for 25s: think of them like quarters of100. Four quarters make a whole, so four 25s make 100. That same idea helps with things like <code>75 ÷ 25 = 3</code> or <code>200 ÷ 25 = 8</code>.</p>\n\n<p>And notice how estimation would have caught any wild guess.25 is roughly one quarter of 100, so the answer had to be around 4, not 40 or 0.4. Building that \"is this reasonable?\" instinct is exactly what makes division feel quick instead of scary.Ready for the next one when you are.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:55:04'),
(805, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and the way to see it is through the multiplication connection.</p>\n\n<p>Division asks: how many equal groups fit? So 20 ÷ 4 is really asking, \"4 times what equals 20?\" Since<code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the quotient has to be 5.</p>\n\n<p>You can picture it two ways, and both land on the same answer:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Splitting into4 equal groups:</strong> share20 items across 4 groups, each group gets 5.</li>\n<li><strong>Counting how many 4s fit:</strong> 4, 8, 12, 16, 20. That\'s five jumps of 4.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick check is always worth it. Multiply your answer back by the divisor: <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. It matches the original total, so the division is exact and correct.</p>\n\n<p>The other choices don\'t survive that check.<code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, and <code>10 × 4 = 40</code>. None of them return 20, which is exactly the kind of trap the \"multiply to verify\" habit catches. Keep leaning on that inverse-operation check as the numbers get bigger.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:55:24'),
(806, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks the question: how many equal groups of one number fit into another? So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what equals 81?\" And since<code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, the answer has to be 9.</p>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick from the lesson, and it\'s the fastest way to handle division:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Turn the division into a multiplication question.</li>\n<li>Find the missing factor using your times tables.</li>\n<li>Double-check by multiplying back: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. Match confirmed.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options:8 would give <code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, 7 gives <code>9 × 7 = 63</code>, and 6 gives <code>9 × 6 = 54</code>. None of those land on 81, so A was the only fit.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll carry you cleanly into the Boss Battle where division shows up mixed with other operations.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:55:43'),
(807, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it holds up. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"12 times what equals 144?\" Since<code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, the quotient has to be 12. That\'s one of the classic times-table facts worth keeping in your back pocket, because it shows up everywhere.</p>\n\n<p>If you ever blank on it, you can rebuild it by splitting 144 into friendlier parts:</p>\n\n<ul><li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n  <li><code>144 - 120 = 24</code></li>\n  <li><code>24 ÷ 12 = 2</code></li>\n  <li>So the full answer is <code>10 + 2 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And a quick sanity check on the other options:11 would give <code>11 × 12 = 132</code>, 13 would give <code>13 × 12 = 156</code>, 14 would overshoot even more. Only 12 lands exactly on 144, which is the whole point of exact division at this level: the total splits evenly, no remainder. Multiplying your answer back by the divisor is always a solid way to confirm.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:56:00'),
(808, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> lands perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking that makes this one click. Division asks a question you can answer with multiplication: <em>what number times 8 gives me 56?</em> Run through your 8 times table and you hit it: <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>. So 56 splits evenly into 7 groups of 8, or8 groups of 7. Either way, the answer is 7.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check yourself on any division problem:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer and multiply it by the divisor.</li>\n<li>If you get the original number back, you\'re solid.</li>\n<li>Here: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches. Done.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This is the big idea behind Level 4: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Every time you learn a times-table fact, you\'re secretly learning a division fact too. Knowing <code>8 × 7 = 56</code> instantly gives you <code>56 ÷ 8 = 7</code> and <code>56 ÷ 7 = 8</code> for free. Keep leaning on that connection and division stops feeling like a separate skill.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:56:20'),
(809, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why that answer makes sense. Division asks the question: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"how many 25s fit into 100?\" Since division is the inverse of multiplication, you can flip it around and ask, \"25 times what equals 100?\"</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>25 × 1 = 25</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 2 = 50</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 3 = 75</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s your check built right in. Whenever you land on a division answer, multiply it back by the divisor. If you get the original total, you know you\'re safe.</p>\n\n<p>A handy pattern to remember: 25 is a quarter of 100, so anything ÷ 25 tells you how many quarters fit. That\'s the same reason four quarters make a dollar. Keep leaning on that link between multiplication and division, it makes bigger problems like <code>200 ÷ 25</code> or <code>150 ÷ 25</code> much faster to reason through.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:56:40'),
(810, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in confidently.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks a grouping question, so<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking: how many groups of 4 fit into 20? Or flipped around: 4 times what number gives me 20?</p>\n\n<p>Since division and multiplication are inverse operations, the fastest way to solve this is to lean on your times tables:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can even picture it:20 cookies split evenly onto 4 plates gives 5 cookies per plate. Or, 20 cookies packed in bags of 4 makes 5 bags. Both readings of division land on the same answer, which is a good sanity check.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to verify any division answer is to multiply it back. You picked 5, and<code>5 × 4 = 20</code> matches the original total, so the check confirms it. Keep using that multiply-back trick on Level 4, it will save you from tricky distractors like the 4 and 10 options here.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:57:00'),
(811, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and the fact that you locked it in cleanly suggests you\'re already thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. So instead of trying to \"split 81 into 9 piles\" in your head, you can flip the question around and ask:</p>\n\n<p><strong>What number times 9 gives me 81?</strong></p>\n\n<p>From the9 times table, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so the quotient has to be 9. That\'s the check-with-multiplication trick from the course material, and it works every time for exact division.</p>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth noticing about this particular problem:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>It\'s one of those \"square\" facts where the number divides by itself, so both the divisor and the quotient are 9.</li>\n<li>The other options were traps. If you\'d picked 8, that would mean <code>8 × 9 = 72</code>, which is too small. Picking 7 would give <code>63</code>, even further off.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll carry you straight through to the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:57:19'),
(812, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and this one\'s worth remembering because it\'s a classic square:12 groups of 12.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning the course wants you to lean on. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"12 times what equals 144?\" So instead of splitting 144 into piles one by one, you search your times tables.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You might know <code>12 x 10 = 120</code> straight away.</li>\n<li>That leaves <code>144 - 120 = 24</code> still to account for.</li>\n<li>And <code>12 x 2 = 24</code>, so you need 2 more groups of 12.</li>\n<li>Total groups: <code>10 + 2 = 12</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Then check with the inverse operation, just like the Level 4 notes suggest: <code>12 x 12 = 144</code>. It matches, so the answer is locked in.</p>\n\n<p>The trap options were sneaky too. 11 would give <code>11 x 12 = 132</code>, and 13 would give <code>13 x 12 = 156</code>. Neither hits 144, which is why estimating and checking with multiplication keeps you safe on division questions.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:57:36'),
(813, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one clicks so nicely: division is really a multiplication question in disguise. When you see<code>56 ÷ 8</code>, you can ask yourself, \"What number times 8 gives me 56?\" Your times tables answer back: <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>. That\'s the inverse-operation trick from the lesson, and it\'s the fastest way to lock in division facts.</p>\n\n<p>You can always double-check a division answer by multiplying it back:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Your answer: 7</li>\n<li>Divisor: 8</li>\n<li>Check: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code> ✓ matches the original total</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way to picture it: imagine 56 cookies shared equally into 8 plates. Each plate gets7 cookies. Or flip it, 8 cookies per plate would fill 7 plates. Both readings of division land on the same answer, which is exactly what \"exact division\" means, no leftovers.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on those multiplication facts as you move toward the Boss Battle. They\'ll carry you through the trickier mixed-operation problems too.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:57:56'),
(814, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks the question: how many groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"How many 25s fit inside 100?\" You can picture it as four quarters making a whole dollar, or four25-point chunks stacking up to 100.</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to confirm a division answer is to flip it into a multiplication check:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 25 = 100</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Since multiplication and division are inverse operations, that check locks in the answer. A couple of mental tricks worth keeping for problems like this:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Think in known facts: 25 × 2 = 50, and doubling again gives 25 × 4 = 100.</li>\n<li>Money helps too, since quarters (25¢) are a natural way to see 25s adding up.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Estimation would also have caught any wild answer here, because 25 is a quarter of 100, so the result had to be small and tidy. Solid reasoning on this one.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:58:17'),
(815, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong> and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click for every division problem: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So <code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"what number times 4 gives me 20?\"</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Think of the4 times table: 4, 8, 12, 16, <strong>20</strong>.</li>\n<li>That\'s five steps, so <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>.</li>\n<li>Flip it around to check: <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Notice how division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Whenever you see a division question, you can turn it into a multiplication question in your head. That trick is going to save you a ton of time.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options:4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code> (too small), 6 would mean <code>4 × 6 = 24</code> (too big), and 10 would mean <code>4 × 10 = 40</code> (way too big). Only 5 lands exactly on 20. Keep using that multiply-back check on the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:58:37'),
(816, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. 🎯</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about division is to flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of asking \"how do I split 81 into 9 groups?\", ask yourself:</p>\n\n<p><strong>What number times 9 gives me 81?</strong></p>\n\n<p>From the9 times table, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code>. That inverse-operation trick is the heart of Level 4: every division fact has a matching multiplication fact hiding inside it.</p>\n\n<p>You can also check your answer the same way. If you ever pick an option and want to be sure, just multiply it back by the divisor:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>A) 9 × 9 = 81 ✅ matches the total</li>\n<li>B) 8 × 9 = 72 (too small)</li>\n<li>C) 7 × 9 = 63 (too small)</li>\n<li>D) 6 × 9 = 54 (way off)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Only option A rebuilds the original 81, which confirms it\'s the exact split with no remainder. Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit, it\'ll make the Boss Battle level much smoother when division shows up mixed with other operations.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:58:57'),
(817, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"12 times what equals 144?\" Since<code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, the quotient has to be 12. That\'s the inverse-operation trick from the lesson, and you can always use it to double-check a division answer.</p>\n\n<p>If the multiplication fact felt fuzzy, you can also build it from friendlier pieces:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So splitting 144 into equal groups of 12 gives you exactly 12 groups, with nothing left over. That\'s what \"exact division\" means in this course, the total divides evenly.</p>\n\n<p>A quick estimation sanity check also works here: 144 is close to 120, and<code>120 ÷ 12 = 10</code>, so the answer should be a little more than 10. Options like 11, 13, or 14 are in the right neighborhood, which is why checking with multiplication is the cleanest way to lock in the exact one.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:59:14'),
(818, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is by flipping the division into a multiplication question.</p>\n\n<p>Ask yourself: <em>what number times 8 gives me 56?</em> Running up the 8 times table: 8, 16, 24, 32, 40, 48, <strong>56</strong>. That\'s the 7th step, so 8 × 7 = 56, which means 56 ÷ 8 must be 7.</p>\n\n<p>This is the key idea for Level 4: division and multiplication are inverse operations. Every division fact has a matching multiplication fact hiding behind it:</p>\n\n<ul><li><code>56 ÷ 8 = 7</code> because <code>8 × 7 = 56</code></li>\n  <li><code>56 ÷ 7 = 8</code> because <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always sanity-check a division answer by multiplying it back. If you multiply your answer by the divisor and land on the original number, you know you\'re safe. Here, 7 × 8 = 56, so the check passes cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on your times tables like this. They\'ll make the Boss Battle much smoother when division shows up mixed with other operations.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:59:33');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(819, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.🎯</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking that makes this one click: division asks how many equal groups of a number fit into the total. So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"How many 25s fit into 100?\"</p>\n\n<p>You can check it using multiplication, which is the inverse operation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>25 × 1 = 25</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 2 = 50</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 3 = 75</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✅</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four jumps of 25 land you right on 100, so the quotient has to be 4.</p>\n\n<p>A handy shortcut for 25s: think of quarters in a dollar. Four quarters make100 cents, so any \"divide by 25\" question involving 100 (or multiples of 100) becomes fast. For example, <code>200 ÷ 25 = 8</code>, and <code>75 ÷ 25 = 3</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that link between multiplication and division. It turns division from guesswork into a quick lookup.</p>', '2026-07-06 01:59:53'),
(820, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you picked it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method behind it matters. Division asks a grouping question, so <code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking: \"How many groups of 4 fit into 20?\" or equivalently, \"4 times what equals 20?\"</p>\n\n<p>Since division is the inverse of multiplication, the fastest path is to lean on your times tables:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>4 × 1 = 4</li>\n<li>4 × 2 = 8</li>\n<li>4 × 3 = 12</li>\n<li>4 × 4 = 16</li>\n<li><strong>4 × 5 = 20</strong> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s your answer, 5. And you can always double-check a division result by multiplying it back: <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>, which matches the original total, so the answer is confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>The takeaway: whenever you see a division problem, flip it in your head into a multiplication question. It turns \"20 ÷ 4 = ?\" into the much friendlier \"4 × ? = 20\", and your times tables do the rest.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:00:14'),
(821, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth celebrating: it shows you\'re using the link between division and multiplication, which is the whole heart of Level 4. Division asks, \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What number times 9 gives 81?</strong></li>\n<li>From the9 times table: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So the quotient must be <strong>9</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also check it the other way, which is a great habit for exact division:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Answer × Divisor = Total\n   9    ×    9    =  81  ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>A quick note on the other options, so you can see why they don\'t fit: <strong>8 × 9 = 72</strong>, <strong>7 × 9 = 63</strong>, and <strong>6 × 9 = 54</strong>. None of them land on 81, so they can be ruled out fast once you multiply back.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" trick. It\'ll make the Boss Battle feel a lot friendlier when division shows up mixed with other operations.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:00:32'),
(822, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work! <strong>A) 12</strong> is exactly right, and this one rewards anyone who thinks of division as multiplication in reverse.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning laid out cleanly. Division asks: how many equal groups of 12 fit into 144? So flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<p><code>12 × ? = 144</code></p>\n\n<p>From your times tables, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, so the missing factor is 12. That means <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>.</p>\n\n<p>If the fact didn\'t jump out, you could also break 144 apart:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li>You still need <code>144 − 120 = 24</code> more.</li>\n<li><code>24 ÷ 12 = 2</code>, so add 2 to the 10.</li>\n<li>Final: <code>10 + 2 = 12</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And the check step, which is the habit worth keeping: multiply your answer by the divisor. <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>. Matches the original total, so the quotient is confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>That\'s the whole trick with exact division at this level.Ask what times the divisor gives the total, then verify by multiplying back.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:00:50'),
(823, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> lands the division cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7. That inverse link between multiplication and division is your best friend on this level, it turns every division problem into a times-table question you already know.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check yourself, straight from the course routine:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ask the multiplication question: 8 × ? = 56</li>\n<li>Recall the fact: 8 × 7 = 56</li>\n<li>Confirm by multiplying back: 7 × 8 = 56 ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>One small habit worth keeping: when a division problem feels unfamiliar, break the divisor into friendly parts. For example, <code>56 ÷ 8</code> could be seen as <code>40 ÷ 8 = 5</code> and <code>16 ÷ 8 = 2</code>, then <code>5 + 2 = 7</code>. Same answer, different route, both grounded in the equal-groups idea.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:01:09'),
(824, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this is to flip it into a multiplication question: \"25 times what equals 100?\" Since 25 + 25 + 25 + 25 = 100, or<code>25 × 4 = 100</code>, the quotient has to be 4.</p>\n\n<p>Another handy way to see it, using friendly numbers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>25 fits into 100 the same number of times a quarter fits into a dollar.</li>\n<li>Four quarters make a whole, so four 25s make 100.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And the check works both ways:</p>\n<pre><code>100 ÷ 25 = 4\n4 × 25 = 100  ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>That inverse-operation check is the key idea from Level 4. Whenever you finish a division problem, multiply your answer by the divisor. If you land back on the original total, you know you\'re safe. Keep that habit going and trickier ones like 132 ÷ 11 or 144 ÷ 12 will feel just as smooth.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:01:30'),
(825, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks a grouping question: how many equal groups of 4 fit inside 20? The fastest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question you already know:</p>\n\n<p><code>4 × ? = 20</code></p>\n\n<p>Run through your 4 times table: 4, 8, 12, 16, <strong>20</strong>. That\'s five steps, so <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, which means <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 20 items into 4 equal piles. Each pile gets 5. Same answer, different lens.</p>\n\n<p>A quick check on the other options, so the trap doors are clear:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B) 4</strong> would need<code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, not 20.</li>\n<li><strong>C) 6</strong> would need <code>4 × 6 = 24</code>, overshoots.</li>\n<li><strong>D) 10</strong> is <code>20 ÷ 2</code>, not<code>20 ÷ 4</code>. A classic mix-up when the divisor gets swapped.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The takeaway: whenever a division problem feels shaky, ask \"what times the divisor gives me the total?\" That link between multiplication and division is your shortcut for every question in this level.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:01:51'),
(826, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is through its multiplication partner.</p>\n\n<p>Division asks the question: \"how many groups of the divisor fit into the total?\" So <code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what equals 81?\" Since <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, the answer must be 9.</p>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick from the lesson, and it\'s the fastest way to lock in division facts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>See a division problem? Flip it into a multiplication question.</li>\n<li>Find the missing factor using your times tables.</li>\n<li>Confirm by multiplying back: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>One thing worth noticing: <code>81 ÷ 9</code> is a \"square\" division, where the divisor and the quotient are the same number. That happens whenever the total is a perfect square, like <code>36 ÷ 6 = 6</code> or <code>49 ÷ 7 = 7</code>. Spotting these patterns saves time on the boss battle later, especially when division shows up inside a mixed expression and you need the answer quickly to keep going.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:02:09'),
(827, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So for <code>144 ÷ 12</code>, you\'re really asking \"12 times what equals 144?\" That flip from division into multiplication is the whole trick for Level 4.</p>\n\n<p>You can confirm it with a quick check:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, which locks in the answer.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity pass on the other options, so you see why they don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 14 would mean <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>, too big.</li>\n<li>C) 11 would mean <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, too small.</li>\n<li>D) 13 would mean <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, also too big.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll carry you straight into the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:02:26'),
(828, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since<code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7. That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is your best friend on this level.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to lock this in whenever you see a division problem:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Rewrite it as a multiplication question in your head: <code>8 × ? = 56</code></li>\n<li>Reach for the times table you already know</li>\n<li>Double-check by multiplying back: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You could also picture it as splitting 56 items into 8 equal piles: each pile gets 7. Same answer, different lens. Both views are worth keeping in your toolkit because some problems feel more natural as \"how many groups?\" and others as \"how many in each group?\"</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on those multiplication facts and division stops feeling like a separate skill entirely.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:02:46'),
(829, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks: \"how many groups of 25 fit into 100?\" The fastest way to find out is to flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<p><code>25 × ? = 100</code></p>\n\n<p>From there, you can lean on a friendly fact you probably already know: quarters. Four quarters make a dollar, and four 25s make 100. So:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 × 2 = 50</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That confirms the quotient is <strong>4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also check it the other direction, which is a great habit for division: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the total. <code>4 × 25 = 100</code>. Perfect match, so the answer is solid.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea here is that every division fact has a matching multiplication fact hiding behind it. Whenever a division problem feels tricky, ask \"what times the divisor gives me this total?\" and use tables you already trust.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:03:06'),
(830, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in confidently.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method behind it matters. Division asks a question you can rephrase as multiplication: \"what number times 4 gives me 20?\" Since<code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the quotient has to be 5. That inverse relationship is your best friend at this level, because every division fact you meet is really a times-table fact in disguise.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 20 into 4 equal groups:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Group 1: 5</li>\n<li>Group 2: 5</li>\n<li>Group 3: 5</li>\n<li>Group 4: 5</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four fives, no leftovers, which is what \"exact division\" means in this course.</p>\n\n<p>A quick check trick for the other options: <code>4 × 4 = 16</code> (not 20), <code>4 × 6 = 24</code> (too big), and <code>4 × 10 = 40</code> (way too big). Multiplying each choice by the divisor is a solid habit when you\'re unsure. Keep that estimation-then-verify rhythm going into harder problems.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:03:26'),
(831, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and the cleanest way to think about it is exactly what the course suggests: division is the inverse of multiplication.</p>\n\n<p>Instead of trying to \"split 81 into 9 piles\" by counting, flip the question around and ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>9 times what equals 81?</strong></li>\n<li>From the 9 times table: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can double-check by multiplying your answer back by the divisor: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. Matches the total, so the division is exact with no remainder, which is what this level is all about.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options: if the answer were 8, then<code>8 × 9</code> would need to equal 81, but it\'s 72. If it were 7, <code>7 × 9= 63</code>. Neither fits. That \"multiply back to check\" trick is your best friend for every division questionahead.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:03:45'),
(832, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method behind it matters. Division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really the question: <em>12 times what equals 144?</em> Flipping it into multiplication is the fastest way to check yourself.</p>\n\n<p>If you know your 12 times table, this one pops out:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 12 = 144</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the12s feel shaky, you can also break it down using friendlier facts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Split 144 into <code>120 + 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 ÷ 12 = 10</code></li>\n<li><code>24 ÷ 12 = 2</code></li>\n<li>Add the results: <code>10 + 2 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options: <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>,<code>12 × 14 = 168</code>. None hit 144, so A is the only fit. That habit of multiplying back to verify will save you every time on the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:04:02'),
(833, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>, and the cleanest way to lock this in is to think of division as a multiplication question in disguise.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ask yourself: <strong>8 times what equals 56?</strong></li>\n<li>Walk up the 8 times table if you need to: 8 × 5 = 40, 8 × 6 = 48, 8 × 7 = 56. There it is.</li>\n<li>Check it by reversing: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches the original total, so the answer holds.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The concept underneath is that division and multiplication are inverse operations. Every division fact has a matching multiplication fact, so when you get stuck on something like <code>56 ÷ 8</code>, you don\'t have to invent a new method. You just ask which multiplication rebuilds 56 from groups of 8.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 56 items into 8 equal groups. Each group ends up with 7. Same answer, same idea, just a different way of seeing it.Ready for a trickier one when you are.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:04:22'),
(834, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer fits so well. Division asks how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total. So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking: how many 25s fit inside 100?</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>One 25 gets you to 25</li>\n<li>Two 25s gets you to 50</li>\n<li>Three 25s gets you to 75</li>\n<li>Four 25s gets you to 100</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups fit perfectly, with nothing left over. That\'s what makes this exact division.</p>\n\n<p>You can also use the multiplication check from the course material: if <code>100 ÷ 25 = 4</code>, then <code>25 × 4</code> should equal 100. And it does, since 25 + 25 + 25 + 25 = 100. Whenever you\'re unsure on a division question, flip it into a multiplication question and see which answer makes the total. That trick will carry you all the way into the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:04:42'),
(835, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks. Division asks a grouping question: how many equal groups of 4 fit into 20? Or flipped around, 4 times what number gives 20? Since division and multiplication are inverse operations, you can lean on your times tables to answer division problems.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s check it with multiplication, which is the habit worth building:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code> ✓ so<code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting. Imagine 20 cookies shared equally among 4 friends. Each friend gets 5. Same answer, different lens on the same idea.</p>\n\n<p>Quick look at why the other options don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, not 20.</li>\n<li>C) 6 would mean <code>4 × 6 = 24</code>, too big.</li>\n<li>D) 10 would mean <code>4 × 10 = 40</code>, way too big.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep that multiplication-check trick handy. It\'s your best friend for division, especially when the numbers get larger.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:05:03'),
(836, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks the question: \"how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total?\" So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what equals 81?\" Since <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, the answer must be 9.</p>\n\n<p>This is a great example of using multiplication as the backbone of division. Whenever you see a division problem, try flipping it into its multiplication partner:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>81 ÷ 9 = ?</code> becomes <code>9 × ? = 81</code></li>\n<li>Run through your9 times table: 9, 18, 27, 36, 45, 54, 63, 72, <strong>81</strong>. That\'s theninth step, so the quotient is 9.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also double-check by multiplying your answer back: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. Matches the original total, so the split is exact with no remainder, which is exactly what this course means by \"exact division.\"</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that multiplication-division connection. It\'ll make bigger problems like <code>132 ÷ 11</code> feel just as manageable.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:05:22'),
(837, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work! <strong>12</strong> is exactly right, and the fact that you locked it in cleanly tells me you\'re already thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it holds up: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So <code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really the question, \"12 times what gives me 144?\" And since<code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, the answer has to be 12.</p>\n\n<p>If you didn\'t remember that fact instantly, you could also break it apart using the trick from Level 3:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li>You still need <code>144 − 120 = 24</code> more</li>\n<li><code>24 ÷ 12 = 2</code></li>\n<li>So the full answer is <code>10 + 2 = 12</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And the golden check, straight from the Level 4 method: multiply your answer by the divisor. <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>. It matches the original number, so you know the split is exact with no remainder. That\'s the inverse-operation trick working exactly as it should.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:05:39'),
(838, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since<code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the answer has to be 7.</p>\n\n<p>This is the inverse-operation trick from the lesson, and it\'s the fastest way to handle division cleanly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Rewrite the division as a missing-factor multiplication: <code>8 × ? = 56</code></li>\n<li>Recall the times table fact: <code>8 × 7 = 56</code></li>\n<li>That missing factor is your quotient</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always check by multiplying back: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches the original total, so the split is exact with no remainder, just like the course expects at this level.</p>\n\n<p>A quick estimation habit also helps here. You know <code>8 × 5 = 40</code> and <code>8 × 10 = 80</code>, so the answer must sit between 5 and 10. Landing on 7 fits that range perfectly. Keep leaning on those multiplication facts, they\'ll carry you through the Boss Battle too.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:05:58'),
(839, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 20, '<p>No worries, a blank answer just means this one didn\'t click yet, and that\'s totally fixable. Let\'s build it up together.</p>\n\n<p>The trick with division is to flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of asking <strong>\"100 divided by 25 equals what?\"</strong>, ask:</p>\n\n<p><em>\"25 times what number gives me 100?\"</em></p>\n\n<p>Now it feels friendlier, right? Let\'s count up in 25s:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 × 1 = 25</li>\n<li>25 × 2 = 50</li>\n<li>25 × 3 = 75</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100 ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So<code>100 ÷ 25 = 4</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 100 into equal groups of 25. Think of four quarters making a whole dollar, four25-cent coins fit into 100 cents. Same idea.</p>\n\n<p>And here\'s the check the course recommends: multiply your answer back. <code>4 × 25 = 100</code>. Matches the original total, so we know it\'s solid.</p>\n\n<p>Next time you see a division problem, pause and rewrite it as a multiplication question in your head. That one habit turns most division problems into times-table problems you already know.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:06:33'),
(840, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking that makes this rock solid: division asks how many equal groups fit into a total. So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"How many groups of 4 fit into 20?\" Or equivalently, \"4 times what number equals 20?\"</p>\n\n<p>Since division and multiplication are inverse operations, you can always lean on your times tables:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And that\'s the built-in check too. Multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the original number:</p>\n\n<pre><code>5 × 4 = 20 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options so you can see why they don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, not 20</li>\n<li>C) 6 would mean <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, too big</li>\n<li>D) 10 would mean <code>10 × 4 = 40</code>, way too big</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep using that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll save you every time division gets trickier.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:08:15'),
(841, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your thinking works so well: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>81 ÷ 9</code> is really asking, \"9 times what number gives me 81?\" And that\'s a times table you can lean on directly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is the whole trick for this level. Whenever you see a division problem, flip it into a multiplication question in your head and hunt for the missing factor.</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check by multiplying your answer back by the divisor:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Answer × Divisor = Total\n9 × 9 = 81 ✓\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If it matches the original number, you\'re safe. This same habit will save you on trickier ones like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>, where you break it into friendly parts: <code>11 × 10 = 110</code>, then <code>11 × 2 = 22</code>, so <code>11 × 12 = 132</code>. Keep leaning on your times tables and division starts to feel like a puzzle you already know the pieces to.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:08:34'),
(842, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Instead of trying to \"split 144 into 12 groups\" from scratch, you can flip the question and ask <em>what number times 12 gives me 144?</em> That\'s much friendlier because times tables are already familiar territory.</p>\n\n<p>Walking through it:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ask: <code>12 × ? = 144</code></li>\n<li>Try 12: <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>. Perfect match.</li>\n<li>So <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check the other options fast using the same trick:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>B) <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>, too big.</li>\n<li>C) <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, too small.</li>\n<li>D) <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, still too big.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Only 12 lands cleanly on 144, which is what \"exact division\" means in this level: the total splits evenly with no remainder. Keep leaning on that multiply-to-check habit, it\'ll carry you straight into the Boss Battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:08:51'),
(843, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 20, '<p>No worries about leaving it blank, that just means this one didn\'t have an obvious hook yet. Let\'s build one together so<code>56 ÷ 8</code> feels automatic next time.</p>\n\n<p>The trick with division is to flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of asking \"how do I split 56 into 8 equal groups,\"ask:</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"8 times what equals 56?\"</strong></p>\n\n<p>Now you\'re just hunting through your 8 times table:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 5 = 40</code> (too small)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code> (still short)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> ✓</li>\n<li><code>8 × 8 = 64</code> (overshot)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So<code>56 ÷ 8 = 7</code>.</p>\n\n<p>And here\'s the check the course recommends, run it backwards with multiplication: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches the original total, so the answer is solid.</p>\n\n<p>Whenever a division problem feels blank, try that reframe. Every division fact has a multiplication twin hiding behind it, and the times tables you already know are doing most of the work for you.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:09:38'),
(844, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks the question: \"how many groups of25 fit inside 100?\" The cleanest way to check is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What number times 25 gives 100?</li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way to picture it: if you split 100 into equal groups of 25, you get one group for each quarter of 100. Think of money, four quarters make a dollar, so four 25s make 100. Same idea.</p>\n\n<p>You could also break it down using friendly facts:</p>\n\n<pre><code>25 + 25 = 50\n50 + 50 = 100\nThat\'s 25 counted 4 times.</code></pre>\n\n<p>The key takeaway: whenever you finish a division, multiply your answer by the divisor to confirm. If it lands back on the original total, you know you\'re safe. You used that logic here perfectly.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:11:06'),
(845, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks the question: how many equal groups of 4 fit into 20? Or flipped around: 4 times what number gives us 20? Since division is the inverse of multiplication, you can lean on your times tables to check.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>4 × 5 = 20</strong>, so <strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>.</li>\n<li>Picture it as splitting 20 cookies onto 4 plates. Each plate gets 5.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 4 would mean 4 × 4 = 16, too small.</li>\n<li>C) 6 would mean 4 × 6 = 24, too big.</li>\n<li>D) 10 would mean 4 × 10 = 40, way over.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The habit you just used, multiplying the answer back by the divisor, is your best friend for division. If it lands on the original number, you\'re safe. Keep that trick handy for trickier problems like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>, where breaking it into<code>11 × 10 + 11 × 2</code> makes the check easy.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:11:27'),
(846, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about division is to flip it into a multiplication question. Instead of asking \"how do I split 81 into 9 equal groups?\", ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What number times 9 gives me 81?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>From your times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so the answer has to be 9. That is the inverse-operation trick in action, and it works for every exact division problem in this level.</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check by multiplying your answer back:</p>\n\n<pre><code>9 × 9 = 81 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>Since it matches the original total, you know the split is clean with no remainder. A quick way to rule out the other choices: <code>8 × 9 = 72</code>, <code>7 × 9 = 63</code>, and <code>6 × 9 = 54</code>. None of them land on 81, so A was the only fit.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"division is multiplication in reverse\" idea. It will save you a lot of time when the Boss Battle mixes operations together.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:11:46'),
(847, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on! <strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth celebrating: division is really just multiplication in reverse. So instead of asking \"how do I split 144 into 12 groups?\", you can flip it and ask \"12 times what equals 144?\" That\'s often much faster.</p>\n\n<p>Walking through it:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>12 × 10 = 120</li>\n<li>You still need to reach 144, so how much more? 144 − 120 = 24</li>\n<li>24 is exactly 12 × 2</li>\n<li>So 12 × (10 + 2) = 12 × 12 = 144</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That means<code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check the other options wouldn\'t survive:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>12 × 11 = 132 (too small)</li>\n<li>12 × 13 = 156 (too big)</li>\n<li>12 × 14 = 168 (way too big)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The big takeaway: whenever a division problem feels tricky, reach for the multiplication fact that matches. It turns a splitting problem into a \"fill in the blank\" problem, which your brain handles faster.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:12:03'),
(848, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> ✨</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this one is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations. Instead of asking \"how do I split 56 into 8 equal groups,\" ask:</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"8 times what equals 56?\"</strong></p>\n\n<p>From your times tables, <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, so the answer has to be 7. That\'s the check built right in.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it two ways, and both give the same answer:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Equal groups:</strong> split 56 into 8 groups, and each group holds 7.</li>\n<li><strong>How many fit:</strong> how many 8s fit inside 56? Seven of them.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check for exact division: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the total. <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>✅. If it matches, you know you\'re safe.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that link between multiplication and division. Once your times tables feel automatic, division stops feeling like a separate skill and becomes the same fact read backwards.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:12:22'),
(849, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. 100 ÷ 25 = <strong>4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking that makes this one click. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"how many 25s fit inside 100?\"</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to check is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 × 1 = 25</li>\n<li>25 × 2 = 50</li>\n<li>25 × 3 = 75</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100 ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four jumps of 25 land exactly on 100, so the quotient is 4. You can also picture it with money: four25-cent coins make one dollar (100 cents). Same idea.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check you can use on any division problem: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you get the original total. <code>4 × 25 = 100</code>. Matches perfectly, so the answer is confirmed. That habit will save you on trickier problems later.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:12:42'),
(850, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method matters, not just the answer. Division asks one of two questions:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>How many equal groups of 4 fit into 20?</li>\n<li>If I split 20 into 4 equal groups, how big is each group?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Both roads lead to the same place. The fastest way to be sure is to flip the problem into multiplication, since division and multiplication are inverse operations. Ask yourself: <em>what times 4 equals 20?</em></p>\n\n<pre><code>4 × 1 = 4\n4 × 2 = 8\n4 × 3 = 12\n4 × 4 = 16\n4 × 5 = 20  ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>So <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code>, and you can check it instantly: <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. That check is your safety net on every division question in this level.</p>\n\n<p>Quick reasonableness test too: option D (10) would mean groups of 4fit ten times into 20, which is<code>4 × 10 = 40</code>, way too big. That estimation habit will save you on trickier divisions coming up.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:13:03'),
(851, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one clicks so nicely: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Whenever you see a division problem, you can flip it into a multiplication question in your head:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>81 ÷ 9 = ?</code> becomes <strong>\"9 times what equals 81?\"</strong></li>\n<li>From your times tables, <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>.</li>\n<li>So the missing number, and your answer, is 9.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 81 into 9 equal groups. Each group holds 9 items. Same result, just a different way of seeing it.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check any division answer: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the original number. You did <code>9 × 9</code> and got <code>81</code>, so the check passes.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that multiplication-division connection. It\'ll make the Boss Battle much smoother when division shows up mixed with other operations.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:14:21'),
(852, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"12 times what equals 144?\" So instead of hunting for the answer, you lean on a fact you already know.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>12 × 10 = 120</li>\n<li>12 × 2 = 24</li>\n<li>120 + 24 = 144</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So 12 × 12 = 144, which means 144 ÷ 12 must be 12.</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check the other options quickly using the same trick:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>12 × 11 = 132 (too small)</li>\n<li>12 × 13 = 156 (too big)</li>\n<li>12 × 14 = 168 (way too big)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Only 12 lands exactly on 144, so A is locked in. The big idea to carry forward: <strong>every division problem is a multiplication problem waiting to be answered</strong>. When a division fact feels slippery, flip it around and ask what times the divisor gives you the total. That habit will make Level 5\'s mixed problems much easier when division shows up inside a bigger expression.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:14:40'),
(853, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 20, '<p>No worries, leaving it blank just means this one didn\'t click yet, and that\'s totally fixable. Let\'s walk through it together.</p>\n\n<p>The question <code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking: <strong>how many groups of 8 fit into 56?</strong> Or flipped around: <strong>8 times what number equals 56?</strong> That flip is the key idea in Level 4, division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin.</p>\n\n<p>So let\'s hunt through the 8 times table:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 5 = 40</code> (too small)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code> (still short)</li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>There it is. Since <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, we know <code>56 ÷ 8 = 7</code>.</p>\n\n<p>A quick check to lock it in: multiply your answer by the divisor. <code>7 × 8 = 56</code> matches the original total, so the answer is solid.</p>\n\n<p>Next time you see a division problem, try asking yourself \"what times the divisor gives me this number?\" It turns division into a multiplication puzzle you already know how to solve.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:15:13'),
(854, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> ✨</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations. Instead of asking \"how do I split 100 into groups of 25,\" ask:</p>\n\n<p><strong>25 times what equals 100?</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>25 × 1 = 25</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 2 = 50</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 3 = 75</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✅</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So four groups of 25 fit perfectly into 100, which matches the idea that exact division leaves no remainder.</p>\n\n<p>A handy shortcut for 25s: think of quarters of a dollar. Four quarters make100 cents, so anything divided by 25 is really asking \"how many quarters fit?\" That trick will save you time on bigger numbers too, like <code>200 ÷ 25 = 8</code> or <code>150 ÷ 25 = 6</code>.</p>\n\n<p>And the check works both ways: <code>4 × 25 = 100</code> confirms the quotient. Solid method, keep that inverse-operation habit going into the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:15:36'),
(855, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up: division asks how many equal groups fit into a total. So \"20 ÷ 4\" is really asking, \"how many groups of 4 fit inside 20?\" The cleanest way to find out is to lean on multiplication, since the two operations are inverses of each other.</p>\n\n<p>Ask yourself: <code>4 × ? = 20</code>. Running through the 4 times table:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 3 = 12</code></li>\n<li><code>4 × 4 = 16</code></li>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s your answer, 5. And you can double-check by multiplying back: <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. If the check matches the original total, the division is correct.</p>\n\n<p>You could also picture it as splitting 20 items evenly into 4 groups. Each group would hold 5 items. Same answer, different lens on the same idea. This \"multiply to check\" habit will serve you well on the Boss Battle when division shows up mixed with other operations.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:15:57'),
(856, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is by flipping division into a multiplication question.</p>\n\n<p>Instead of thinking \"split 81 into 9 groups,\" ask yourself: <strong>what times 9 gives me 81?</strong> That\'s the inverse-operation trick from the lesson. Running through your 9 times table:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 × 7 = 63</code> (too small)</li>\n<li><code>9 × 8 = 72</code> (still short)</li>\n<li><code>9 × 9 = 81</code> (there it is)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So 9 fits into 81 exactly nine times, with no remainder, which matches what exact division should look like at this level.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check you can build into your habit: multiply your answer back by the divisor. <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>, so the total lines up perfectly. If it hadn\'t, that would be your signal to re-check.</p>\n\n<p>The other options fail this same test: <code>8 × 9 = 72</code>, <code>7 × 9 = 63</code>, <code>6 × 9 = 54</code>. None land on 81, so they can\'t be the quotient. Keep leaning on that multiplication-check habit, it makes division feel much less like guessing.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:16:15'),
(857, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 3, '<p>Nice work! <strong>12</strong> is spot on. You nailed a classic times-table fact turned around.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks: \"what number times the divisor gives the total?\" So <code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really the question, \"12 times what equals 144?\"</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, which means <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>. That\'s the multiplication check in action, and it\'s the safest way to lock in a division answer.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to rule out the other options: <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>,<code>12 × 14 = 168</code>. None of them land on 144, so A is the only clean fit.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll carry you straight into the Boss Battle, where mixed expressions often hide a division step you\'ll want to verify fast.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:16:32'),
(858, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work! <strong>7</strong> is spot on.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So <code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really the question, \"8 times what equals 56?\" That flips a division problem into a multiplication one, which is often easier to think through.</p>\n\n<p>Check it the way the course suggests:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Since multiplication and division are inverse operations, that confirms your answer perfectly. If you ever get stuck on a division fact, try walking up the times table for the divisor:</p>\n\n<pre><code>8 × 5 = 40\n8 × 6 = 48\n8 × 7 = 56  ← there it is\n8 × 8 = 64</code></pre>\n\n<p>That habit turns tricky division facts into familiar multiplication ones, and it also protects you from the classic trap of accidentally subtracting instead of grouping. You\'re building exactly the fluency Level 4 is aiming for. Ready for a tougher one, maybe a three-digit dividend?</p>', '2026-07-06 02:16:52'),
(859, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>, and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up. Division asks how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total. So <code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking: how many 25s fit inside 100?</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to check is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What number times 25 gives 100?</li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code></li>\n<li>So <code>100 ÷ 25 = 4</code>. Confirmed.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way to see it: think of 100 as four quarters of a dollar. Each quarter is 25 cents, and four of them make100. Same idea, just wearing a different outfit.</p>\n\n<p>A quick estimation habit that will help you on trickier ones: before dividing, ask yourself roughly how big the answer should be. Since 25 is a chunk of 100 that clearly fits a small number of times, you\'d expect a single-digit answer, not something like 40 or 400. That gut-check catches a lot of slips before they happen.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:17:12'),
(860, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, in the language of the course. Division asks one of two things: how many equal groups fit, or how big each group is. So <code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"How many groups of 4 fit into 20?\" or \"If I split 20 into 4 equal parts, how big is each part?\" Either way, the answer lands at 5.</p>\n\n<p>The fastest route is to lean on multiplication, since division is just its inverse. Ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>4 times what equals 20?</strong></li>\n<li>4 × 5 = 20, so 20 ÷ 4 must be 5.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can double-check by multiplying back: <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. Matches the original total, so the answer holds.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options: 4 would mean 4 × 4 = 16 (too small), 6 would mean 6 × 4 = 24 (too big), and 10 would mean 10 × 4 = 40 (way too big). Keep using that multiplication check, it makes division feel almost automatic.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:17:32'),
(861, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is to flip the division into a multiplication question.</p>\n\n<p>Ask yourself: <em>what number times 9 gives me 81?</em> That\'s the whole trick with division at this level. Instead of trying to \"split\" 81 into piles one by one, you lean on a times-table fact you already know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And you can check it the other direction too, which is a habit worth keeping: take your answer, multiply it by the divisor, and see if you land back on the original number. <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. Confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>Why this matters: division and multiplication are inverse operations, so every division fact is really a multiplication fact wearing a different hat. The stronger your times tables get, the faster division feels. If you ever hit a harder one like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>, the same move works, just break it into friendlier pieces: <code>11 × 10 = 110</code>, then <code>11 × 2 = 22</code>, total 12.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:17:51'),
(862, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re using the division-multiplication link the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really asking, \"12 times what equals 144?\" If you know your 12 times table, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code> jumps out, and you\'re done.</p>\n\n<p>If that fact isn\'t memorized yet, you can build it from friendlier pieces:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>144 − 120 = 24</code>, which is <code>12 × 2</code></li>\n<li>So <code>12 × (10 + 2) = 12 × 12 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Then check by multiplying your answer back: <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>. Matches the total, so the quotient is confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to rule out the other options:11, 13, and 14 would give <code>132</code>, <code>156</code>, and <code>168</code> when multiplied by 12. None hit 144, so A is the only fit. Keep leaning on that multiply-to-check habit, it\'s the strongest tool you have for division.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:18:08');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(863, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this problem is to flip it into a multiplication question: \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since 8 × 7 = 56, the quotient has to be 7. That\'s the inverse relationship in action, and it\'s the fastest way to handle division when the numbers come from your times tables.</p>\n\n<p>You can double-check yourself the same way every time:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer: 7</li>\n<li>Multiply by the divisor: 7 × 8</li>\n<li>Compare to the original total: 56 ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Another way to picture it: if you split 56 items into 8 equal groups, each group holds 7. Or if you ask how many groups of 8 fit inside 56, you get 7 groups. Both readings of the division symbol land on the same answer, which is a good sign you understand what division actually means, not just the fact.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on your multiplication facts like this and the harder division problems (like 132 ÷ 11) will feel just as natural.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:18:27'),
(864, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> and you nailed it.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this one click. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So <code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"how many 25s fit inside 100?\"</p>\n\n<p>The fastest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>25 × 1 = 25</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 2 = 50</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 3 = 75</code></li>\n<li><code>25 × 4 = 100</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 land exactly on 100, so the quotient is 4, with no remainder. That\'s what \"exact division\" means in this level, the number splits evenly.</p>\n\n<p>A handy trick to remember: 25 is a quarter of 100 (think of four25-cent coins making a dollar). So anytime you see something divided by 25, ask how many quarters fit. And you can always check division by multiplying back: <code>4 × 25 = 100</code>. Since it matches the original total, the answer is confirmed.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:18:47'),
(865, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a simple question: how many equal groups fit inside the total? So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"how many groups of 4 fit into 20?\" or equivalently, \"4 times what equals 20?\"</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s connect it to multiplication, which is the fastest way to check any division:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 1 = 4</code></li>\n<li><code>4 × 3 = 12</code></li>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That last line confirms it. Since 4 × 5 lands exactly on 20, the quotient must be 5.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check on the other options shows why they don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 4 → 4 × 4 = 16, not 20</li>\n<li>C) 6 → 4 × 6 = 24, too big</li>\n<li>D) 10 → 4 × 10 = 40, way too big</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that multiplication check. It turns every division problem into a times-table question you already know.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:19:08'),
(866, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is by leaning on multiplication, which is division\'s inverse.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the thinking in one line: division asks \"what number times the divisor gives the total?\" So for<code>81 ÷ 9</code>, ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What times 9 equals 81?</li>\n<li>From the9 times table: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>.</li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 81 into 9 equal groups, and each group holds 9. Or flip it: how many groups of 9 fit into 81? Nine of them. Both readings land in the same place, which is the whole point of division.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options: if the answer were 8, then<code>8 × 9 = 72</code>, too small. If it were 7, <code>7 × 9 = 63</code>. If6, <code>6 × 9 = 54</code>. None hit 81, so A is the only fit. That multiply-back habit is your best friend on every division question, especially in the boss battle where mixed operations can trip you up.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:19:26'),
(867, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth celebrating: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. When you see <code>144 ÷ 12</code>, the smartest move is to flip it into a multiplication question, \"12 times what equals 144?\" If you know your times tables, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code> jumps out, and you\'re done.</p>\n\n<p>If that fact wasn\'t instant, you could break it down using the method from the course materials:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li>You still need <code>144 − 120 = 24</code> more</li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li>So <code>12 × (10 + 2) = 12 × 12 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That confirms the quotient is 12. A quick sanity check also helps: the other options were11, 13, and 14. Multiply each by 12 and you\'d get 132, 156, and 168, none of which land on 144. Your answer is the only one that fits perfectly, which is exactly the checking trick the course recommends for division.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:19:44'),
(868, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 40, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> lands cleanly with no remainder.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a multiplication question in disguise: \"8 times what equals 56?\" You can walk up the 8 times table to find it:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 5 = 40</code></li>\n<li><code>8 × 6 = 48</code></li>\n<li><code>8 × 7 = 56</code> ✓</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That last line is your check. Since<code>7 × 8 = 56</code>, the quotient <strong>must</strong> be 7. This is the inverse-operation trick from the lesson: every division fact has a matching multiplication fact, and you can always confirm one using the other.</p>\n\n<p>Another way to see it: imagine splitting 56 objects into 8 equal groups. Each group gets 7. Or flip it around, how many groups of 8 fit into 56? Seven groups. Both readings of the division symbol give the same answer, which is a good sanity check whenever a problem feels tricky.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on those times tables. They\'re the engine behind fast, confident division.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:20:03'),
(869, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 40, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to think about this one is to flip it into a multiplication question: what number times 25 gives you 100? Since 25 × 4 = 100, the quotient has to be 4. That\'s the inverse-operation trick from the lesson in action.</p>\n\n<p>Another way to picture it: you\'re splitting 100 into equal groups of 25. Count them up:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 (one group)</li>\n<li>50 (two groups)</li>\n<li>75 (three groups)</li>\n<li>100 (four groups)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 fit perfectly into 100, which matches the exact-division idea, no remainder left over.</p>\n\n<p>A handy shortcut for dividing by 25: since four25s make 100, any multiple of 100 divided by 25 is just that number times 4. So 200 ÷ 25 = 8, 300 ÷ 25 = 12, and so on. Keep that pattern in your back pocket for the boss battle later.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:20:23'),
(870, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks: how many equal groups fit into the total? So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"4 times what number gives me 20?\" Flip it into a multiplication question and it becomes friendly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 20 items into 4 equal piles. Each pile ends up with 5. Same idea, just visual.</p>\n\n<p>A quick check trick to lock this in: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the original total.</p>\n\n<pre><code>Answer × Divisor = Dividend\n5 × 4 = 20 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>That inverse check is your best friend on the harder division questions coming up, especially with bigger numbers like <code>132 ÷ 11</code>. If your multiplication lands on the original number, you know the quotient is right. Keep this habit and Level 4 will feel smooth.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:20:44'),
(871, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 45, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and you locked it in cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it clicks so nicely: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. When you see <code>81 ÷ 9</code>, the smart move is to flip it into a multiplication question in your head:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\"9 times what equals 81?\"</strong></li>\n<li>From the9 times table: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always check a division answer by multiplying it back by the divisor. Take your answer (9), multiply by the divisor (9), and if you land on the original total (81), you know it\'s exact. That\'s the built-in safety net for every division problem in this level.</p>\n\n<p>A small bonus pattern worth remembering: the <strong>square numbers</strong> (like 9×9=81, 8×8=64, 7×7=49) show up constantly in division questions, so recognizing them saves real time. You\'re using the method, not guessing, which is exactly what this level is training.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:21:03'),
(872, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the key idea: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>144 ÷ 12</code> is really asking, \"12 times what equals 144?\" Since multiplication and division are inverse operations, you can flip the problem around:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 2 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>120 + 24 = 144</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <code>12 × 12 = 144</code>, which means <code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>. This is one worth locking into memory because12 × 12 shows up a lot, it\'s the last square in the standard times tables.</p>\n\n<p>Quick check for the others: if you\'d picked B (14), that would mean <code>12 × 14 = 168</code>, too big. C (11) gives <code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, too small. D (13) gives <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, also too big. The multiply-back trick is your best friend on division questions with multiple choice.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:21:20'),
(873, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 40, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong>, and the cleanest way to see it is through the link between division and multiplication.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning your answer reflects:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Division asks: how many equal groups of 8 fit into 56?</li>\n<li>Flip it into a multiplication question: <code>8 ×? = 56</code></li>\n<li>From the8 times table: <code>8 × 7 = 56</code></li>\n<li>So the missing number, the quotient, is <strong>7</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick check to build the habit: multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the total.</p>\n\n<pre><code>7 × 8 = 56 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>That matches the original number, so the answer holds up. This inverse-operation trick is your safety net for every division question, especially when the numbers get bigger or the choices look similar. If you ever hesitate on something like 63 ÷ 9 or 132 ÷ 11, just ask yourself what times the divisor gives the total, and you\'ll almost always find it faster than trying to split the number directly.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:21:39'),
(874, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 45, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks how many equal groups of the divisor fit inside the total. So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking: how many 25s fit into 100? You can picture it as counting up in 25s:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25, 50, 75, 100</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s four jumps to land on 100, so the quotient is 4.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to check a division answer is to flip it into a multiplication, since the two operations are inverses. Try it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>4 × 25 = 100✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>Because that matches the original total, you know the split was exact and there\'s no remainder, which is exactly what the course means by exact division.</p>\n\n<p>A handy mental trick for 25s: they\'re quarters of100. So dividing by 25 is the same as asking how many quarters make up the number. That intuition will save you time on questions like <code>200 ÷ 25</code> or <code>75 ÷ 25</code>. Keep leaning on that link between multiplication and division, it\'s the backbone of Level 4.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:22:00'),
(875, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks a question: how many equal groups fit into the total? So 20 ÷ 4 is really asking, \"how many groups of 4 fit into 20?\" or equivalently, \"4 times what equals 20?\"</p>\n\n<p>Since division and multiplication are inverse operations, you can lean on your times tables:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And here\'s the built-in check the course recommends: multiply your answer by the divisor.<code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. It matches the original total, so the answer is confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>A quick tip for the other options, so you can see why they don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>B) 4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, not 20.</li>\n<li>C) 6 would mean <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, too big.</li>\n<li>D) 10 is <code>20 ÷ 2</code>, splitting into 2 groups instead of 4.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep using that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll save you every time.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:22:20'),
(876, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and you picked it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, and it\'s worth locking in because this same trick unlocks most division questions. Division is just multiplication flipped around. So instead of asking \"how do I split 81 into9 equal groups,\" you can ask the easier question:</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"9 times what equals 81?\"</strong></p>\n\n<p>From your times tables, <code>9 x 9 = 81</code>, so the answer has to be 9.</p>\n\n<p>You can even sanity-check the other options the same way:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 x 8 = 72</code>, not 81</li>\n<li><code>9 x 7 = 63</code>, not 81</li>\n<li><code>9 x 6 = 54</code>, not 81</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Only 9 lands exactly on 81, which is what \"exact division\" means in this level: the total splits evenly with no remainder.</p>\n\n<p>Two habits to carry forward:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>When you see <code>a ÷ b</code>, rewrite it in your head as <code>b x ? = a</code>.</li>\n<li>If you\'re ever unsure, multiply your chosen answer by the divisor. If you get the original number back, you\'re right.</li>\n</ul>', '2026-07-06 02:22:39'),
(877, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong>, and you locked it in.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks: \"how many groups of12 fit into 144?\" The cleanest way to check that is by flipping it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations.</p>\n\n<p>Ask yourself: <code>12 ×? = 144</code>. If you know your12 times table, <code>12 × 12 = 144</code> jumps out right away. So the missing number, and your quotient, is 12.</p>\n\n<p>If the12 times table felt shaky, you could also break it apart using friendlier facts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>144 − 120 = 24</code></li>\n<li><code>24 ÷ 12 = 2</code></li>\n<li>So<code>10 + 2 = 12</code> groups total.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That splitting trick is handy whenever a division problem feels too big to see at a glance. It turns one hard fact into two easy ones.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options:11would give <code>11 × 12 = 132</code>, and 13 would give <code>13 × 12 = 156</code>. Neither hits 144, so you can rule them out fast by multiplying back.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:22:56'),
(878, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> ✨</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up so well. Division asks a question: how many groups of 8 fit into 56? The fastest way to answer that is to flip it into a multiplication question, since division and multiplication are inverse operations.</p>\n\n<p>So instead of struggling with \"56 split by 8,\" you can ask yourself: <strong>8 times what equals 56?</strong> From the times tables, <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, so the quotient must be 7.</p>\n\n<p>You can always double-check a division answer using this trick:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer:7</li>\n<li>Multiply it by the divisor: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code></li>\n<li>You land back on the original number, so the division is exact.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick reasonableness check also fits here. 8 × 5 = 40 (too small) and 8 × 10 = 80 (too big), so the answer had to sit somewhere between 5 and 10. Landing on 7 feels right in that range.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on those times tables, they\'re the backbone of clean division.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:23:15'),
(879, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 15, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up: division asks how many equal groups fit into the total. So <code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"how many 25s fit inside 100?\" You can picture it as counting up in25s:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25, 50, 75, 100</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s four jumps to reach 100, which matches your answer.</p>\n\n<p>The cleanest way to confirm a division result is to use its inverse, multiplication. If<code>100 ÷ 25 = 4</code>, then <code>25 × 4</code> should give back 100. And it does: <code>25 × 4 = 100</code>. Perfect check.</p>\n\n<p>A handy mental trick for dividing by 25: think in quarters, since 25 is one quarter of 100. So dividing any multiple of 100 by 25 is the same as asking how many quarters fit. For example, <code>200 ÷ 25 = 8</code> because 200 is two hundreds, and each hundred holds four quarters.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"multiply to check\" habit. It\'ll save you every time division gets trickier.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:23:35'),
(880, 30, NULL, 492, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the right way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks: how many equal groups fit inside the total? So<code>20 ÷ 4</code> is really asking, \"how many groups of 4 fit into 20?\" or equivalently, \"4 times what equals 20?\"</p>\n\n<p>Since division and multiplication are inverse operations, you can flip the question into a multiplication fact you already know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>And you can always check by multiplying your answer back:</p>\n\n<pre><code>answer × divisor = total\n5 × 4 = 20 ✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options:4 would mean <code>4 × 4 = 16</code>, too small. 6 would mean <code>6 × 4 = 24</code>, too big. 10 would mean <code>10 × 4 = 40</code>, way too big. Only 5 lands exactly on 20.</p>\n\n<p>That habit of turning division into \"what times the divisor gives the total\" will carry you through every division question in this level.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:23:56'),
(881, 30, NULL, 493, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>81 ÷ 9 = 9</strong>, and you picked it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why this one is worth pausing on: division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin. Instead of thinking \"how do I split 81 into 9 piles,\" you can flip the question into something friendlier:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>9 times what number equals 81?</strong></li>\n<li>From your times tables: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code></li>\n<li>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That\'s the checking trick built right in. Whenever you finish a division, multiply your answer by the divisor and see if you land back on the original number. If <code>9 × 9</code> gave you 81, you know the quotient is correct.</p>\n\n<p>The other options fail this test quickly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 × 8 = 72</code>, not 81</li>\n<li><code>9 × 7 = 63</code>, not 81</li>\n<li><code>9 × 6 = 54</code>, not 81</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that multiplication-check habit. It\'ll save you on trickier divisions like <code>132 ÷ 11</code> where the answer isn\'t an instant recall.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:24:14'),
(882, 30, NULL, 494, 'a', NULL, 1, 40, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s a clean solve.<strong>144 ÷ 12 = 12</strong> is spot on.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the reasoning holds up: division asks how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total. So the real question behind <code>144 ÷ 12</code> is \"12 times what equals 144?\" Flip it into a multiplication check:</p>\n\n<pre><code>12 × 12 = 144</code></pre>\n\n<p>Since 12 twelves make exactly 144, the quotient must be 12. This is one of those facts worth locking in because12 × 12 shows up everywhere, it\'s the corner of the times table.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check on the other options so you can see why they don\'t fit:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 11 = 132</code>, too small for144</li>\n<li><code>12 × 13 = 156</code>, overshoots</li>\n<li><code>12 × 14 = 168</code>, way past</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Notice the pattern: each step up in the quotient adds another 12. That\'s the equal-groups idea in action, and it\'s exactly why multiplying your answer back by the divisor is such a reliable check. Keep using that habit and division stays predictable.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:24:31'),
(883, 30, NULL, 495, NULL, '7', 1, 40, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>56 ÷ 8 = 7</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up: division asks \"how many equal groups fit?\" So<code>56 ÷ 8</code> is really asking, \"8 times what equals 56?\" Since <code>8 × 7 = 56</code>, the quotient has to be 7. That inverse relationship between multiplication and division is the key idea for this whole level.</p>\n\n<p>A quick way to double-check yourself on any division problem:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Take your answer and multiply it by the divisor.</li>\n<li>If you land back on the original number, you nailed it.</li>\n<li>Example: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>. Matches. Done.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also think of it as splitting: 56 items shared into 8 equal groups puts 7 in each group. Same answer, different lens, both valid.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on your times tables here. The stronger those get, the faster division feels, because you\'re really just running multiplication backwards. Ready for a trickier one when you are.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:24:50'),
(884, 30, NULL, 496, NULL, '4', 1, 40, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. Division asks: how many equal groups of the divisor fit into the total? So<code>100 ÷ 25</code> is really asking, \"How many 25s fit inside 100?\" You can picture it as four quarters making a whole dollar, or four 25-point jumps landing exactly on 100:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25, 50, 75, 100. That\'s four jumps.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The reliable way to confirm any division answer is to flip it into multiplication, since they\'re inverse operations. Check:</p>\n\n<pre><code>4 × 25 = 100✓</code></pre>\n\n<p>Because that multiplication lands exactly on the original total, you know the division is exact with no remainder, which is what this level expects.</p>\n\n<p>A handy pattern to keep in your pocket: anything divided by 25 can be checked using the \"quarters of100\" idea, since 25 is one quarter of 100. So 200 ÷ 25 = 8, 75 ÷ 25 = 3, and so on. That mental shortcut will save you time when the boss battle mixes operations together.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:25:11'),
(885, 25, NULL, 375, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice one, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> is a perfectly valid Python variable name, and picking it means you\'ve internalized the naming rules already.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it works, and why the others don\'t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B) name_1</strong> — Starts with a letter, contains only letters, digits, and an underscore. All good.</li>\n<li><strong>A) 1name</strong> — Starts with a digit, which Python doesn\'t allow. Try it and you\'ll get a <code>SyntaxError</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>C) name-1</strong> — The hyphen is actually the minus operator in Python, so Python reads this as \"name minus 1\", not a variable name.</li>\n<li><strong>D) my name</strong> — Spaces aren\'t allowed in identifiers. Python would see two separate tokens and get confused.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The underlying rule to remember: a Python variable name can contain <strong>letters, digits, and underscores</strong>, but it<strong>cannot start with a digit</strong>, and it can\'t contain spaces or hyphens. Underscores are the standard way to separate words, which is why you\'ll see names like <code>user_age</code> or <code>total_score</code> everywhere in Python code. This style is called snake_case.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:48:04'),
(886, 25, NULL, 376, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on!<strong>3.14</strong> is a <code>float</code>, and you nailed why it matters.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the underlying idea: Python looks at the literal you write and picks a type automatically. The presence of a decimal point is the giveaway. Anything with a <code>.</code> in it, even something like <code>3.0</code>, is treated as a <code>float</code> (short for \"floating-point number\"). Whole numbers with no decimal, like <code>3</code> or <code>42</code>, are <code>int</code>. That\'s the key distinction between the two numeric types you\'ll use most.</p>\n\n<p>Quick way to confirm this yourself in Python:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\n\ny = 3\nprint(type(y))   # &lt;class \'int\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Just to round out the other options so they stick:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>str</code> is for text wrapped in quotes, like <code>\"3.14\"</code>. Notice that<code>\"3.14\"</code> in quotes would be a string, not a number.</li>\n<li><code>bool</code> is onlyever <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the rule of thumb: decimal point means float, no decimal means int.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:48:22'),
(887, 25, NULL, 377, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>array</strong> is the odd one out here.</p>\n\n<p>Python does not have a general-purpose <code>array</code> as a built-in everyday type. If you type <code>array</code> at the top of a fresh Python file, you\'ll get a <code>NameError</code>. There is an <code>array</code> module in the standard library, but you have to <code>import array</code> to use it, and it\'s mostly for low-level numeric data. Most Python programmers reach for a <code>list</code> instead, which is flexible and built right in.</p>\n\n<p>The other three are all first-class citizens you can use without importing anything:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> for whole numbers like <code>42</code></li>\n<li><code>list</code> for ordered collections like <code>[1, 2, 3]</code></li>\n<li><code>dict</code> for key-value pairs like <code>{\"name\": \"Aaron\"}</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The bigger idea to hold onto: when you hear \"array\" from a friend who codes in another language (C, Java, JavaScript), the Python equivalent is almost always a <code>list</code>. Same job, different name.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:48:36'),
(888, 25, NULL, 378, NULL, 'type', 1, 15, 7, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>type</code> is the built-in you reach for whenever you want Python to tell you what kind of value something is.</p>\n\n<p>The way it works: you pass any value or variable into it, and it hands back the class that value belongs to. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\nprint(type(\"hello\"))  # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\nprint(type(42))       # &lt;class \'int\'&gt;\nprint(type(True))     # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth tucking away:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>type</code> is a function, so you always call it with parentheses, like <code>type(x)</code>. Just writing <code>type</code> on its own gives you the function object itself, not a useful answer about your variable.</li>\n<li>Python figures out types automatically when you assign a value, which is why <code>type()</code> is so handy for confirming what Python decided. If you write <code>age = 21</code> versus <code>age = \"21\"</code>, they look similar but <code>type()</code> will show one is an <code>int</code> and the other a <code>str</code>, which matters a lot once you start doing math or comparisons.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Great instinct reaching for it.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:48:57'),
(889, 25, NULL, 379, NULL, 'none', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, you clearly understood the concept. You typed <code>none</code>, and since our quiz is checking the idea rather than being strict about capitalization, that counts. But here\'s the important nuance to lock in for real Python code.</p>\n\n<p>Python\'s \"nothing\" value is written as <strong>None</strong>, with a capital N. Python is case-sensitive, so <code>none</code>, <code>NONE</code>, and <code>None</code> are three different things to the interpreter. Only <code>None</code> is the real special value. If you type <code>none</code> in an actual program, you\'ll get a <code>NameError</code> because Python will try to look it up as a variable and won\'t find one.</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None\nprint(winner)   # None\n\nloser = none    # NameError: name \'none\' is not defined</code></pre>\n\n<p><code>None</code> is useful as a placeholder when you don\'t have a value yet, for example a game where no one has won, a search that hasn\'t found a result, or a function that intentionally returns nothing. You\'ll also see it as the default return value when a function has no <code>return</code> statement.</p>\n\n<p>So: right idea, just remember the capital N when you\'re writing real code.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:49:20'),
(890, 24, NULL, 464, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>20 ÷ 4 = 5</strong>, and you spotted it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why the method behind it matters. Division asks one of two questions:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>How many groups of 4 fit into 20?</li>\n<li>If I split 20 into 4 equal groups, how big is each group?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Both questions land on the same answer here. The fastest way to solve it is to flip it into a multiplication question: <em>what number times 4 gives me 20?</em> Since<code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, the quotient must be <strong>5</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>That inverse-operation trick is the heart of Level 4. Whenever you see something like <code>36 ÷ 6</code> or <code>72 ÷ 8</code>, ask yourself what times the divisor lands on the total. Your times tables carry most of the work.</p>\n\n<p>Quick sanity check you can always run: multiply your answer back by the divisor. <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. Matches the original total, so the split is exact with no remainder. That\'s what \"exact division\" means in this course.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:49:32'),
(891, 24, NULL, 465, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Close, but not quite. Picking <strong>B) 8</strong> suggests you were thinking of a nearby fact, maybe <code>9 × 8 = 72</code>. That\'s a solid times-table fact, just not the one that matches 81.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reliable way to handle division: turn it into a multiplication question. Ask yourself, <strong>\"9 times what equals 81?\"</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>9 × 7 = 63</code> — too small</li>\n<li><code>9 × 8 = 72</code> — still too small (this is where your answer landed)</li>\n<li><code>9 × 9 = 81</code> — that\'s the match</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So <code>81 ÷ 9 = 9</code>, which is option A.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea for Level 4: division and multiplication are inverse operations. Every time you see something like <code>81 ÷ 9</code>, you can flip it into <code>9 × ? = 81</code> and hunt for the missing factor. And you can always double-check by multiplying your answer back: <code>9 × 9 = 81</code>. If it lands on the original number, you\'re good.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:49:46'),
(892, 24, NULL, 466, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one is close but let\'s untangle it. You picked <strong>D) 13</strong>, which would mean that 12 fits into 144 exactly thirteen times. Let\'s test that with the multiplication check the course recommends: <code>12 × 13 = 156</code>. That\'s already past 144, so 13 groups of 12 is too many.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the cleanest way to think about <code>144 ÷ 12</code>. Division asks: <strong>what number times 12 gives 144?</strong> Let\'s walk the12 times table nearby:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>12 × 10 = 120</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 11 = 132</code></li>\n<li><code>12 × 12 = 144</code> ✅</li>\n<li><code>12 × 13 = 156</code> (too big)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So<code>144 ÷ 12 = 12</code>, which is option <strong>A</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy trick for next time: when you\'re unsure on a division question, multiply each answer choice by the divisor and see which one lands exactly on the total. That inverse check turns division into a multiplication problem you already know how to handle, and it catches \"off by one\" slips like this one.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:50:04'),
(893, 24, NULL, 467, NULL, '45', 0, 0, 9, '<p>No worries, this is a super common mix-up and easy to fix once you see it. Your answer of <strong>45</strong> looks like you may have been thinking about a multiplication fact instead of a division one, maybe something like 5 × 9 = 45. Close in feel, but it doesn\'t fit here because 45 has nothing to do with splitting 56 into groups of 8.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the tidy way to think about <code>56 ÷ 8</code>. Division asks: how many groups of 8 fit inside 56? The fastest route is to flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What number times 8 equals 56?</li>\n<li>8 × 5 = 40 (too small)</li>\n<li>8 × 6 = 48 (still too small)</li>\n<li>8 × 7 = 56 ✅</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So<code>56 ÷ 8 = 7</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You can always double-check a division answer by multiplying it back: 7 × 8 = 56, which matches the original total. That little reverse-check is your safety net whenever division feels shaky. Try leaning on your times tables first, and division becomes basically the same skill in reverse.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:50:25'),
(894, 24, NULL, 468, NULL, '78', 0, 0, 7, '<p>No worries, let\'s untangle this together. Your answer of <strong>78</strong> is quite a bit larger than what division here can give us, so something went sideways in the setup. A quick sanity check: if 100 ÷ 25 were 78, then 25 × 78 would need to equal 100, but 25 × 78 is actually 1,950. That mismatch tells us78 can\'t be right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean way to think about <code>100 ÷ 25</code>. Division asks: how many groups of 25 fit inside 100? So flip it into a multiplication question:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>25 × 1 = 25</li>\n<li>25 × 2 = 50</li>\n<li>25 × 3 = 75</li>\n<li>25 × 4 = 100 ✅</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Four groups of 25 fill up100 exactly, so <strong>100 ÷ 25 = 4</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy shortcut for dividing by 25: think in terms of quarters. Every 100 contains four25s, just like a dollar has four quarters. So 200 ÷ 25 = 8, 300 ÷ 25 = 12, and so on.</p>\n\n<p>Always check a division answer by multiplying it back by the divisor. If it doesn\'t return the original number, the answer needs another look.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:50:48'),
(895, 24, NULL, 464, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>C) 6</strong>. That would mean 4 groups of 6, but<code>4 × 6 = 24</code>, not 20. So 6 is a little too big to be the right split.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the trick with division: it\'s just multiplication in reverse. When you see <code>20 ÷ 4</code>,ask yourself:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\"4 times what equals 20?\"</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Walk up the 4 times table:</p>\n\n<pre><code>4 × 3 = 12\n4 × 4 = 16\n4 × 5 = 20  ✓\n4 × 6 = 24</code></pre>\n\n<p>There it is. <code>4 × 5 = 20</code>, so <code>20 ÷ 4 = 5</code>. The answer is <strong>A) 5</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>You can also picture it as splitting 20 items into 4 equal groups, each group gets 5. And you can always double-check by multiplying back: <code>5 × 4 = 20</code>. If it lands on the original number, you nailed it. Try that check trick on the next one and see how much steadier it feels.</p>', '2026-07-06 02:51:09'),
