(905, 25, NULL, 375, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> follows every rule Python cares about for variable names.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the quick reasoning behind why the other three fail, because knowing why the wrong ones are wrong is half the battle:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A) <code>1name</code></strong> starts with a digit. Python needs the first character to be a letter or an underscore, otherwise it can\'t tell a name apart from a number.</li>\n<li><strong>C) <code>name-1</code></strong> contains a hyphen, and Python reads <code>-</code> as the subtraction operator. So it would try to compute <code>name minus 1</code> instead of seeing one name.</li>\n<li><strong>D) <code>my name</code></strong> has a space, which Python treats as a separator between tokens. It would see two things, <code>my</code> and <code>name</code>, and get confused.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your answer <code>name_1</code> works because it starts with a letter, and the rest is just letters, digits, and an underscore, all of which are allowed. A handy way to remember the rule:</p>\n\n<pre><code>letters + digits + underscores, and never start with a digit</code></pre>\n\n<p>Bonus tip: names are case sensitive, so <code>name_1</code> and <code>Name_1</code> are two different variables.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:04:55'),
(906, 24, NULL, 459, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up. You picked <strong>36</strong>, which is actually <code>6 × 6</code>. It looks like your brain slid one step short on the six times table, landing on the neighbor instead of the correct fact.</p>\n\n<p>The right answer is <strong>42</strong>. Here\'s the reasoning:</p>\n\n<p><code>6 × 7</code> means six groups of seven, or seven groups of six. If memorizing the fact feels shaky, break it apart using easier pieces:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>6 × 7</code> = <code>(5 × 7) + (1 × 7)</code></li>\n<li><code>5 × 7= 35</code></li>\n<li><code>35 + 7 = 42</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Or count up the six times table in steps of 6: <code>6, 12, 18, 24, 30, 36, 42</code>. That seventh step lands on 42, and you can see 36 was just one jump too early.</p>\n\n<p>A handy check: multiplication is commutative, so <code>6 × 7</code> and <code>7 × 6</code> give the same product. If you know one, you know the other. Try to lock this fact in, it shows up constantly in bigger problems.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:05:22'),
(907, 25, NULL, 376, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on. <code>3.14</code> is a <strong>float</strong>, and you nailed why: any number with a decimal point in Python is treated as a floating-point number.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the underlying idea. Python looks at how you write the value and picks the type automatically:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>3</code> would be an <strong>int</strong> (whole number, no decimal point)</li>\n<li><code>3.14</code> is a <strong>float</strong> (has a decimal point, so it can hold fractional values)</li>\n<li><code>\"3.14\"</code> would be a <strong>str</strong> (quotes make it text, even though it looks like a number)</li>\n<li><code>True</code> or <code>False</code> would be a <strong>bool</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can always confirm this yourself with the <code>type()</code> function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>One neat thing to remember: even <code>3.0</code> is a float, not an int. It\'s the decimal point that decides, not whether there\'s anything after it. So<code>type(3)</code> gives <code>int</code>, but <code>type(3.0)</code> gives <code>float</code>. Small detail, but it trips people up later when doing math.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:05:22'),
(908, 25, NULL, 377, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s the right call. <code>array</code> is the odd one out here.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning: Python does have <code>int</code>, <code>list</code>, and <code>dict</code> available the moment you open the interpreter, no imports needed. You can just write:</p>\n\n<pre><code>numbers = [1, 2, 3]\nages = {\"Aaron\": 21}\ncount = 42</code></pre>\n\n<p>But <code>array</code> is not a built-in everyday type. Python does ship an <code>array</code> module in its standard library, but you\'d have to explicitly write <code>import array</code> to use it, and even then it\'s rarely needed. It only stores one specific numeric type at a time and exists mostly for low-level memory efficiency.</p>\n\n<p>For 99% of situations where a beginner from another language (like Java or C) reaches for an \"array,\" the Pythonic answer is a <strong>list</strong>. Lists are flexible:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>They can hold mixed types: <code>[1, \"hi\", True]</code></li>\n<li>They can grow and shrink</li>\n<li>They support indexing and slicing just like strings</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the takeaway: when you hear \"array\" in Python-land, mentally translate it to \"list.\" That\'s the built-in you\'ll actually reach for.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:05:38'),
(909, 25, NULL, 378, NULL, 'type', 1, 15, 4, '<p>Nice one, spot on! <strong>type</strong> is exactly the built-in you reach for when you want Python to tell you what kind of value something is.</p>\n\n<p>The way it works: you pass any value or variable into it, and it hands back the class that value belongs to. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\nprint(type(\"hello\"))  # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\nprint(type(42))       # &lt;class \'int\'&gt;\nprint(type(True))     # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Why this matters at the beginner stage: Python is dynamically typed, meaning you never declare a type up front. The interpreter infers it from the value you assign. That\'s convenient, but it also means bugs can sneak in when you think a variable holds an<code>int</code> and it\'s actually a <code>str</code> (a super common trap when reading user input, since <code>input()</code> always gives you a string).</p>\n\n<p>A couple of handy follow-ups you\'ll meet soon:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>type(x) == int</code> checks a type directly</li>\n<li><code>isinstance(x, int)</code> does the same thing but plays nicer with inheritance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For now, <code>type()</code> is your go-to inspector. Keep it in your back pocket for debugging.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:05:55'),
(910, 24, NULL, 459, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Nice try, and don\'t worry — this is one of the trickiest facts in the times tables, so you\'re in good company.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>36</strong>, which is actually <code>6 × 6</code>. It looks like you may have been one group of 6 short. That happens a lot with6s and 7s because they sit right next to each other in your memory.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s rebuild it using the \"break it apart\" idea from the lesson:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>6 × 7</code> means six groups of seven.</li>\n<li>Split it: <code>5 × 7 = 35</code>, then add one more 7.</li>\n<li><code>35 + 7 = 42</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Or flip it using commutativity — <code>6 × 7</code> is the same as <code>7 × 6</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Double 6 is12 (that\'s <code>6 × 2</code>).</li>\n<li>Triple that:<code>12 × 3 = 36</code>… wait, that\'s only <code>6 × 6</code>. Add one more 6 to get <code>42</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the answer is <strong>A) 42</strong>. A handy anchor: <code>6 × 7 = 42</code> is worth memorizing outright since it trips people up. Next time you\'re unsure, lean on <code>5 × 7 = 35</code> and add a7.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:06:14'),
(911, 25, NULL, 379, NULL, 'none', 1, 15, 9, '<p>Nice, you\'ve got the right concept locked in. Python\'s way of saying \"there\'s nothing here yet\" is indeed <code>None</code>. That\'s the placeholder you reach for when a variable exists but doesn\'t have a meaningful value assigned to it.</p>\n\n<p>Quick heads-up though, and this one matters once you start writing real code: Python is <strong>case-sensitive</strong>. The quiz accepted <code>none</code>, but the actual language will not. Try running this and you\'ll see:</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = none\n# NameError: name \'none\' is not defined\n\nwinner = None\nprint(winner)   # None</code></pre>\n\n<p>To Python, <code>none</code> looks like some variable you never created, so it throws an error. Only <code>None</code> with a capital N is the built-in \"no value.\" The same rule applies to <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>, which also need capital letters.</p>\n\n<p>Where you\'ll actually use <code>None</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Initializing a variable before you know its value: <code>winner = None</code></li>\n<li>As the default return when a function has no <code>return</code> statement</li>\n<li>Marking optional function parameters</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Just watch that capital N in your own code and you\'re set.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:06:15'),
(912, 34, NULL, 433, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why it holds up when you break it down by place value:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones column: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the 2, carry the 1 into the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens column: <code>1 + 2 = 3</code>, plus the carried 1 gives <code>4</code>.</li>\n<li>Put them together: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick estimation trick also confirms this. Round 15 up to 20 and 27 up to 30, and you get 50. The real sum should be a bit less, which lines up nicely with 42. That\'s a handy sanity check when the options are close together, like B) 40 and D) 41 in this question. Those \"off by one\" traps usually come from forgetting to carry the 1, so the fact that you caught it means your place-value habit is solid.</p>\n\n<p>Keep leaning on that \"ones first, then carry\" routine. It scales up beautifully when you hit three-digit sums later on.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:11:17'),
(913, 34, NULL, 434, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up. Picking <strong>55</strong> usually means the borrowing step got skipped. If you subtract each column without borrowing, you might end up doing <code>8 - 3 = 5</code> in the tens and something odd in the ones, which lands near 55. But that shortcut breaks the place-value rule.</p>\n\n<p>Here is the clean walk-through for <code>84 - 39</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up place values: 84 on top, 39 below.</li>\n<li>Ones column: <code>4 - 9</code>. Since4 is smaller than 9, you need to borrow.</li>\n<li>Borrow1 ten from the 8 tens. Now the tens digit becomes 7, and the ones become 14.</li>\n<li>Ones: <code>14 - 9 = 5</code>.</li>\n<li>Tens: <code>7 - 3 = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Answer: <strong>45</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick check with the inverse operation: <code>45 + 39</code> should give back84. Ones: <code>5 + 9 = 14</code>, carry 1. Tens: <code>4 + 3 + 1 = 8</code>. That is 84. Confirmed.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea: whenever the top digit is smaller than the bottom digit in a column, borrow before subtracting. Never flip the digits to make it easier.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:11:31');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(914, 34, NULL, 435, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>13 × 6 = 78</strong>, and you picked it cleanly.</p>\n\n<p>The reason this one trips people up is that 13 isn\'t a friendly times-table number, so the smart move is to break it apart using place value, exactly like the course suggests:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Split 13 into <code>10 + 3</code></li>\n<li>Multiply each part by 6: <code>10 × 6 = 60</code> and <code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Add the parts back together: <code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check with estimation. 13 is a bit more than 12, and <code>12 × 6 = 72</code>, so the answer should be just a little above 72. That instantly rules out 84 (too big) and confirms 78 fits.</p>\n\n<p>Notice how the wrong options are designed to catch specific slip-ups: 76 is what you\'d get if you added instead of carrying properly, 72 is the neighbouring fact <code>12 × 6</code>, and 84 is <code>14 × 6</code>. Knowing why the traps exist makes you faster on the boss battle.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:11:44'),
(915, 34, NULL, 436, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right.<strong>96 ÷ 8 = 12</strong>, and picking A shows you\'re thinking about division the smart way.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning that makes this click. Division asks: \"how many groups of 8 fit into 96?\" The fastest way to answer is to flip it into a multiplication question: <code>8 × ? = 96</code>. From there, you can break96 into friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>8 × 10 = 80</code></li>\n<li>That leaves <code>96 − 80 = 16</code></li>\n<li><code>8 × 2 = 16</code></li>\n<li>So <code>8 × (10 + 2) = 8 × 12 = 96</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That confirms the quotient is 12.</p>\n\n<p>You can also sanity-check by working backwards: <code>12 × 8</code>. Ten 8s make 80, two more 8s make 16, and 80 + 16 = 96. Everything lines up.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea to carry into the Boss Battle: whenever a division fact feels unfamiliar, turn it into \"what times the divisor gives me this total?\" It turns division into a multiplication puzzle you already know how to solve.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:11:57'),
(916, 34, NULL, 437, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>50</strong> is the answer, and more importantly, you handled the order of operations correctly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your reasoning fits the method:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Multiplication comes before subtraction, so <code>7 × 8</code> gets solved first.</li>\n<li><code>7 × 8 = 56</code>.</li>\n<li>Then subtract: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Notice how the trap answers were designed around common slip-ups. <strong>56</strong> would be what you\'d get if you stopped after multiplying and forgot the subtraction. <strong>62</strong> is what happens if someone reads the minus sign as a plus. And <strong>48</strong> is the classic left-to-right mistake: doing <code>7 × 8 - 6</code> as <code>7 × (8 - 6) = 7 × 2 = 14</code>... actually that gives 14, but a learner rushing might compute <code>8 - 6 = 2</code> first, then <code>7 × ... </code> and land on a wrong path. The point is, sticking to multiply-then-subtract keeps you safe.</p>\n\n<p>You underlined the operations mentally and picked the right sequence. That\'s the exact habit the Boss Battle rewards.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:12:08'),
(917, 34, NULL, 438, NULL, '27', 1, 20, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. You spotted the trap and handled it perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>The key here is that <strong>multiplication comes before addition</strong>, no matter which one appears first when you read left to right. So even though the <code>9+</code> shows up first, you don\'t touch it until the multiplication is done.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean walkthrough:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with <code>9 + 9 × 2</code></li>\n<li>Do the multiplication first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>9 + 18</code></li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick way to catch yourself on problems like this: before you calculate anything, scan the whole expression for <code>×</code> or <code>÷</code> symbols. If you see one, that piece gets solved first, and the rest waits its turn.</p>\n\n<p>The common trap answer here would have been <strong>36</strong>, which is what you get if you go strictly left to right (<code>9 + 9 = 18</code>, then <code>18 × 2 = 36</code>). You avoided it by respecting the order of operations. That\'s exactly the Boss Battle skill in action.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:12:23'),
(918, 34, NULL, 439, NULL, '30', 0, 0, 5, '<p>No worries, this is a classic order-of-operations trap and it\'s a great one to learn from. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>30</strong> looks like it came from doing20 - 5 = 15, and then somehow doubling to 30, or maybe multiplying instead of dividing. Either way, the ÷ 3 step got lost. That\'s the exact kind of slip the boss battle is designed to catch, so good news: you\'re already close.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the clean way through it:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Brackets first.</strong> <code>(20 - 5)</code> becomes <code>15</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Rewrite what\'s left</strong> so you don\'t lose track: <code>15 ÷ 3</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Divide.</strong> Ask yourself, \"3 times what equals 15?\" That\'s <code>5</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the answer is <strong>5</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea: brackets always go first, no matter what operations sit outside them. After each step, rewrite the expression on a fresh line. It feels slower, but it stops your brain from mixing up numbers mid-problem, which is exactly what happened here.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:12:42'),
(919, 34, NULL, 440, NULL, '5', 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips a lot of people up. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>Your answer of <strong>5</strong> looks like what you\'d get if you worked strictly left to right and treated everything as one running calculation, maybe something like <code>6 + 4 = 10</code>, then <code>10 - 12 = -2</code>… it\'s hard to land exactly on 5 without a mix-up somewhere. The key point is that left-to-right isn\'t the rule here.</p>\n\n<p>Order of operations says multiplication and division happen <strong>before</strong> addition and subtraction. So tackle it in stages:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Multiply first: <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Divide next: <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Now the expression is <code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Add last: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A handy trick: before calculating, underline the × and ÷ parts and solve those first, then rewrite the expression with just the results. That way you never lose track. Think of × and ÷ as forming little \"packages\" that resolve before the + and − step in.</p>', '2026-07-06 05:12:54'),
(920, 19, NULL, 260, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 14, '<p>Nice one, that\'s exactly right.<code>s[0]</code> gives you <code>\'h\'</code>, the first character of <code>\"hello\"</code>.</p>\n\n<p>The key idea here is <strong>indexing</strong>. In Python, strings are sequences of characters, and every character has a position number starting from <strong>zero</strong>, not one. So for <code>\"hello\"</code>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>s[0]</code> is <code>\'h\'</code></li>\n<li><code>s[1]</code> is <code>\'e\'</code></li>\n<li><code>s[2]</code> is <code>\'l\'</code></li>\n<li><code>s[3]</code> is <code>\'l\'</code></li>\n<li><code>s[4]</code> is <code>\'o\'</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The square brackets <code>[]</code> are Python\'s syntax for accessing an item by position. That\'s why the other options don\'t work:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>s(0)</code> uses parentheses, which Python reads as trying to <em>call</em> the string like a function.</li>\n<li><code>s.first()</code> looks reasonable but there\'s simply no <code>.first()</code> method on strings.</li>\n<li><code>s{0}</code> uses curly braces, which are for sets and dicts, not indexing.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Bonus trick: you can also count from the end with negatives. <code>s[-1]</code> gives you <code>\'o\'</code>, the last character. Handy when you don\'t know the length.</p>', '2026-07-07 06:56:52'),
(921, 19, NULL, 261, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, '<p>Looks like you didn\'t lock in an answer this time, so it got marked wrong by default. No stress, let\'s lock the concept in so it\'s automatic next round.</p>\n\n<p>The correct choice is <strong>B) .upper()</strong>. In Python, string methods are called with dot notation right after the string (or a variable holding one), and <code>.upper()</code> returns a new string with every letter converted to uppercase.</p>\n\n<pre><code>shout = \"hello\".upper()\nprint(shout)   # HELLO\n\nname = \"alice\"\nprint(name.upper())   # ALICE</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick tour of why the others don\'t fit:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>.capital()</code> isn\'t a real method. You might be thinking of <code>.capitalize()</code>, which only uppercases the first letter.</li>\n<li><code>.toUpper()</code> is the style used in JavaScript and Java (<code>toUpperCase</code>). Python prefers short, lowercase names.</li>\n<li><code>.uppercase()</code> sounds right but simply doesn\'t exist in Python.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>One thing worth remembering: strings are immutable, so <code>.upper()</code> does not change the original string. It hands you back a new one. If you want to keep it, assign it: <code>name = name.upper()</code>.</p>', '2026-07-07 06:57:16'),
(922, 19, NULL, 262, 'a', NULL, 1, 10, 4, '<p>Nice one, you nailed it.<code>\"abc\" + \"123\"</code> gives you <strong>\"abc123\"</strong>, exactly as you picked.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the concept underneath it: the <code>+</code> operator in Python is overloaded, meaning it behaves differently depending on the types on either side of it. When both sides are numbers, it adds them. When both sides are strings, it performs <strong>concatenation</strong>, which just means \"glue these two sequences of characters together, end to end.\"</p>\n\n<p>A few things worth locking in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>No space or separator gets inserted between the pieces. That\'s why option B was wrong, there\'s no hidden space.</li>\n<li><code>\"123\"</code> here is a string, not the number 123. The quotes matter. That\'s why the result isn\'t 124 or any kind of math.</li>\n<li>If you mix types, like <code>\"abc\" + 123</code>, Python actually does raise a <code>TypeError</code>. You\'d have to convert first: <code>\"abc\" + str(123)</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also check the length afterwards to confirm what got built:</p>\n<pre><code>combined = \"abc\" + \"123\"\nprint(len(combined))   # 6</code></pre>\n\n<p>Solid instinct. Keep that mental model of \"same operator, different behavior by type\" handy, it comes up a lot.</p>', '2026-07-07 06:57:31'),
(923, 19, NULL, 263, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people coming from other languages. Your pick, <code>s.last(3)</code>, looks reasonable because it reads almost like English, but Python strings simply don\'t have a <code>.last()</code> method. If you ran it, you\'d get an <strong>AttributeError</strong>. Python\'s string toolkit includes things like <code>.upper()</code>, <code>.strip()</code>, <code>.replace()</code>, and <code>.split()</code>, but grabbing a range of characters is done with slicing, not a method call.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) s[-3:]</strong>. Here\'s the reasoning:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Negative indexes count from the end, so <code>-1</code> is the last character, <code>-2</code> the second-to-last, and <code>-3</code> the third-from-last.</li>\n<li>The slice syntax is <code>s[start:end]</code>. Leaving <code>end</code> empty means \"go all the way to the end.\"</li>\n<li>So <code>s[-3:]</code> means \"start 3 from the end, go to the end\" which gives <code>\'ing\'</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick check on the others: <code>s[3:]</code> gives <code>\'gramming\'</code> (everything from index 3 onward), and <code>s[3:-1]</code> gives <code>\'grammin\'</code> because the end index is excluded. Slicing is your go-to tool anytime you want a chunk of a string.</p>', '2026-07-07 06:57:51'),
(924, 19, NULL, 264, NULL, 'FWF', 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one\'s a quick fix. Your answer <code>FWF</code> doesn\'t map to anything in Python — it looks like a slip rather than a misunderstanding, so let\'s lock in the real answer.</p>\n\n<p>The function you want is <strong>len</strong>. It\'s a built-in, meaning it\'s always available without importing anything, and it returns the number of items in a sequence. For a string, that means the number of characters (including spaces and punctuation).</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s it in action:</p>\n\n<pre><code>word = \"python\"\nprint(len(word))# 6\n\ngreeting = \"Hi there!\"\nprint(len(greeting))    # 9  (the space and! count too)\n\nprint(len(\"\"))          # 0  (empty string)</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth knowing:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>len</code> isn\'t a method, so you don\'t write <code>word.len()</code> — you pass the string into it: <code>len(word)</code>.</li>\n<li>It works on other sequences too, like lists: <code>len([1, 2, 3])</code> gives <code>3</code>. So once you meet lists later, this same function carries over.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Try it on your own name and see what number you get.</p>', '2026-07-07 06:58:20'),
(925, 19, NULL, 260, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 0, '<p>No worries, this is a super common mix-up when you\'re getting started. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <code>s{0}</code>. In Python, curly braces <code>{ }</code> aren\'t used for grabbing characters from a string. You\'ll actually see them in two other places: building sets and dictionaries (like <code>{\"a\": 1}</code>), and inside f-strings to insert values (like <code>f\"Hi {name}\"</code>). So <code>s{0}</code> looks reasonable, but Python will just throw a syntax error.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) s[0]</strong>. Here\'s the idea:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Strings are sequences of characters, and each character has a position called an <strong>index</strong>.</li>\n<li>Python is <strong>zero-indexed</strong>, meaning the first character is at position <code>0</code>, not <code>1</code>.</li>\n<li>You access a character using<strong>square brackets</strong>: <code>s[i]</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So for <code>s = \"hello\"</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>s[0]  # \'h\'\ns[1]  # \'e\'\ns[-1] # \'o\'  (negative indexes count from the end)</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick way to remember: parentheses <code>( )</code> call functions, curly braces <code>{ }</code> build sets/dicts, and square brackets <code>[ ]</code> reach into a sequence.</p>', '2026-07-07 06:58:43'),
(926, 19, NULL, 280, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, so let\'s clear it up together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>float</strong>, which in Python means a decimal number like <code>3.14</code> or <code>1.75</code>. So your answer was saying that <code>True</code> is a decimal number, but<code>True</code> doesn\'t have a decimal point or any numeric look to it at all, so <code>float</code> isn\'t the right fit.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>bool</strong> (short for boolean). A boolean is Python\'s yes/no, on/off type, and it only ever has two possible values: <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>. You\'ll use booleans constantly once you start writing <code>if</code> statements, because every condition you check (like <code>age &gt;= 18</code>) evaluates to either <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>.</p>\n\n<p>You can always confirm a type yourself with <code>type()</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>print(type(True))   # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;\nprint(type(3.14))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick way to remember the four basics:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers</li>\n<li><code>float</code> — decimals</li>\n<li><code>str</code> — text in quotes</li>\n<li><code>bool</code> — <code>True</code> or <code>False</code></li>\n</ul>', '2026-07-07 15:43:36'),
(927, 19, NULL, 281, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this one trips up almost everyone coming from another language. You picked <strong>D) elsif</strong>, which is actually the keyword used in Ruby and Perl — so if you\'ve seen it before, that\'s probably why it felt familiar. Python just spells it differently.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) elif</strong>. It\'s a squished-together shortcut for \"else if,\" and Python\'s designers chose it to keep the keyword short and the indentation tidy. The other options are all valid in some language, just not this one:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>elseif</code> — used in PHP and Lua</li>\n<li><code>else if</code> — used in C, Java, JavaScript (two separate words)</li>\n<li><code>elsif</code> — Ruby and Perl (your pick)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Here\'s how it looks in action:</p>\n\n<pre><code>score = 75\nif score &gt;= 90:\n    grade = \"A\"\nelif score &gt;= 75:\n    grade = \"B\"\nelse:\n    grade = \"F\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>You can chain as many <code>elif</code> branches as you need between the opening <code>if</code> and the final <code>else</code>. Python checks each condition top to bottom and runs the first one that\'s true.</p>', '2026-07-07 15:47:21'),
(928, 19, NULL, 280, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 0, NULL, '2026-07-07 16:22:28'),
