(936, 1, NULL, 2, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of folks starting out. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <code>my name</code>, which reads perfectly fine to a human, but Python sees that space in the middle and gets confused. To Python, a space separates things, so it would think <code>my</code> and <code>name</code> are two different words rather than one variable. That\'s why spaces aren\'t allowed in variable names.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) name_1</strong>. Here\'s the quick rulebook for naming variables in Python:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Letters, digits, and underscores only</li>\n<li>Cannot start with a digit (so <code>1name</code> is out)</li>\n<li>No spaces (rules out <code>my name</code>)</li>\n<li>No hyphens either, because Python reads <code>-</code> as the minus operator (so <code>name-1</code> would look like \"name minus 1\")</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That leaves <code>name_1</code> as the only valid option: it starts with a letter, and the underscore is the standard way to glue words together in Python names, like <code>is_student</code> or <code>first_name</code>.</p>\n\n<p>A handy mental check: if you can imagine Python mistaking your name for math or two separate things, it probably won\'t fly.</p>', '2026-07-07 19:36:21'),
(937, 25, NULL, 375, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 15, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people because the rules feel a bit arbitrary at first. Let\'s walk through each option so the pattern clicks.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A) <code>1name</code></strong> — invalid. Variable names cannot start with a digit. Python needs to tell numbers and names apart, and anything starting with a digit looks like a number to it.</li>\n<li><strong>C) <code>name-1</code></strong> — invalid. The hyphen is actually the minus operator in Python, so Python reads this as <code>name - 1</code> (subtract 1 from a variable called <code>name</code>).</li>\n<li><strong>D) <code>my name</code></strong> — invalid. Spaces separate tokens in Python, so it sees two things: <code>my</code> and <code>name</code>, not one variable.</li>\n<li><strong>B) <code>name_1</code></strong> — valid. It uses only letters, digits, and an underscore, and it starts with a letter. Underscores are the standard way to join words in Python variable names (this style is called snake_case).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The rule to remember: letters, digits, and underscores only, and never start with a digit. So<code>user_2</code>, <code>total_score</code>, and <code>_temp</code> all work, but <code>2user</code> or <code>total-score</code> do not.</p>', '2026-07-08 03:45:03'),
(938, 25, NULL, 400, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 20, '<p>No worries, this one trips people up because it looks like it could be a few things. Let me walk you through it.</p>\n\n<p>You didn\'t actually pick an option this time, so let\'s break down what each one would have meant:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> is for whole numbers like <code>42</code> or <code>-7</code></li>\n<li><code>str</code> is for text wrapped in quotes like <code>\"True\"</code> — note the quotes matter</li>\n<li><code>float</code> is for decimal numbers like <code>3.14</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) bool</strong>. A boolean (bool) represents one of exactly two values: <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>. Python uses booleans anywhere you need a yes/no or on/off answer, which is why they power every <code>if</code> statement you write.</p>\n\n<p>You can confirm it yourself:</p>\n\n<pre><code>print(type(True))   # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>One sneaky detail: notice <code>True</code> has no quotes around it. If it were <code>\"True\"</code> with quotes, that would be a string. The capital T also matters, lowercase <code>true</code> would give you an error. Give it a try in an editor and see what<code>type(False)</code> returns too.</p>', '2026-07-08 03:46:30'),
(939, 25, NULL, 401, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up almost everyone who\'s used another language first. Your answer, <code>else if</code>, is exactly how you\'d write it in JavaScript, C, or Java, so your instinct isn\'t wrong, it\'s just wearing the wrong outfit for Python.</p>\n\n<p>In Python, the keyword is<strong>elif</strong>, which is a squished-together version of \"else if.\" Python\'s designers wanted the language to stay short and readable, so they merged the two words into one keyword. If you type <code>else if</code> in Python, you\'ll get a <code>SyntaxError</code> because Python sees <code>else</code> as its own keyword and then doesn\'t know what to do with a stray <code>if</code> on the same line.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the shape to memorize:</p>\n\n<pre><code>score = 75\nif score &gt;= 90:\n    grade = \"A\"\nelif score &gt;= 75:\n    grade = \"B\"\nelse:\n    grade = \"F\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick mental checklist for the chain:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>if</code> starts it</li>\n<li><code>elif</code> adds more checks (as many as you want)</li>\n<li><code>else</code> catches everything left over</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The other two options, <code>elseif</code> and <code>elsif</code>, belong to other languages too (PHP andRuby/Perl). Python picked <code>elif</code> and stuck with it.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:00:35'),
(940, 25, NULL, 402, 'b', NULL, 1, 15, 6, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>while</strong> is Python\'s condition-controlled loop, it keeps running its block over and over as long as the condition at the top evaluates to true.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the mental model: every time Python reaches the top of the loop, it re-checks the condition. If it\'s still true, the body runs once more. The moment it becomes false, Python skips past the loop and moves on.</p>\n\n<pre><code>count = 0\nwhile count &lt; 3:\n    print(\"hello\")\n    count += 1</code></pre>\n\n<p>Quick tour of why the others don\'t fit:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>for</code> exists in Python, but it iterates over a sequence (a list, a range, a string), not \"while a condition holds.\"</li>\n<li><code>repeat</code> and <code>foreach</code> aren\'t Python keywords at all. You\'ll see them in other languages, but Python sticks with just <code>for</code> and <code>while</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>One trap worth remembering: if the variable in your condition never changes inside the loop, the condition stays true forever and you get an infinite loop. That\'s why the <code>count += 1</code> line above matters so much, it\'s what eventually makes the condition false.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:00:58'),
(941, 25, NULL, 403, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 3, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners, especially if you\'ve seen other languages first. You picked <code>function</code>, which is a very reasonable guess. JavaScript actually uses that exact keyword, so if you\'ve peeked at any web code, your brain naturally reaches for it. But Python doesn\'t recognize <code>function</code> as anything special. If you tried to run it, Python would just see an unknown name and raise a <strong>SyntaxError</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) def</strong>, short for \"define.\" Python\'s designers wanted the language to feel light and readable, so many keywords are shortened: <code>def</code> for define, <code>elif</code> for else-if, and so on.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the shape to remember:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def greet(name):\n    print(f\"Hello, {name}!\")\n\ngreet(\"Aaron\")   # Hello, Aaron!\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>A quick way to lock it in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>def</code> starts the definition</li>\n<li>then the function name</li>\n<li>then parentheses with any parameters</li>\n<li>then a colon, and the body indented below</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Say it out loud once: \"def greet, colon.\" That rhythm will stick.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:01:10'),
(942, 25, NULL, 404, NULL, 'end', 0, 0, 6, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people coming from other languages or from plain English intuition. Your answer <code>end</code> makes total sense as a guess since \"end the loop\" is exactly what you\'re trying to do, but <code>end</code> isn\'t actually a Python keyword. If you typed it inside a loop, Python would treat it as an undefined variable name and raise a <code>NameError</code>.</p>\n\n<p>The keyword you want is <strong>break</strong>. When Python hits <code>break</code> inside a loop, it immediately exits the loop entirely, skipping any remaining iterations. Here\'s the pattern:</p>\n\n<pre><code>for i in range(10):\n    if i == 5:\n        break\n    print(i)\n# prints 0 1 2 3 4, then stops</code></pre>\n\n<p>It\'s worth knowing its cousin too:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>break</code> stops the loop completely</li>\n<li><code>continue</code> skips just the current iteration and moves to the next one</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick way to remember: think of <code>break</code> as \"break out of\" the loop, like breaking out of a room. Next time you see a loop that should stop when some condition is met, <code>break</code> is your tool.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:01:32'),
(943, 25, NULL, 405, NULL, 'str', 0, 0, 10, '<p>No worries, this one trips people up because <code>str</code> feels like it should be related to strings, and it is, just not in this context. <code>str</code> is actually the name of Python\'s string <strong>type</strong>. You\'d see it when you run something like <code>type(\"hello\")</code> and get back <code>&lt;class \'str\'&gt;</code>, or when you convert a number to text with <code>str(42)</code>. So your answer points to strings in general, but not to the special formatting feature the question was asking about.</p>\n\n<p>The prefix the question wants is the single letter <strong>f</strong>. You place it directly before the opening quote, and it turns the string into an <strong>f-string</strong> (short for \"formatted string\"). Anything inside curly braces <code>{ }</code> then gets evaluated and dropped into the text:</p>\n\n<pre><code>name = \"Aaron\"\nage = 21\nprint(f\"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.\")\n# My name is Aaron and I am 21 years old.</code></pre>\n\n<p>Without the <code>f</code>, Python treats <code>{name}</code> as literal characters and prints the braces exactly as written. The<code>f</code> is what flips the switch and tells Python \"evaluate the stuff in braces.\"</p>', '2026-07-08 04:01:55'),
(944, 25, NULL, 406, NULL, 'import', 0, 0, 14, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners because both words feel \"official\" and Python-y. Let\'s untangle them.</p>\n\n<p><code>import</code> is the keyword you use to <strong>bring outside code into your program</strong>, like pulling in a library someone else wrote:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import math\nprint(math.sqrt(16))   # 4.0</code></pre>\n\n<p>So<code>import</code> is about<em>getting things in</em>, not sending things out. That\'s why it doesn\'t fit here.</p>\n\n<p>The keyword you were after is <code>return</code>. When a function finishes its work, <code>return</code> hands a value back to whoever called it, so the caller can use it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def square(n):\n    return n * n\n\nresult = square(4)   # result is now 16\nprint(result)</code></pre>\n\n<p>A couple of things worth locking in:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>If you forget <code>return</code>, the function silently gives back <code>None</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Printing is not returning.</strong> <code>print(n * n)</code> shows the value on screen but doesn\'t hand it back, so <code>result = square(4)</code> would end up as <code>None</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Quick way to remember: <code>import</code> pulls code<em>in</em>, <code>return</code> sends a value <em>out</em>.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:02:18'),
(945, 25, NULL, 376, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <strong>3.14</strong> is a <code>float</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning behind it. In Python, any number that has a decimal point is treated as a <code>float</code>, short for \"floating-point number.\" The decimal is the giveaway. Even something like <code>3.0</code> is a float, not an int, purely because of that dot.</p>\n\n<p>Quick tour of why the other options don\'t fit:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> is for whole numbers with no decimal, like <code>42</code> or <code>-7</code>.</li>\n<li><code>str</code> is for text wrapped in quotes, like <code>\"3.14\"</code>. That would look identical when printed but behaves totally differently. You couldn\'t do math with it.</li>\n<li><code>bool</code> is just <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you ever want to double-check a value\'s type yourself, Python gives you a built-in tool for it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Handy trick to remember when you\'re experimenting and something isn\'t behaving how you\'d expect. Often it\'s a type mismatch hiding in plain sight.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:12:10'),
(946, 25, NULL, 377, 'c', NULL, 1, 10, 2, '<p>Nice work, you nailed it. <strong>array</strong> is the odd one out. Python does have an <code>array</code> module in its standard library, but you have to explicitly <code>import array</code> to use it, and it\'s rarely the right tool for everyday code. It only holds numeric values of a single type, so it feels more like a specialized container than a general-purpose data type.</p>\n\n<p>The other three are all built right into the language,ready to use without importing anything:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> — whole numbers like <code>42</code></li>\n<li><code>list</code> — an ordered, flexible collection like <code>[1, \"hi\", True]</code></li>\n<li><code>dict</code> — key-value pairs like <code>{\"name\": \"Aaron\", \"age\": 21}</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The course material hinted at exactly this trap: when beginners reach for an \"array\" in Python, what they actually want is a <strong>list</strong>. Lists can hold mixed types, grow and shrink freely, and support slicing just like strings do.</p>\n\n<p>Quick way to double-check any type yourself:</p>\n\n<pre><code>print(type([1, 2, 3]))   # &lt;class \'list\'&gt;\nprint(type({\"a\": 1}))# &lt;class \'dict\'&gt;</code></pre>', '2026-07-08 04:12:23'),
(947, 25, NULL, 378, NULL, 'type', 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice one, that\'s spot on. <code>type</code> is exactly the built-in you reach for when you want to know what kind of value a variable is holding.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the idea behind it: Python is dynamically typed, meaning you never declare a variable\'s type up front. Python figures it out from whatever value you assign. That\'s convenient, but it also means sometimes you need to peek inside and check. That\'s where <code>type()</code> comes in.</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\n\nname = \"Aaron\"\nprint(type(name))     # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\n\nis_ready = True\nprint(type(is_ready)) # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>Notice the output looks like <code>&lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code> rather than just <code>float</code>. That\'s because every type in Python is actually a class under the hood, but for now you can read it as \"this variable is a float.\"</p>\n\n<p>A little bonus for later: there\'s also <code>isinstance(x, int)</code>, which returns <code>True</code> or <code>False</code> and is often the more practical tool when you want to make a decision based on a type. But for simply inspecting what you\'ve got, <code>type()</code> is the go-to.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:12:38'),
(948, 25, NULL, 379, NULL, 'none', 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, you clearly know the concept. Python uses <code>None</code> to mean \"no value yet\" or \"nothing here.\" Your answer got accepted because the quiz was lenient about capitalization, but there\'s an important detail worth locking in now.</p>\n\n<p>In actual Python code, <strong>the capital N matters</strong>. Python is case-sensitive, so <code>None</code>, <code>none</code>, and <code>NONE</code> are three different things:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>None</code> is the real built-in value.</li>\n<li><code>none</code> would just be treated as a variable name Python has never heard of, and you\'d get a <code>NameError</code>.</li>\n<li><code>NONE</code> would fail the same way.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You\'ll see <code>None</code> most often as a placeholder before a real value shows up:</p>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None\nif winner is None:\n    print(\"No winner yet\")</code></pre>\n\n<p>Small tip: when checking for None, the idiomatic way is <code>x is None</code> rather than <code>x == None</code>. Both usually work, but <code>is</code> is what experienced Python developers use, since there\'s only ever one <code>None</code> object in memory.</p>', '2026-07-08 04:12:49'),
(949, 34, NULL, 553, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 3, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>42</strong> is exactly right.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why your answer holds up. When you stack the numbers by place value, you handle the ones column first, then the tens:</p>\n\n<pre><code>  15\n+ 27\n----\n</code></pre>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Ones: <code>5 + 7 = 12</code>. Write down the <strong>2</strong> and carry the <strong>1</strong> to the tens column.</li>\n<li>Tens: <code>1 + 2 + 1 (carried) = 4</code>. Write down the <strong>4</strong>.</li>\n<li>Result: <strong>42</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That carry step is the part most people trip over, so the fact that you handled it cleanly is a good sign. A quick sanity check also works nicely here: 15 is close to 15, and 27 is close to 25, so you\'d expect something near 40. Getting 42 lands right in that estimate zone, which tells you the answer is reasonable.</p>\n\n<p>Notice how option B (40) would be what you get if you forgot the carry, and C (52) would be adding an extra ten by mistake. You avoided both traps.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:08:51'),
(950, 34, NULL, 554, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 2, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>84 − 39 = 45</strong>, and this one has a little borrowing trick baked into it, so getting it right means you handled place value correctly.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reasoning laid out cleanly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Line up the place values: 84 on top, 39 underneath.</li>\n<li>Ones column: 4 − 9 doesn\'t work directly, so borrow 1 ten from the 8. Now the tens digit becomes 7, and the ones become 14.</li>\n<li>Ones: <code>14 − 9 = 5</code>.</li>\n<li>Tens: <code>7 − 3 = 4</code>.</li>\n<li>Put them together: <strong>45</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A neat mental-math shortcut for this one: 39 is close to 40. So think<code>84 − 40 = 44</code>, then add 1 back (because you subtracted one too many) to get <strong>45</strong>. Same answer, less borrowing.</p>\n\n<p>You can also double-check with the opposite operation: <code>45 + 39</code> should return you to 84. Ones: 5 + 9 = 14, carry 1. Tens: 4 + 3 + 1 = 8. That gives 84. Confirmed.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:09:06'),
(951, 34, NULL, 555, 'a', NULL, 1, 15, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s spot on.<strong>13 × 6 = 78</strong>, and the cleanest way to get there is exactly the splitting strategy from Level 3.</p>\n\n<p>Break 13 into friendlier parts, then multiply each piece:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>10 × 6 = 60</code></li>\n<li><code>3 × 6 = 18</code></li>\n<li><code>60 + 18 = 78</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This works because multiplication distributes over addition. Instead of memorizing 13 × 6 as one fact, you\'re leaning on two facts you already know from the times tables and stitching them together. That\'s a huge skill for the Boss Battle, since you\'ll often meet numbers bigger than 12.</p>\n\n<p>A quick sanity check also rules out the other options. Since 13 is a bit more than 12, and<code>12 × 6 = 72</code>, the answer must be slightly larger than 72, which knocks out C. And 6 × 13 has to be even (any number times 6 is even), so odd-looking traps aside, 78 fits perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>Carry this splitting habit into the mixed problems ahead. It keeps mental math accurate under pressure.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:09:20'),
(952, 34, NULL, 556, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Close call, but not quite. Your answer of <strong>11</strong> would mean that8 groups of 11 make 96. Let\'s test that: <code>8 × 11 = 88</code>. That\'s 8 short of 96, so 11 can\'t be the right quotient.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the reliable way to handle division: turn it into a multiplication question. Ask yourself,<em>\"8 times what equals 96?\"</em></p>\n\n<p>You can break96 into friendly parts:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><code>8 × 10 = 80</code></li>\n  <li>96 − 80 = 16left over</li>\n  <li><code>8 × 2 = 16</code></li>\n  <li>So<code>8 × (10 + 2) = 8 × 12 = 96</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That means <code>96 ÷ 8 = 12</code>, which is option A.</p>\n\n<p>A quick check confirms it: <code>12 × 8 = 96</code>. Perfect match. The big idea here is that division and multiplication are two sides of the same coin, so whenever a division fact feels shaky, rebuild it from a multiplication fact you already trust.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:09:36'),
(953, 34, NULL, 557, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 6, '<p>No worries, this is one of the classic boss-battle traps. Your answer of <strong>56</strong> is actually the result of just <code>7 × 8</code> on its own. It looks like you stopped after the multiplication step and didn\'t apply the <code>- 6</code> at the end.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s the full reasoning using order of operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Scan the expression: <code>7 × 8 - 6</code>. There are no brackets, so look for multiplication or division first.</li>\n<li>Do the multiplication: <code>7 × 8 = 56</code>.</li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left so you don\'t lose track: <code>56 - 6</code>.</li>\n<li>Now do the subtraction: <code>56 - 6 = 50</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the correct answer is <strong>A) 50</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>A good habit for the boss battle: after you finish a multiplication or division step, rewrite the whole expression with that piece replaced. That way the leftover <code>- 6</code> can\'t sneak past you. Estimation helps too. Since <code>7 × 8</code> is in the fifties and you\'re subtracting a small number, the answer should be a little below56, not 56 itself.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:09:56'),
(954, 34, NULL, 558, NULL, '27', 1, 20, 5, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. You spotted the trap and handled it like a pro.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s why<strong>27</strong> is correct. When an expression mixes addition and multiplication, multiplication always goes first, no matter which operation appears earlier when you read left to right.</p>\n\n<p>Walking through it one step at a time:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with the expression: <code>9 + 9 × 2</code></li>\n<li>Do the multiplication first: <code>9 × 2 = 18</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>9 + 18</code></li>\n<li>Now add: <code>9 + 18 = 27</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The classic mistake here is going strictly left to right and computing <code>9 + 9 = 18</code>, then <code>18 × 2 = 36</code>. That answer feels natural but ignores the order-of-operations rule that multiplication outranks addition.</p>\n\n<p>A good habit for boss-battle problems: before you calculate anything, scan the expression and underline the multiplication or division signs. Those get handled first, then addition and subtraction clean up whatever\'s left. You clearly have that instinct working.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:10:14'),
(955, 34, NULL, 559, NULL, '15', 0, 0, 4, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of people, and your answer actually tells me exactly where things went sideways. You wrote <strong>15</strong>, which is the result of just the bracket part: <code>20 - 5 = 15</code>. It looks like the division step got skipped along the way.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s walk it through together using the order of operations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Brackets first: <code>(20 - 5)</code> becomes <code>15</code>.</li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left so you don\'t lose track: <code>15 ÷ 3</code>.</li>\n<li>Now divide: ask yourself, \"3 times what equals 15?\" Since <code>3 × 5 = 15</code>, the answer is <code>5</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the final answer is <strong>5</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>The big idea here: brackets are step one, not the whole problem. After you solve inside them, the expression usually still has more work to do. A handy habit is to rewrite the expression on a new line after each step, like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>(20 - 5) ÷ 3\n= 15 ÷ 3\n= 5</code></pre>\n\n<p>That way your eyes always land on what\'s left to solve.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:10:31'),
(956, 34, NULL, 560, NULL, '27', 0, 0, 3, '<p>Close, but not quite. Your answer of <strong>27</strong> tells me you likely handled the multiplication and division correctly, but then something slipped in the final addition step. Let\'s walk through it together.</p>\n\n<p>The expression mixes multiplication, division, and addition, so order of operations is the key. Multiplication and division come first, left to right, then addition last.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Start with <code>6 × 4 = 24</code></li>\n<li>Then <code>12 ÷ 2 = 6</code></li>\n<li>Rewrite what\'s left: <code>24 + 6</code></li>\n<li>Add: <code>24 + 6 = 30</code></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you got 27, you may have added <code>24 + 3</code> by mistake, perhaps dividing 12 by 4 instead of 2, or you added <code>21 + 6</code> somewhere along the way. Either way, the fix is the same trick: after you finish the multiplication and division,<strong>rewrite the expression on a fresh line</strong> before adding. That tiny habit stops small copy errors from turning into wrong final answers.</p>\n\n<p>The correct result is <strong>30</strong>.</p>', '2026-07-08 08:10:45'),
(957, 1, NULL, 2, 'b', NULL, 1, 10, 1, '<p>Nice work, that\'s exactly right. <code>name_1</code> follows every one of Python\'s variable naming rules.</p>\n\n<p>Let\'s quickly walk through why the others fail so the rule sticks:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A) <code>1name</code></strong> starts with a digit. Python needs variable names to begin with a letter or an underscore, so this is a syntax error the moment Python reads it.</li>\n<li><strong>C) <code>name-1</code></strong> contains a hyphen. Python sees the <code>-</code> as the subtraction operator, so it would try to compute <code>name</code> minus <code>1</code> instead of treating the whole thing as one name.</li>\n<li><strong>D) <code>my name</code></strong> has a space. Python uses whitespace to separate tokens, so it reads this as two separate things and gets confused.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The rules to remember:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Letters, digits, and underscores only</li>\n<li>Must not start with a digit</li>\n<li>No spaces or hyphens (use <code>_</code> to separate words, called snake_case)</li>\n<li>Case-sensitive, so <code>Name_1</code> and <code>name_1</code> are two different variables</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A quick mental test: if you can imagine Python confusing the name with math or a keyword, it\'s probably invalid. Underscores are your safe glue between words.</p>', '2026-07-08 09:09:26'),
(958, 1, NULL, 3, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this is a super common mix-up early on. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>bool</strong>, which is Python\'s type for yes/no values. A <code>bool</code> can only ever be one of two things: <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>. Since <code>3.14</code> is a number, not a True/False flag, it doesn\'t fit the <code>bool</code> category.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>float</strong>. Here\'s the reasoning: any number in Python that has a decimal point is treated as a <code>float</code> (short for \"floating-point number\"). Whole numbers like <code>42</code> are <code>int</code>, but the moment you add a decimal, like <code>3.14</code> or even <code>3.0</code>, Python classifies it as a <code>float</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Quick way to double-check yourself in Python:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>A handy mental cheat sheet for the four basic types:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>int</code> → whole numbers like <code>7</code></li>\n<li><code>float</code> → decimals like <code>3.14</code></li>\n<li><code>str</code> → text like <code>\"hello\"</code></li>\n<li><code>bool</code> → only <code>True</code> or <code>False</code></li>\n</ul>', '2026-07-08 09:09:47'),
(959, 19, NULL, 255, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 12, '<p>No worries, this one trips up a lot of beginners. You picked <code>my name</code>, which looks perfectly natural to read, but Python sees that space in the middle and gets confused. It thinks <code>my</code> and <code>name</code> are two separate things, so it raises a <strong>SyntaxError</strong>. Variable names have to be a single unbroken token.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>B) <code>name_1</code></strong>. Here\'s the rule of thumb for naming variables in Python:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Letters, digits, and underscores only</li>\n<li>Cannot start with a digit (so <code>1name</code> is out)</li>\n<li>No spaces (rules out <code>my name</code>)</li>\n<li>No hyphens, because Python reads <code>-</code> as the minus operator (rules out <code>name-1</code>, which Python interprets as <code>name</code> minus <code>1</code>)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The underscore <code>_</code> is your friend here. It\'s the standard way to separate words in a Python variable name, a style called snake_case:</p>\n\n<pre><code>user_age = 21\nfirst_name = \"Aaron\"\nis_logged_in = True</code></pre>\n\n<p>So whenever you\'d naturally want a space, reach for an underscore instead.</p>', '2026-07-08 13:30:59'),
(960, 19, NULL, 256, 'd', NULL, 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this is a really common mix-up when you\'re just getting started. Let\'s untangle it together.</p>\n\n<p>You picked <strong>bool</strong>, which stands for boolean. A boolean can only ever be one of two values: <code>True</code> or <code>False</code>. It represents yes/no or on/off answers, like <code>is_student = True</code>. Since <code>3.14</code> is clearly a number, not a True/False value, <code>bool</code> doesn\'t fit here.</p>\n\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>float</strong>. Here\'s the reasoning:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>A number without a decimal point, like <code>42</code>, is an <code>int</code> (integer, whole numbers only).</li>\n<li>A number with a decimal point, like <code>3.14</code>, is a <code>float</code> (short for \"floating-point number\").</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>That decimal point is the giveaway. The moment Python sees <code>.</code> in a number, it treats the whole value as a float. You can always double-check in Python itself:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))   # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>So the rule of thumb: whole number equals int, decimal number equals float, text in quotes equals str, and True/False equals bool.</p>', '2026-07-08 13:31:09');
INSERT INTO `QUIZ_LEARNING_RECORD_T` (`learning_record_id`, `user_id`, `room_id`, `question_id`, `selected_option`, `text_answer`, `is_correct`, `marks_earned`, `response_time`, `ai_explanation`, `answered_at`) VALUES
(961, 19, NULL, 257, 'b', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>No worries, this is a really common mix-up. You picked <code>list</code>, which is actually one of Python\'s most-used built-in types. A <code>list</code> is how Python stores an ordered collection of values, like <code>[1, 2, 3]</code> or <code>[\"a\", \"b\"]</code>. So it definitely counts as built-in.</p>\n\n<p>The trick answer here is <strong>C) array</strong>. Python does not have a plain <code>array</code> type sitting there ready to use like other languages (say, Java or C) do. If you write:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = array(1, 2, 3)# NameError!</code></pre>\n\n<p>Python has no idea what you mean. There is an <code>array</code> module in the standard library, and libraries like NumPy add their own array type, but you have to import them. That\'s why the course notes warn:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>int</strong>, <strong>float</strong>, <strong>str</strong>, <strong>bool</strong> are the basic built-in scalar types</li>\n<li><strong>list</strong> and <strong>dict</strong> are built-in collection types</li>\n<li><strong>array</strong> is not a general-purpose built-in, use a <code>list</code> instead</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>So the rule of thumb: when you want a \"bunch of values\" in Python, reach for a <code>list</code>, not an array.</p>', '2026-07-08 13:31:19'),
(962, 19, NULL, 258, NULL, 'bvfer', 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one\'s an easy fix once you see it. Your answer <code>bvfer</code> doesn\'t match any Python built-in, so it looks like the keys might have slipped, or the name just wasn\'t fresh in memory yet. That\'s totally fine, this is exactly the kind of thing repetition locks in.</p>\n\n<p>The function you were after is <strong>type()</strong>. It\'s built right into Python, so you can call it anywhere without importing anything. You hand it a value or a variable, and it tells you what kind of thing it is.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s it in action:</p>\n\n<pre><code>x = 3.14\nprint(type(x))        # &lt;class \'float\'&gt;\n\nname = \"Aaron\"\nprint(type(name))     # &lt;class \'str\'&gt;\n\nprint(type(42))       # &lt;class \'int\'&gt;\nprint(type(True))     # &lt;class \'bool\'&gt;</code></pre>\n\n<p>The output<code>&lt;class \'float\'&gt;</code> is Python\'s way of saying the value belongs to the <code>float</code> type. This is super handy when you\'re debugging and something isn\'t behaving the way you expect. A quick <code>print(type(whatever))</code> often reveals that a number is secretly a string, or vice versa.</p>', '2026-07-08 13:31:33'),
(963, 19, NULL, 259, NULL, 'xwqwq', 0, 0, 2, '<p>No worries, this one trips people up because it looks like a trick question. Your answer <code>xwqwq</code> isn\'t a valid Python value at all. If you typed that into Python, it would treat it as a variable name and raise a <code>NameError</code> because nothing has been assigned to it yet.</p>\n\n<p>The value Python uses to represent \"nothing\" or \"no value\" is <strong>None</strong>. It\'s a special built-in constant, and note that the capital <strong>N</strong> matters. <code>none</code> or <code>NONE</code> won\'t work.</p>\n\n<p>You\'ll see <code>None</code> pop up in a few common situations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>As a placeholder when a value hasn\'t been decided yet</li>\n<li>As the automatic return value of a function that doesn\'t use <code>return</code></li>\n<li>To reset a variable to \"empty\" without deleting it</li>\n</ul>\n\n<pre><code>winner = None\nprint(winner)   # None</code></pre>\n\n<p>So think of <code>None</code> as Python\'s way of saying \"there\'s a slot here, but it\'s intentionally empty.\" Very different from <code>0</code> or <code>\"\"</code>, which are actual values, just smallones.</p>', '2026-07-08 13:31:45'),
(964, 19, NULL, 561, 'c', NULL, 0, 0, 1, '<p>Hey, it looks like this question came through blank on my end. I can see you picked C and the correct answer was A, but I don\'t have the actual question text or the options to work with, so I can\'t walk you through the reasoning properly.</p>\n\n<p>Could you paste the question and its four options here? Once I can see what was being asked, I\'ll break down why A fits and what C would have meant instead.</p>\n\n<p>In the meantime, since we\'re in the<strong>Variables & Data Types</strong> chapter, here\'s a quick refresher on the kinds of things that usually show up in these questions:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>The four basic types: <code>int</code>, <code>float</code>, <code>str</code>, <code>bool</code></li>\n<li>How to check a type with <code>type(x)</code></li>\n<li>Naming rules (no leading digits, no hyphens, case-sensitive)</li>\n<li>The special value <code>None</code> for \"no value yet\"</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For example, if you saw <code>x = 3.14</code>, that\'s a <code>float</code>, not an <code>int</code>, because it has a decimal point. Send over the question and we\'ll nail down exactly where things went sideways.</p>', '2026-07-08 13:31:57'),
